Also see tacticalTerrainTypeFromPositionForUnitType and tacticalTerrainFromPositionForUnitType.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: tactical terrain types from a position
label: tactical terrain type from a position
tacticalTerrainTypeFromPosition

comment: This predicate relates a street to another street that is a specified number of "streets over" from the first. (nthStreetOver STREET1 STREET2 N) means that STREET1 and STREET2 run parallel to each other in some GridStreetSystem, and that, for any given perpendicular street XSTREET that intersects both of them, the distance between the two intersections is a distanceInBlocksOfStreet of N blocks along XSTREET. For example, in a typical grid system, 15th Street is five streets over from 10th Street. Of course, 5th Street is also five streets over from 10th Street; so to identify a particular street in a given context using this predicate, it is generally also necessary to specify a direction from STREET1 to STREET2.
label: Nth Street Over
nthStreetOver

comment: A predicate used to state the previous day's closing price of a share of a certain company's Stock (of a certain "class", e.g. common or preferred). (stockPrice_Close STOCK PRICE DATE EXCHANGE) means that PRICE is the price per share for STOCK at the most recent market closing of EXCHANGE prior to DATE. See also stockPrice_Open, stockPrice_Ask and stockPrice_Bid.
label: closing price
stockPrice-Close

comment: The predicate sitConstraints is used to relate the constraints on a particular situation to the type of consequences that will occur if those constraints are NOT met. In `(sitConstraints SIT CONSTR RESULT)', CONSTR is a proposition, expressed as a #$ELSentence-Assertible, which describes a constraint for the Situation SIT. If CONSTR is NOT true in the situation SIT, the outcome is RESULT. For example, if a car engine is running (the situation), and there is no oil in it (the constraint), the result is a DamageOutcome. Depending on the particular OutcomeType indicated by RESULT, additional inferences may be made about how SIT will develop if CONSTR is not satisfied. Possible values for RESULT include, e.g., InjuryOutcome, DamageOutcome, FailureOutcome; see also OutcomeType.
label: Sit Constraints
sitConstraints

comment: (ionizationEnergy ELEMENT N KJ_PER_MOLE) means that the ionization energy for removing the Nth electron from an atom of ELEMENT is the specified amount (normally expressed in kiloJoules per mole).
label: ionization energy
ionizationEnergy

comment: (relatedTermHasUnreviewedAssertions THING-1 THING-2 AGENT TEMPLATE-TYPE) holds just in case THING-2 is related to THING-1 in an appropriate way and has at least one FET viewable assertion in some instance of TEMPLATE-TYPE that hasn't been reviewed by AGENT.
label: Related Term Has Unreviewed Assertions
relatedTermHasUnreviewedAssertions

comment: The predicate denotationRelatedTo_New is used to link English words with concepts indirectly related to their meanings. For instance, both #$Wife-TheWord and #$Husband-TheWord are semantically connected to the predicate wife, but the two words do not denote the same relation. If (denotationRelatedTo_New #$Husband-TheWord CountNoun 0 wife), we know that the word 'husband' somehow relates to wife, but should not be taken to denote it.
label: Denotation Related To New
denotationRelatedTo-New

comment: A sentence of the form (binarySimpleVectorWithDimensions VECTOR DIM-1-VALUE DIM-2-VALUE) states that VECTOR is the BinarySimpleVector whose first dimension has the ScalarPointValue DIM-1-VALUE and whose second dimension has the ScalarPointValue DIM-2-VALUE.
label: Binary Simple Vector With Dimensions
binarySimpleVectorWithDimensions

comment: The ternary predicate (cycProblemLinkID CYC-PROBLEM-LINK CYC-PROBLEM-STORE SUID) relates an instance of CycProblemLink qualified by the containing CYC-PROBLEM-STORE, with its internal ID.
label: Cyc Problem Link ID
cycProblemLinkID

comment: (costBenefitPredForSitTypeInArg PRED SIT-TYPE ROLE ARG-NUM) holds just in case any sentence S of the form (PRED ... COL . ARGS) where a specialization COL of SIT-TYPE appears in the ARG-NUMth place of S is a sentence that expresses a fact worth considering when assessing the costs/benefits of playing ROLE in a TYPE.
label: Cost Benefit Pred For Sit Type In Arg
costBenefitPredForSitTypeInArg

comment: (few_GenQuantRelnTo RELN COL THING) is true if few of the instances X of COL are such that (RELN X THING) holds.
label: Few Gen Quant Reln To
few-GenQuantRelnTo

comment: A sentence of the form (strategyParameterValue STRAT PARAM VALUE) means that the ScoringSoftwareStrategy STRAT contains the Parameter PARAM and that it has assigned PARAM a value of VALUE, some ScalarInterval.
label: Strategy Parameter Value
strategyParameterValue

comment: This is a stub created to be used in determining cost estimates for SKSI removal modules.
label: Kappa Cardinality
kappaCardinality

comment: (analysisTypeVariableConstraints ANALYSIS-TYPE VAR MEANING-SENT) means that VAR is an open or existentially bound CycLVariable in the CycLFormula representing a question asked during events of type ANALYSIS-TYPE, and MEANING-SENT expresses the constraints on VAR. In other words, VAR is a placeholder for something ;whose identity is to be discovered during ANALYSIS-TYPE events, and MEANING-SENT is a CycLExpression representing some conditions that must be met by that thing.
label: Analysis Type Variable Constraints
analysisTypeVariableConstraints

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates two comparable scalar intervals (see comparableScalars) to the (usually proper) interval between and including them. (intervalRange RANGE SCALAR1 SCALAR2) means that RANGE is the interval that ranges from SCALAR1 to SCALAR2 inclusive.

For example, (intervalRange CoolToCold Cold Cool) means that CoolToCold is the Temperature ranging from Cold to Cool. Also, (intervalRange (Unity 1.0 10.0) 1.0 10.0) holds.

For more details, see the corresponding function IntervalRangeFn.
label: Interval Range
intervalRange

comment: (numericFluentReln OBJ1 F1(X) RELN OBJ2 F2(X)) states that F1(OBJ1) RELN F2(OBJ2) is true. Thus, we can say (numericFluentReln UT-ESB-Building lengthOfObject GreaterThan UT-Tower heightOfObject) to state that the UT engineering science building is longer thatn the tower is tall.
label: Numeric Fluent Reln
numericFluentReln

comment: A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly genls based relationship holds between the fourth argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg2ResultGenls FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when a subcollection of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the fourth argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is a subcollection of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is a subcollection of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is a subcollection of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg4ResultGenls _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultGenl.
label: Inter Arg 4 Result Genls
interArg4ResultGenls

comment: (inflationRateDuring GE THING NR) means that NR is the inflation rate of the GeopoliticalEntity GE's economy during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (THING will often be a calendar time period.) That is, NR is the quotient of the difference between the price level in GE's economy at the end of the temporal extent of THING and the price level at the start of the temporal extent of THING (as dividend) and the price level at the start of the temporal extent of THING (as divisor). For example, to express the fact that Oman's inflation rate for 1997 was 1.1%, we can say (inflationRateDuring Oman (YearFn 1997) .011).
label: inflation rate
inflationRateDuring

comment: (objectActsOnObjectInEvent EVENT SOMETHING SOMETHING-ELSE) holds iff SOMETHING-ELSE is a patient_Generic in the Event as a proximal effect of a role played by SOMETHING. The latter's (relevant) role must be a specialization of actors, and might or might not be an instance of BinaryRolePredicate. For example, if it holdsSometimeDuring an event that a Gun launchesProjectile a certain ProjectileShellAssembly, then there ought to be a rule which determines that (objectActsOnObjectInEvent <EVENT> <THE GUN> <THE PSA>) holds as well, and Cyc should further be able to determine that <THE GUN> acts on the parts of <THE PSA>, namely the ProjectileCasing and ProjectileSlug_Bullet which are (originally) physicalParts of it. This predicate is not transitive, in that if the SOMETHING-ELSE acts on some other object, this doesn't mean that SOMETHING acts on it as well, So, in this example, the fact that (objectActsOnObjectInEvent <EVENT> <THE BULLET> <THE OBJECT>) holds for whatever the bullet hits, this is not an argument for (objectActsOnObjectInEvent <EVENT> <THE GUN> <THE OBJECT>) holding as well (of course, its holding coincidentally isn't ruled out, either).
label: Object Acts On Object In Event
objectActsOnObjectInEvent

comment: (verbSemTrans VERB NUM FRAME TRANS) means that the translation of word sense number NUM of VERB, appearing with subcategorization frame FRAME, is TRANS.
label: Verb Sem Trans
verbSemTrans

comment: A SpatialPredicate that relates a pair of GeopoliticalEntitys whose territories share a border to parts of the border that separates them. (formsBorderBetweenPolities BORDER POLITY1 POLITY2) means that BORDER constitutes at least part of the border between the territories of POLITY1 and POLITY2. BORDER is an instance of SpatialThing; it might be a GeopoliticalBorder, a MountainRange, a River, or something else. Note that BORDER need not constitute the entire border between the territories of POLITY1 and POLITY2. See the corresponding function BorderBetweenPolitiesFn for specifying the border between two GeopoliticalEntitys and formsBorderBetween for specifying the border between two GeopoliticalRegions (or other SpatialThings.
label: Forms Border Between Polities
formsBorderBetweenPolities

comment: (onlyTypePlaysRoleInSubSituationType SIT-TYPE ROLE-PLAYER-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE ROLE) means that in an instance of SIT-TYPE, whatever plays the role ROLE in the sub-situation that is the instantiation of SUBSIT-TYPE must be an instance of ROLE-PLAYER-TYPE. Cf. the stronger predicate someAndOnlyTypePlaysRoleInSubSituationType, which requires that in every instance of SUBSIT-TYPE, some instance of ROLE-PLAYER-TYPE plays ROLE.
label: Only Type Plays Role In Sub Situation Type
onlyTypePlaysRoleInSubSituationType

comment: (decreasesImmediately PERIOD THING SLOT) means that the value for the predicate SLOT applied to THING (in the first argument position) is lower immediately after (STIF q.v.) PERIOD than it was immediately before (STIB q.v.) PERIOD. PERIOD may be any instance of TemporalThing, i.e., anything that has a time period associated with it, whether an event, an entity, a life stage, etc. No causal connection is implied between the TemporalThing PERIOD and the decrease. See #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for a map of related predicates.
label: Decreases Immediately
decreasesImmediately

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate that is a specialization of both relationAllExistsMin and relationAllExistsMax (qq.v.). (relationAllExistsCount BINPRED COL1 COL2 N) means that for any instance INST of COL1 there are exactly N instances INST1, ..., INSTn of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST INSTi) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 
  (implies
    (isa ?INST COL1)
    (thereExistExactly N ?INST-I
      (and
        (isa ?INST-I COL2)
        (BINPRED ?INST ?INST-I))))

(wherein the variable ?INST is interpreted as if it were bound by an initial universal quantifier).

For example, (relationAllExistsCount anatomicalParts Dog Leg 4) means that all dogs have four legs.

Cf. relationExistsCountAll, and see the #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation All Exists Count
relationAllExistsCount

comment: (mtsConflict PROP MTPROVE MTDISPROVE) means that PROP is provable in MTPROVE and that (not PROP) is provable in MTDISPROVE.
label: Mts Conflict
mtsConflict

comment: (regionalDialectOfLanguage LANGUAGE REGION DIALECT) means that DIALECT is the LanguageDialect of LANGUAGE indigienous to REGION. For example, (regionalDialectOfLanguage ItalianLanguage (NorthEasternRegionFn Italy) FriulianDialect) means that Friulian is the a dialect of Italian indigenous to northeatern Italy.
label: Regional Dialect Of Language
regionalDialectOfLanguage

comment: (attitudeTowardsObject AGT OBJ QUANT) means that the SentientAnimal AGT has the quantity of feeling described by QUANT (see FeelingAttribute) about the Individual. By `attitude' we mean a possibly latent and/or long-lasting feeling. To refer to feelings that AGT experiences immediately and consciously towards OBJ, use feelsTowardsObject_Ternary.
label: Attitude Towards Object
attitudeTowardsObject

comment: The corresponding predicate to QuantifiedBinaryPredicateFn
label: Quantified Binary Predicate For Pred With Macro
quantifiedBinaryPredicateForPredWithMacro

comment: (goalImportance AGT G DEGREE) means that the IntelligentAgent AGT has the Goal G, and G has the degree of importance DEGREE for AGT.
label: Goal Importance
goalImportance

comment: (atomicComposition CHEM ELEM N) means that molecules of CHEM contain N atoms of ELEM. For instance, (atomicComposition Water Hydrogen 2) means that every molecule of water contains two atoms of hydrogen. See completeAtomicComposition_List to express the chemical formula for a ChemicalSubstanceType.
label: atomic composition
atomicComposition

comment: The predicate titleOfPersonInOrganization relates a person to a title that s/he holds in an organization. (titleOfPersonInOrganization PER TITLE ORG) means that the Person PER has the Title TITLE in the Organization ORG.
label: Title Of Person In Organization
titleOfPersonInOrganization

comment: (compositionFeaturesSoloistTypeCount COMP TYPE INT) means that the MusicalComposition COMP features INT solists of type TYPE. For instance, (compositionFeaturesSoloistTypeCount BachDoubleViolinConcerto (PlayerOfInstrumentFn Violin) 2) means that the Bach double violin concerto features two violin soloists.
label: Composition Features Soloist Type Count
compositionFeaturesSoloistTypeCount

comment:
A ternary MetaFunction predicate that relates two interconvertible UnitOfMeasures (q.v.) to the real number by which the larger unit is a multiple of the smaller. (unitMultiplicationFactor SMALLUNIT BIGUNIT N) means that there are N SMALLUNITs in one BIGUNIT. In other words, to convert from a measure BIGUNITs to a measure in SMALLUNITs, multiply by N.

For example, (unitMultiplicationFactor Inch Foot_UnitOfMeasure 12) entails that, when converting from feet to inches, one multiplies the number of feet by twelve.

Note that SMALLUNIT and BIGUNIT must be instances of the same InterconvertibleUnitType (q.v.), and that N must be greater than or equal to 1.

See also QuantityConversionFn.
label: Unit Multiplication Factor
unitMultiplicationFactor

comment: An instance of RuleMacroPredicate. (relationInstanceExistsAndOnly PRED THING-1 TYPE-2) says that there exists a thing THING-2 such that (PRED THING-1 THING-2) where the fact that (PRED THING-1 THING-2) guarantees that (isa THING-2 TYPE-2) and that there is at least one THING-2 such that (PRED THING-1 THING-2).
label: Relation Instance Exists And Only
relationInstanceExistsAndOnly

comment: (loggedInAsOn AGENT ACCOUNT COMPUTER) means that AGENT is logged on to COMPUTER as ACCOUNT. Note that AGENT might be logged into a computer under a certain account but not knowsLoginInformationForAccount.
label: Logged In As On
loggedInAsOn

comment: (synonymousExternalConceptWRTPredicate THING SOURCE PRED STRING) means that when THING stands in the relation PRED to any other thing, the string STRING (when it occurs in the data source SOURCE) denotes THING.
label: Synonymous External Concept WRT Predicate
synonymousExternalConceptWRTPredicate

comment: (lifeSpanType_1 s col o ti) means that as a default, if an instance of col is on the slot s of the object o, the temporal projection time of this proposition is ti
label: Life Span Type 1
lifeSpanType-1

comment:
An ExistentialQuantifier (q.v.) and a specialized (albeit higher arity) version of thereExists (q.v.). Compared to the latter, standard existential quantifier, thereExistAtLeast has an extra argument-place for specifying how many things (at the least) satisfy a given condition (specified by an #$ELSentence-Assertible, in which the also-specified #$ELVariable will typically occur free). A closed sentence of the form (thereExistAtLeast NUM VAR SENT) means that there are at least NUM distinct things that satisfy SENT, i.e. that render SENT true when taken as the value of VAR. For example, the sentence 

  (thereExistAtLeast 7 ?X (isa ?X Sea))

means that there are at least seven seas.

In the degenerate case where VAR does not appear free in SENT, then (thereExistAtLeast NUM VAR SENT) is equivalent to SENT.

See also thereExistAtMost, thereExistExactly.
label: There Exist At Least
thereExistAtLeast
Non Assertible Term
nonAssertibleTerm
comment: A MetaPredicate for stating a certain restriction regarding the use of a given term in assertions to the Cyc Knowledge Base. (nonAssertibleTerm TERM) means that a certain class of ground atomic formulas (or "GAFs"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence) containing this term should not be asserted into the KB. This condition is hard to precisely define, but the idea is that the term can appear in GAFs that say things about TERM -- that TERM is an instance of certain collections or believed by some cyclist to be someone's favorite term. But, there is a certain class of assertions in which it should never appear. For instance sentenceTruth is a nonAssertibleTerm in that it can't appear in arg0 of GAFs, but, of course, it can appear in arg1 of (notAssertible sentenceTruth). ELRelation should have no direct instances, so (notAssertibleCollection ELRelation) holds. But, of course, that term can appear in other GAFs (genls assertions for example). AnytimePSC should not appear as the time dimension in any assertion in the KB. But, it can appear in asserted GAFs where it does not appear in some argument position of an MtSpace NAUT. This is basically a documentation predicate. See the two specializations of this predicate, notAssertible and notAssertibleCollection, which constrain predicates and collections, respectively and which can be given precise definitions.
(standardConcerns STAND SCRIPT ASLOT) states that the standard STAND concerns the things which show up on the ASLOT of instances of SCRIPT
label: Standard Concerns
standardConcerns

comment: (combatForceAvailableToAgentForEvent AGENT EVENT N) means that N is the estimated value of the combat force of the units available to agent for carrying out EVENT. The combat force value is generally relative to some military unit which is given the value of 1. Thus, a value of .8, for instance, would mean that the unit, or units, assigned to carry out EVENT have a combat force value (see <font color="#ff0000">#$combatForceValueOfUnit</font>) of .8 relative to the unit designated as the standard.
label: Combat Force Available To Agent For Event
combatForceAvailableToAgentForEvent

comment: (populationLevelOfTypeInEcosystem ORG-TYPE ECOSYSTEM NUMBER) means that the number of instances of ORG-TYPE currently functioning as components in ECOSYSTEM (componentInSystem_FunctionalRole) is NUMBER.
label: ecosystem population level
populationLevelOfTypeInEcosystem

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate holds between a specified thing and some instance of a given collection. (relationInstanceExists PRED THING COL) means that there exists an instance INST of COL such that (PRED THING INST) holds. It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 

     (thereExists ?INST
          (and
               (isa ?INST COL)
               (PRED THING ?INST))) .

For example, '(relationInstanceExists geographicalSubRegions Iran OilField)' means that there exists an oilfield in Iran. Cf. relationExistsInstance, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Instance Exists
relationInstanceExists

comment: (hueInRange BETWEEN-HUE HUE-1 HUE-2) means that BETWEEN-HUE is a MunsellHue with a value somewhere between HUE-1 and HUE-2 on the Munsell scale of hue. Munsell hues are represented using group of functions that return instances of instances of MunsellHue. For further information, please see MunsellHue, and the #$SharedNoteOnMunsellSystemOfColorClassification.
label: Hue In Range
hueInRange

comment: A ternary SpaceRegionPredicate that holds among certain straight lines (see Line_Straight). (copunctualLines LINE1 LINE2 LINE3) is true if and only if LINE1, LINE2, and LINE3 all intersect at a common Point.
label: Copunctual Lines
copunctualLines

comment:
(cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree_Numeric Q-SPEC DEGREE) means that Q-SPEC is an instance of CycLQuerySpecification that is, to the degree of relevance DEGREE, pertinent to an instance of information gathering, due to the pertinence of the terms in SET).

This predicate is similar in meaning to cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree (q.v.). Whereas, however, cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree takes an instance of Relevance as an argument in the second argument position, cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree_Numeric takes a number in the range of 0 to 1.

(cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree_Numeric Q-SPEC 0) means that Q-SPEC has no relevance (i.e. it is equivalent to (cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree_Numeric Q-SPEC (NoAmountFn Relevance)).

NOTE: This predicate should only be used in microtheories which specify the appropriate qualifications of assertions made with it: e.g., for whom the query is pertinent, on what task, at what time and place, etc.
label: Cyc L Query Specification Pertinent To Degree Numeric
cycLQuerySpecificationPertinentToDegree-Numeric

comment:
A MetaRelation predicate used for stating that the result returned by a given function always stands in a specified Relation to a certain one of its arguments. (interResultArgReln FUNC N RELN) means that the result of applying FUNC to any admitted sequence of arguments ARGS stands in RELN to the Nth item (ARGN) of ARGS. Stated schematically: if (FUNC . ARGS) = RESULT, then (RELN RESULT ARGN) holds. For example, 
  (interResultArgReln #$SubPathInsideRegionFn 2 pathInsideRegion)
means that the result of applying #$SubPathInsideRegionFn to a given PATH and REGION is itself a path that is wholly inside of REGION.

See also interArgResultReln.
label: Inter Result Arg Reln
interResultArgReln
Use Reformulation Rule With Salient Descriptor
useReformulationRuleWithSalientDescriptor
comment:
Use this predicate to tag reformulator rules that are to be used
 immediately after the SME responds to a salient descriptor suggestion, and prior to 
wff-checking the SME's resultant assertion.

easierThan(AGENT Y_ACTIONS Z_ACTIONS) means that it is (mentally, physically) easier for AGENT to perform an action of type Y_ACTIONS than to perform an action of type Z_ACTIONS. This is different from moreConvenientThan. In performing any event, there are often other things that need to be done - getting the tools, cleaning up the place, travelling.... Convenience seems to be a measure of the ease of these other subsidiary actions. The concept of ease is more general and applies to the whole event. So, for most people, eating spaghetti is easier than solving quadratics, but solving quadratics might be more convenient (if you are given a piece of paper and a pencil, but have to go buy the spaghetti, etc.).
label: Easier Than
easierThan

comment: A quaternary spatial predicate that relates adjacent edges of an object to the measure of the angle they form at their common endpoint, as measured from the interior of the object. (angleBetweenEdgesOfObject EDGE1 EDGE2 DEGREES OBJ) means that EDGE1 and EDGE2 form an angle that measures DEGREES within OBJ.
label: Angle Between Edges Of Object
angleBetweenEdgesOfObject

comment: (lawContributesToSlotValue LAW SLOT THING SIT) means that the law of nature, LAW, applies to the thing THING in the situation SIT, and partially determines the value of SLOT applied to THING in SIT.
label: Law Contributes To Slot Value
lawContributesToSlotValue

comment: A predicate used to encode constraints on a class of situations licensed by an instance of Entitlement. (entitlementRolePlayerConstraints ENTITLEMENT ROLE PRED THING) means that if ENTITLEMENT is an entitlement that licenses the bringing about of some situation SIT, anything that plays the role ROLE in SIT will bear the relationship PRED to THING. Otherwise, SIT is not licensed by ENTITLEMENT.
label: Entitlement Role Player Constraints
entitlementRolePlayerConstraints

comment: '(uniquePartOfType WHOLE PART-TYPE PART)' means that PART is the one and only part of WHOLE of type PART-TYPE.
label: Unique Part Of Type
uniquePartOfType

comment: (specPredsRelevantToTermSummaryPredWRTSpecsInArg PRED TERM-SUMMARY-PRED TYPE N) means that if a thing THING is a specialization of TYPE, then any assertions in which a specialization of PRED occurs in arg 0 and THING occurs as arg N should appear in the fact sheet for THING under the category associated with TERM-SUMMARY-PRED.
label: Spec Preds Relevant To Term Summary Pred WRT Specs In Arg
specPredsRelevantToTermSummaryPredWRTSpecsInArg

comment: (playsRoleInSitTypeEnsuresRelnToA ROLE SIT-TYPE AGENT COL RELN) means that when AGENT plays the role ROLE in an instance of SIT-TYPE, the upshot is that AGENT comes to bear the relation RELN (expressed by a BinaryPredicate) to an instance of COL.
label: Plays Role In Sit Type Ensures Reln To A
playsRoleInSitTypeEnsuresRelnToA

comment: (totalInventoryInRegion REGION TYPE AMOUNT) means that total quantity of TYPE that exists in inventories in REGION is AMOUNT. Such inventory levels are sensitive to, and thus often treated as indicators of, the ratio between supply and demand for TYPE.
label: total inventory
totalInventoryInRegion

comment: The Common Lisp format string ARG3 can be applied to the argument list ARG4 to generate a question for the Cyc Relation ARG1 when all the arguments are filled except the argument indicated by ARG2. For example, when applied to (movieActors DieHard_TheMovie :WHO) it can generate the question 'Who acted in Die Hard?'
label: Gen Question
genQuestion

comment:
A MetaRelation predicate for stating that the type-constraints on two specified argument-places of a given Relation are mutually compatible. (cosatisfiableInArgs RELN M N) means that there could be a particular thing that is admissible as an argument (see admittedArgument) to RELN both in its Mth and its Nth argument-places. More precisely: the (single-argument) argument-type constraints (see argIsa and argGenls) on RELN's Mth and Nth argument-places do not preclude the possibility of there being some THING such that both (admittedArgument THING M RELN) and (admittedArgument THING N RELN) hold. (Note that this by itself does not entail that such a THING actually exists -- though typically that will be the case -- but only that the existence of such a thing is logically compatible with the argument-constraints on RELN.)

Also note that (cosatisfiableInArgs RELN M N) is not incompatible with (interArgDifferent RELN M N). The latter sentence is not about argument-constraints but about truth-conditions, and means that RELN does not hold of any sequence whose Mth and Nth items are identical. For example, (cosatisfiableInArgs biologicalMother 1 2) and (interArgDifferent biologicalMother 1 2) both hold: a given animal might both have a mother and be a mother, but cannot be its own mother.

See also the shared #$NoteOnArgumentCosatisfiabilityRequirement.
label: Cosatisfiable In Args
cosatisfiableInArgs

comment: (tradeBalanceDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE THING MONEY) means that the instance of MonetaryValue MONEY is a measure of the difference between the value of the instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE exported by the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING and the value of the instances of PRODUCT-TYPE imported by REGION during the temporal extent of THING. (THING will often be a calendar time period.) Thus if the value of REGION's exports of PRODUCT-TYPE is greater than the value of its imports of PRODUCT-TYPE during the temporal extent of THING, REGION will have a positive trade balance. If the value of its imports of PRODUCT-TYPE exceeds that of its exports, it will have a negative trade balance. This latter case can be expressed using a UnitOfMoney function with a negative number as its argument. A region's overall trade balance for all goods and services (over a given time period) can be expressed with this predicate using the constant Product as the second argument.
label: Trade Balance During
tradeBalanceDuring

comment:
An instance of both ArgCardinalityPredicate and InterArgConstraintPredicate (qq.v.) that can be used to put a conditional argument-cardinality constraint on a specified argument-place of a predicate, dependent upon the type of thing occupying that or another specified argument-place.

(interArgCardinality PRED M COL N CARD) means that when PRED's Mth argument is an instance of COL then its Nth argument is constrained to a cardinality of CARD. Thus for any particular way of fixing the other arguments to PRED besides the Nth, if the Mth argument is an instance of COL, then there are at most CARD distinct things such that, if any one of them is taken as the _Nth_ argument while keeping the other arguments as already fixed (and keeping the Mth argument an instance of COL if N = M), PRED holds of those arguments. That is (assuming without loss of generality that M > N), there are at most CARD distinct sequences of the form <... ARGM ... ARGN(i) ...> with an Mth member (ARGM) that is an instance of COL and that differ from one another _only_ in their Nth members (their respective ARGN(i)) and are such that (PRED ... ARGM ... ARGN(i) ...) holds.

For example, (interArgCardinality performedBy 1 Breathing 2 1) means that for any event BREATH that is a Breathing, there is at most one thing BREATHER such that (performedBy BREATH BREATHER) holds. Simply put, an act of breathing is never performed by more than one agent.

As in the case of the unconditional constraint predicate argCardinality (q.v.), most interArgCardinality sentences asserted to the Knowledge Base are such that CARD is 1. For more discussion on argument-cardinality constraints in general, see the comment on argCardinality. See also assertedArgCardinality, and intraArgReln.
label: Inter Arg Cardinality
interArgCardinality

comment: The corresponding predicate (functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical) of MarketForCommodityTypeInPolityFn.
label: Market For Commodity Type In Polity
marketForCommodityTypeInPolity

comment: (slotValueSum SLOT THING SETORCOL) says that the value of SLOT for THING can be computed by summing the values of SLOT over the elements of SETORCOL. For instance, world population is equivalent to the sum of population over every country: (slotValueSum numberOfInhabitants PlanetEarth Country). See also PlusAll: the value of SLOT for THING is the value of (PlusAll SETORCOL (FunctionToArg 2 SLOT)).
label: Slot Value Sum
slotValueSum

comment: (nodeOfTypeInLAN COMPUTER COMPUTERTYPE LAN) means that COMPUTER is one of the computers that constitutes the LocalAreaNetwork LAN, and COMPUTER plays the role of COMPUTERTYPE in LAN. For instance, (nodeOfTypeInLAN Router001 Router_Network #$CycorpLAN) means that Router001 is a network router on the Cycorp LAN. See also the more specialized nodeOfTypeInAccountSystem.
label: Node Of Type In LAN
nodeOfTypeInLAN

comment:
A fully functional ternary predicate relating a physical schema, physical field, and a string. (physicalSchemaFieldWithName SCHEMA FIELD NAME) means that:

1. FIELD is a physical field of SCHEMA (See physicalFields);

2. FIELD is named NAME (See fieldName_SKS);

See also the function corresponding to the second argument of this predicate, PhysicalFieldFn.
label: Physical Schema Field With Name
physicalSchemaFieldWithName

comment: (assistedReaderSourceSpindleForTaskAndUser TASK USER SPINDLE) means that SPINDLE is the MicrotheorySpindle designed to hold source microtheories whose contents are authored using the CycAssistedDocumentReader by USER while working on TASK.
label: Assisted Reader Source Spindle For Task And User
assistedReaderSourceSpindleForTaskAndUser

comment: (goalCategoryForAgent AGT CYCFORMULA GOALCAT) means that the CYCFORMULA is a goal for AGT of GOALCAT. Each GOALCAT is a collection of goals in a particular category, such as ForeignPolicyGoal, LifePreservationGoal, etc. They specify what type of goal GOAL is for the agent.
label: Goal Category For Agent
goalCategoryForAgent

comment: (valveRegurgitationSeverity EVENT VALVE VALVE-TYPE SEVERITY) means that according to the information on VALVE, a cardiac valve of VALVE-TYPE, that is associated with EVENT (an instance of CardiacCatheterization or Echocardiogram) the focal valve has the regurgitation severity SEVERITY.
label: valve regurgitation
valveRegurgitationSeverity

comment: (tourMealsTotal TOUR MEALTYPE N) means that TOUR provides a total of N meals of type MEALTYPE for the tour participants, these having already been paid for in advance by the participants as part of the tour package.
label: Tour Meals Total
tourMealsTotal

comment: The predicate toneOfInformationThing is used to characterize the evaluation made or implied by a particular assertion about something. (toneOfInformationThing PROP THING TONE) means that the proposition expressed in the #$ELSentence-Assertible PROP explicitly or implicitly makes an evaluation of THING that has the AISTypeByEvaluationTone TONE. Some possible values of TONE are: PositiveTone, NegativeTone, NeutralTone. For example, a Cyc formula stating that Socrates feels Courageousness_Feeling in the face of his execution can be said to be positive in tone about Socrates. (Such a formula would utilize feelsTowardsEvent.)
label: Tone Of Information Thing
toneOfInformationThing

comment: (correspondingDomainInArg QUERY-COLL DOMAIN-COLL ARG-NUM) holds just in case the normal domain for instances of QUERY-COLL in ARG-NUM is DOMAIN-COLL. QUERY-COLL is restricted to collections of single literal queries.
label: Corresponding Domain In Arg
correspondingDomainInArg
Term Needs Better Lexification
termNeedsBetterLexification
comment: (termNeedsBetterLexification TERM) states that TERM is poorly lexified and that its lexification should be improved.

An expression of the form (userOfProgramUsingProgram USER-OF-PROGRAM PROGRAM USER) states that 'USER-OF-PROGRAM' denotes USER while USER is using program. This is the corresponding predicate of the function UserOfProgramFn.
label: User Of Program Using Program
userOfProgramUsingProgram
Seats Won In Elections
seatsWonInElections
comment: (seatsWonInElections ELECTIONS PARTY NUM) means that in the group of elections (e.g., to some legislative body) designated by ELECTIONS, PARTY wins/won/has won NUM seats.
(solubilityOfSampleInSubst SOLUTE SOLVENT DEGREE) means that the PartiallyTangible individual SOLUTE can dissolve in the substance type SOLVENT with this qualitative DEGREE of Solubility (q.v.).
label: Solubility Of Sample In Subst
solubilityOfSampleInSubst

comment: (extendAnalogyMatch OLD CONSTRAINTS NEW) extends the match OLD, based on changes in base and target, if any, and under CONSTRAINTS. The result is denoted via NEW.
label: Extend Analogy Match
extendAnalogyMatch

comment:
(nearestGenlsOfType COL TYPE-COL NEAR-COL) means that NEAR-COL is a "nearest" generalization of COL which is of type TYPE-COL. More precisely: (i) (genls COL NEAR-COL) holds, (ii) COL is not identical to NEAR-COL, (iii) (isa NEAR-COL TYPE-COL), and (iv) there is no reified Collection NEARER-COL distinct from COL and NEAR-COL such that (genls COL NEARER-COL), (genls NEARER-COL NEAR-COL), and (isa NEARER-COL TYPE-COL) hold.

Note that nearestGenlsOfType is non-assertible (see notAssertible), since its extension at any given time depends upon (and so must be recomputed from) the current state of the Cyc Knowledge Base.
label: Nearest Genls Of Type
nearestGenlsOfType

comment: (taskConceptForUser CONCEPT USER TASK) holds just in case CONCEPT is pertinent to USER working on TASK. This is basically a dexcontextualized version of conceptPertinentToDegree with the degree argument existentially generalized.
label: Task Concept For User
taskConceptForUser

comment: The value of all the units of product ARG1 sold during time interval ARG2 is ARG3
label: Amount Of Sales During
amountOfSalesDuring

comment: A binary predicate that relates Algorithms (q.v.) to their outputs for given inputs. (algorithmOutputFor ALGORITHM INPUT OUTPUT) means that ALGORITHM, when applied to INPUT, produces OUTPUT as its final result. Note that ALGORITHM might not produce a final output for every allowable input (see algorithmInputs).
label: Algorithm Output For
algorithmOutputFor

comment: (quantityInfluenceFunction TIME THING QUANTITY-SLOT FUNCTION-TYPE) means that during TIME the value of QUANTITY-SLOT for successive time slices of THING is subjected to some influence. If that influence were to be expressed, e.g. in the absence of other influences, then the shape of that function would be one characteristic of elements of FUNCTION-TYPE. Unlike quantityChangeFunction, quantityInfluenceFunction does not necessarily entail a change in the value of QUANTITY-SLOT for THING. It can be used to directly infer quantityChangeFunction in the absence of other influences. If other influences are present, the relative strengths of each influence along with the direction of each influence can be summed to infer a final quantityChangeFunction. See also quantityInfluenceFunctionStrength.
label: Quantity Influence Function
quantityInfluenceFunction

comment:
A unary MetaLanguagePredicate (q.v.) that holds of a certain kind of CycLTerm that, via its internal structure, specifies its denotatum -- which will either be a set or a list (ordered n-tuple) -- by enumerating the items that constitute it.

(specifiesSetOrListByEnumeration NAT) means that there is some SETORLIST such that NAT denotes (see denotes) SETORLIST, and does so in virtue of having constituent terms that serve to enumerate the items that belong to SETORLIST. These constituent terms supply the arguments to a function (denoted by NAT's arg0 operator) that returns the value SETORLIST (a particular Set_Mathematical or List) for those arguments. The function in question might be TheSet, TheList, TheCovering, or ThePartition.

For example, the sentence

(specifiesSetOrListByEnumeration (Quote (ThePartition BaleenWhale ToothedWhale)))

is true because the CycL term "(ThePartition BaleenWhale ToothedWhale)" specifies, by enumeration, the set whose members are the two collections BaleenWhale and ToothedWhale.

Note that the predicate's argument-place is not a quotedArgument (q.v.), so the arg1 position of a specifiesSetOrListByEnumeration sentence will typically be filled by an explicitly quoted expression. Thus the use of Quote (q.v.) in the above example is crucial; without it the arg1 would be a partition-set instead of a CycL term, in violation of the predicate's argument-constraint.
label: Specifies Set Or List By Enumeration
specifiesSetOrListByEnumeration

comment: (budgetExpenditureFractionOfGDP GE COL THING NR) means that NR is the quotient of the amount of money spent by the GeopoliticalEntity GE on instances of the specialization of SpatialThing_Localized COL during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING (as dividend) and the monetary value of GE's total domestic production of goods and services (its gross domestic product) during the temporal extent of THING (as divisor). A country would be a typical instance of GE. COL might be any type of thing on or for which budget expenditures are made; for example, goods, services, institutions (such as government agencies or military organizations), or debt service. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that Oman's 1996 expenditure on the military was 13.7% of its gross domestic product for that year, we can say (budgetExpenditureFractionOfGDP Oman GovernmentMilitaryOrganization (YearFn 1996) (Percent 13.7)). See also budgetExpenditures and grossDomesticProduct.
label: Budget Expenditure Fraction Of GDP
budgetExpenditureFractionOfGDP

comment: An expression of the form (genlsLinkedArgGenls PRED1 ARG1 PRED2 ARG2 COLLECTION) means that either (1) the collection that is the argGenl value for the Predicate PRED1's ARG1th argument is a sub-collection of the collection is the argGenl value for the Predicate PRED2's ARG2th value or (2) the collection that is the argGenl value for the Predicate PRED2's ARG2th argument is a sub-collection ofthe collection is the argGenl value for the Predicate PRED1's ARG1th value. Further, the COLLECTION is one of those arguments' constraining collection and, so, is a common sub-collection of both argument's constraining collections.
label: Genls Linked Arg Genls
genlsLinkedArgGenls

comment: (proposedAgreementSlotForAgent PROPOSAL SLOT AGENT) means that if AGREEMENT is the instance of Agreement that results from the instance PROPOSAL of Proposal, then AGENT will stand in the SLOT relation to AGREEMENT.
label: Proposed Agreement Slot For Agent
proposedAgreementSlotForAgent
True Sub L
trueSubL
comment: (trueSubL SUBL) states that the SubL expression SUBL evaluates to a value other than NIL. This predicate allows for a procedural test for programmatic 'truth' in the implementation language to be reflected as a CycL test for logical truth in the logical language. For example, (trueSubL (ExpandSubLFn () (integerp 42))) states that the SubL expression (integerp 42) evaluates to something other than NIL. See ExpandSubLFn for a way to denote SubL within CycL. See also evaluate and EvaluateSubLFn, and performSubL.
(agentTypeGivesSupportToAgentOfCategory GIVER-TYPE RECEIVER CATEGORY) means that there exists at least instance GIVER of GIVER-TYPE such that (givesSupportToAgent GIVER RECEIVER CATEGORY).
label: Agent Type Gives Support To Agent Of Category
agentTypeGivesSupportToAgentOfCategory

comment: (operatingIncomeForPeriod ORG MONEY TIME) means MONEY is the operating income (EBIT) of ORG during TIME.
label: Operating Income For Period
operatingIncomeForPeriod
Tactical Area From GIS
tacticalArea-FromGIS
comment: (tacticalArea_FromGIS TAREA) means that TAREA is an instance of TacticalArea, according to some GeographicInformationSystem to which Cyc has access.
if (spatiallyHoldsOver OBJ REG-TYPE SLOT ATT) is true, this means that if the OBJ has a part which is an instance of REG-TYPE, that part has SLOT with value ATT.
label: Spatially Holds Over
spatiallyHoldsOver

comment:
(predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg PREDICATE POS-1 N POS-2 M) means that PREDICATE, an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, licenses the extension of the sense of some word that denotes arguments appearing in its Nth place to arguments appearing in its Mth place. For example, 
(predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromArgToArg woodTypeOfPlantType CountNoun 1 MassNoun 2)
means that for WOOD-TYPE and PLANT-TYPE such that 
(woodTypeOfPlantType PLANT-TYPE WOOD-TYPE),
there is likely to be some word(s) that, as a count noun, denotes PLANT-TYPE whose sense can be extended to also denote WOOD-TYPE with a mass noun. For example, there is a count-noun sense of the word "redwood" (see #$Redwood-TheWord) that denotes the tree (c.f., RedwoodTree); that the collection of such trees bears the woodTypeOfPlantType relation to the collection of samples of wood from such trees, licenses a mass-noun sense extension of "redwood" to denote that second collection.

comment: (denotationTemplate WORD POS TEMPLATE) says that TEMPLATE captures the meaning of one of the senses of WORD with part of speech POS. denotationTemplate is used in conjunction with denotesArgInReln to provide denotations for words whose meaning is best expressed in CycL using relations. For example, sentences in which the word "mother" occurs as a count noun (e.g., "everyone has a mother") are best expressed in CycL using the relation mother (e.g., (relationAllExists mother Person FemaleAnimal)). However, since mother is an inappropriate denotation for #$Mother-TheWord, instead of asserting (#$denotation-New #$Mother-TheWord CountNoun mother), we infer from (denotesArgInReln #$Mother-TheWord CountNoun 2 mother) that the meaning of the CountNoun form of #$Mother-TheWord is best expressed through a template: (SubcollectionOfWithRelationToTypeFn FemaleAnimal mother Animal). Thus the assertion, (denotationTemplate #$Mother-TheWord CountNoun (SubcollectionOfWithRelationToTypeFn FemaleAnimal mother Animal)) allows us to parse "mother" NPs and NBars into this template, without requiring us to add unnecessary collections to the KB.
label: Denotation Template
denotationTemplate

comment: This predicate is used to construct 'non-Davidsonian' representations of actions and events, which are of the form WALKS(Mary, Marys-Home). In the usual 'Davidsonian' style, this would be expressed as 'there is an event X such that X is a Walking_Generic, etc.'. Notice that, unlike its Davidsonian counterpart, it makes sense to say that WALKS(Mary, Marys-Home) is true at some times -- namely when Mary *is walking* home -- but not at others -- e.g., after she has arrived. The problem is that we don't have such predicates as WALKS in Cyc. eventPred is intended to fill this gap in a general and simple way, and without introducing a lot of redundant duplication. Suppose EVTYPE is a subcollection of Event, LIST1 is a n-ary list of the form SLOT01 ... SLOT0n, where each element is an instance of ActorSlot, and LIST2 is a n-ary list of things satisfying the arg2Isa constraint on their respective actor slot. Then (eventPred EVTYPE LIST1 LIST2) is true at a time t iff t if the 1st element of LIST2 is playing role SLOT01 in an event of type EVTYPE, the 2nd element of LIST2 is playing role SLOT02, and so on. Consider the example above: we can form (eventPred Walking_Generic (TheList performedBy toLocation) (TheList MARY HOME)) to represent the clause WALKS(Mary, Home) as described in the example. The meaning of this #$ELSentence-Assertible is expressed by the sentence 'Mary is walking home'.
label: Event Pred
eventPred

predHoldsBetweenRolePlayersOfType-SubSitTypeToSubSitType

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa4_2 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the fourth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the second argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 INDEPENDENT-ARG ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG2 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.

comment:
A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate (q.v.) that applies to predicates. (completeExtentDecidable PRED) means that the CycInferenceEngine can determine if any given sequence of things is in the extent of PRED (see relationExtension and relationHoldsAmong). More precisely: for any given n-length sequence SEQ among which PRED holds (and for nothing else), there are CycL terms TERM1, ..., TERMN that denote the respective items in SEQ such that (without using transformations) the Inference Engine, given a query of the form (PRED TERM1 ... TERMN), will return the answer True.

For example, (completeExtentDecidable integerBetween) holds, as the Inference engine can correctly determine if any given triple of integers is such that the second member is numerically between the first and third. Conversely, the extent of likesAsFriend is not decidable, as many of the friendships in the world are beyond Cyc's ken.

If PRED's extent is completely decidable and there are CycL terms TERM1, ..., TERMN such that the sentence (PRED TERM1 ... TERMN) is semantically well-formed but not provable by the Inference Engine, that fact consitutes a strong argument for the truth of its negation (not (PRED TERM1 ... TERM1)). But note that it is not a conclusive argument: the normally-reliable "unique name assumption" might fail here, and some TERMI could conceivably denote something that Cyc can prove to be a member of a sequence in the extent of PRED only under some other CycL name it has. For suppose #$Pace's favorite number happens to be 3, but nobody has told that to Cyc. Cyc can prove the sentence (integerBetween 1 2 3); but it might nevertheless fail to prove the equally true sentence 

  (integerBetween 1 2 (FavoriteNumberOfFn #$Pace)) .
See also the more specific predicates completeExtentEnumerable and completeExtentAsserted. And see completelyDecidableCollection.
label: Complete Extent Decidable
completeExtentDecidable

comment: (actsInCapacityAsMember AGENT OCCUPATION-TYPE ORGANIZATION) holds just in case AGENT is a member of ORGANIZATION and works as OCCUPATION-TYPE for ORGANIZATION. For instance, asserting the conjunction of (isa AGENT ComputerScientist) and (employees ORGANIZATION AGENT) isn't sufficient to represent the situation where AGENT works as a computer scientist in ORGANIZATION -- the mere conjunction is consistent with the fact that AGENT is a computer scientist somewhere else and moonlights as a janitor for ORGANIZATION.
label: Acts In Capacity As Member
actsInCapacityAsMember

(uniquelyBehaviorCapable OBJ SIT-TYPE ROLE) does not imply that OBJ actually can play ROLE in every instance of SIT-TYPE -- it means only that if anything can play such a role, only OBJ can do so. comment: The predicate harmfulActions is used to indicate that an agent engaged in a particular effort would (normally) diminish the chances of success in that effort by taking a certain role in events of a certain kind. (harmfulActions ENDEAVOR SIT-TYPE ROLE DEGREE) means that the PurposefulAction ENDEAVOR would (normally) be hindered if its agent participated as described by ROLE in a situation of the type SIT-TYPE. DEGREE is an instance of GenericQuantity used to give an estimate of how damaging such an occurrence would be to the success of ENDEAVOR. For example, for an agent trying to win in a football game, fumbling the ball disadvantages the agent to a highToVeryHighAmountOf degree.

comment: commandTemplate_Reln relates English sentences meant as commands to the Cyc system to CycL. Unlike commandTemplate, commandTemplate_Reln has a slot for the Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation. For example, (commandTemplate_Reln STemplate CycConceptCreator ("I" "want" "to" "create" "a" "concept" "called" (StringTemplate :NEW)) (NLRequestFn StartTool-NLRequest CycConceptCreator (:NEW))) would map "I want to create a concept called Muffet" to (NLRequestFn StartTool-NLRequest CycConceptCreator ("Muffet")).

commandTemplate-Reln

comment: An assertion of the form sitPartiallySatisfiesSpecificationForAgents SIT SPEC AGENT) is used to represent the fact that a particular Situation SIT partially satisfies the NormativeSpecification SPEC for the Agent_Generic AGENT. A NormativeSpecification describes a type of Situation that an agent has some interest in either bringing about, maintaining, or preventing,. For example, let us say that SPEC has the specification that AGENT's business competitors COMP1 and COMP2 die, then if SIT is the death of COMP1, then SIT would bear the relation sitPartiallySatisfiesSpecificationForAgents to SPEC and AGENT. More generally, this predicate serves as a way of relating an situation to a NormativeSpecification when the situation bears the relation sitSatisfiesSpecificationForAgents to some other NormativeSpecification to which the first NormativeSpecification bears the relation subSpecification This predicate implies that AGENT is aware of SIT.
label: Sit Partially Satisfies Specification For Agents
sitPartiallySatisfiesSpecificationForAgents

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.)that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain relationship with two collections. (relationExistsAllMany BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that for every instance INST of COL2, there are many (see Many_Quant) instances INST(i) of COL1 such that (BINPRED INST(i) INST). It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(implies (isa ?INST COL2) (thereExistRange Many_Quant ?INST-I (and (isa ?INST COL1) (BINPRED ?INST-I ?INST)))) .

For example, `(relationExistsAllMany soldAt PostageStamp PostOfficeOrganization)' means many postage stamps are sold at each post office. Cf. relationAllExistsMany, and see #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists All Many
relationExistsAllMany

comment:
(collectionGenlsBackchainEncouraged COLLECTION)

means that rules that conclude

(genls <anything> COLLECTION)

are most likely going to have to be used in order to prove literals of the form

(genls <anything> COLLECTION).

This directs the inference engine to use such rules even if HL predicate transformation is disabled. Note that it will not necessarily use rules of the form

(genls <anything> <variable>)

where <variable> might bind to COLLECTION, and it will not necessarily use rules of the form

(genls <anything> SPEC),

where (genls SPEC COLLECTION).

See also backchainEncouraged for the analogue of this predicate applicable to predicates rather than collections.
label: Collection Genls Backchain Encouraged
collectionGenlsBackchainEncouraged

(endTogetherInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 and SIT2 end at the same time.

Note that (endTogetherInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).

comment: A ternary ArgGenlPredicate (q.v.). (argGenl RELN N COL) means that semantic well-formedness requires that anything given as the Nth argument to RELN must be a subcollection of COL. That is, (RELN ... ARGN ...) is semantically well-formed only if (genls ARGN COL) holds. For example, (argGenl AtomFn 1 ElementStuff) and (argGenl argGenl 3 Thing) both hold. In the special case where N is 0, argGenl is used to state that a certain genls constraint applies to each of RELN's argument-places. Thus, (argGenl RELN 0 COL) means that any semantically appropriate argument to RELN, regardless of argument-place, must be a specialization of COL. For example, (argGenl AtomicCompositionFn 0 (GroupFn Atom)) holds. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its specializations. For similar but less flexible binary predicates, see arg1Genls et al. See also argIsa.
label: Arg Genl
argGenl

comment:
A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate that is a specialization of completelyEnumerableCollection (qq.v.). (completelyAssertedCollection COL) means that, for every instance INST whatsoever of the collection COL, there is an assertion in the Cyc Knowledge Base of the form (isa INST COL). This requires, of course, that for every instance of COL there be a reified CycL term that denotes it.

For example, (completelyAssertedCollection DayOfWeekType) holds because there are seven assertions of the form (isa INST DayOfWeekType) in the KB, one for each day of the week (viz. Monday, Tuesday, etc.).

Note, however, that if one reified a specialization of DayOfWeekType called DayOfWeekendType, and edited the isa assertions on Saturday and Sunday so that they referenced the latter collection instead of the former, then DayOfWeekType would no longer be a completelyAssertedCollection (though it would still be a completely-enumerable one).
label: Completely Asserted Collection
completelyAssertedCollection

programConfigurationForAccount
comment: (programConfigurationForAccount U-PROGRAM ACCOUNT CONFIG) means that for the UserAccount ACCOUNT, the UserProgram U-PROGRAM has the #$ProgramConfigurationAttribute CONFIG. If it is true that ACCOUNT is logged in on a computer (see accountLoggedInOn) a computer and a process associated with U-PROGRAM is running on the same computer, then the process is most likely running within parameters delineated by CONFIG.

An assertion of the form (declarationModes_Final DEC PRED SYMB LIST) is used to state that for the InductiveLogicProgrammingDeclaration DEC, one of its elements, the Predicate PRED, can be given the mode represented by SYMB and LIST, which is itself a list of instances of InductiveLogicProgrammingMode. In short, this allows us to pass out to a Prolog-ComputerLanguage based ILP system a mode declaration in a recognizable format that recognizes arg constraints among CycL predicates. Assertion using the predicate declarationModes-Final are generated in conjunction with assertions using the predicate declarationModesThroughArg.
label: Declaration Modes Final
declarationModes-Final

That is, (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 INDEPENDENT-ARG ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG2 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 5 2
interArgEqualsIsa5-2

comment: (importExpenditureFractionDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE THING NR) means that NR is the quotient of the monetary value of imports of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE by the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING (as dividend) and the monetary value of REGION's imports of all goods and services during the temporal extent of THING (as divisor). THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that Oman's oil imports accounted for 80 percent of the total value of its imports in 1997, we can say (importExpenditureFractionDuring Oman PetroleumProduct (YearFn 1997) (Percent 80)). importExpenditureFractionDuring

comment: (assignedValueOfQuantityForEvaluationType NUMBER INTERVAL EVALUATION-TYPE) says that the Quantity QUANT has been assigned the real number NUMBER for purposes of performing evaluations of type EVALUATION-TYPE. That is, instances of EVALUATION-TYPE will invoke a numeric scale NUM-SCALE isomorphic with a non-numeric scale SCALE such that NUMBER and QUANT are points along NUM-SCALE and SCALE, respectively, where NUMBER is mapped to QUANT. For example, given a request such as, 'on a scale from 1 to 10, rate your satisfaction with your new Honda,' the scale that ranges from 1 to 10 is mapped onto a scale that ranges from a certain level of Dissatisfaction to a certain level of Satisfaction; assignedValueOfQuantityForEvaluationType is the predicate one would use in this case to identify the mapping of numbers to levels of satisfaction.

assignedValueOfQuantityForEvaluationType

comment: This predicate specifies the amount by which a given quantity changes in a given time period. For instance, (changesQuantityByAmount (YearFn 1980) SaudiArabia oilExport (MillionBarrelsPerYear 1)) means that in 1980, Saudi Arabia's oil export increased by 1 million barrels per day. Note that the `everything else being equal' clause indicates that the value of SLOT for THING might change, even *de*crease, were more information to become available about TYPE: this means that this predicate is *not* inverse-transitive w.r.t. the genls relation in the first argument. comment:
This predicate is used to state that the value of a quantity slot remains constant for a fixed object throughout an event. (constantThroughoutEvent SLOT THING EVENT) is true if and only if for every pair of sub-events SUB1 and SUB2 of EVENT there exist values VAL1 and VAL2 such that if 
(and
  (startsAfterEndingOf SUB1 SUB2)
  (holdsIn SUB1 (SLOT THING VAL1))
  (holdsIn SUB2 (SLOT THING VAL2)))
it follows that 
(numericallyEquals VAL1 VAL2)
is true. See also decreasesThroughoutEvent and increasesThroughoutEvent.
label: Constant Throughout Event
constantThroughoutEvent

comment:
(wordSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred_Inverse WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION BINARY-PREDICATE) means that the fact that 
   (wordSenseExtension WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION)
is explained in part by the fact that 
   (BINARY-PREDICATE ARG1 ARG2)
for some ARG1 and ARG2 such that 
   (denotation WORD ARG2 SPEECH-PART-1 N)
for some N.

The reason why this sense extension is only partly explained by the above considerations reflects the fact that due to Cyc's incomplete knowledge, there will be many cases where BINARY-PREDICATE is not an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and so cannot reliably broker sense extensions from SPEECH-PART-1 to SPEECH-PART-2 for any word denoting one of its arg1s. Rather, there is a possibly unreified specialization SPEC-PRED of BINARY-PRED (see genlPreds) that is an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and the fact that (SPEC-PRED ARG1 ARG2) fully explains the sense extension in question.

comment: (laborForceOfIndustryOrOccupationDuring REGION COL THING NR) means that NR is the average labor force of the economic sector or occupation COL in the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING, where the labor force of an economic sector or occupation in a region at a point in time is the sum of the number of persons employed and unemployed in the sector or occupation in the region. COL can range from a broad economic sector, such as agriculture, manufacturing, or services to a more specific segment of the economy such as the automobile industry; in either of these cases, COL will be a specialization of the collection Industry_Localized. Alternatively, COL can be an instance of the collection PersonTypeByOccupation. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. See also laborForceDuring.

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates a given spatial thing to a pair of points in it that are in a broad sense "polar opposites". (antipodesInSpatialThing POINT1 POINT2 OBJ) holds if and only if POINT1 and POINT2 are maximally distant points in OBJ with respect to some line that passes through OBJ's center. More precisely: (i) POINT1 and POINT2 are both subsumed (see spatiallySubsumes) by OBJ; (ii) POINT1, POINT2, and the centroid (see centroidOfObject) CENTER of OBJ are collinearPoints on a line LINE such that CENTER lies between the other two points; (iii) there is no point POINT1A in OBJ and on LINE such that POINT1 is between CENTER and POINT1A; and (iv) there is no point POINT2A in OBJ and on LINE such that POINT2 is between CENTER and POINT2A.

See also the specialization polesOfSpheroid.
label: Antipodes In Spatial Thing
antipodesInSpatialThing

PT might, for example, be a Country or a Business or a FactoryBuilding. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. If AMOUNT is a Rate, AMOUNT indicates the average rate of emission of instances of COL by PT during the temporal extent of THING.

comment:
A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate (q.v.) that applies to collections. (completelyDecidableCollection COL) means that the CycInferenceEngine can determine if any given thing is an instance of COL. More precisely: for any given instance INST whatsoever (and for no non-instances) of COL, there is a CycL term INST-TERM that denotes INST such that (without using transformations) the Inference Engine, given a query of the form (isa INST-TERM COL), will return the answer True.

For example, the collection Integer is completely decidable. Given any integer INT, the Cyc query (isa INT Integer) -- wherein INT is given its standard base-10 arabic numeral representation -- will come back True.

If COL is completely decidable and Cyc fails to return True for some query (isa TERM COL), that fact consitutes a strong argument for the truth of its negation (not (isa TERM COL)). But note that it is not a conclusive argument: the normally-reliable "unique name assumption" might fail here, and the term TERM could conceivably denote something that Cyc can prove to be an instance of COL only under some other CycL name it has. For suppose #$Pace's favorite number happens to be 3, but nobody has told that to Cyc. Cyc can prove the sentence (isa 3 Integer); but it might nevertheless fail to prove the equally true sentence 

  (isa (FavoriteNumberOfFn #$Pace) Integer) .
See also the more specific predicates completelyEnumerableCollection and completelyAssertedCollection. And see completeExtentDecidable, which applies to Predicates.
label: Completely Decidable Collection
completelyDecidableCollection

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa5_3 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the fifth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the third argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 INDEPENDENT-ARG ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG3 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 5 3
interArgEqualsIsa5-3

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat2_2 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the second argument-place of PRED when PRED's second argument is restricted to being an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ... ARGN) in which ARG2 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg2 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG2' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation. Note that interArgFormat2_2 is one of several "degenerate-case" inter-argument format predicates, in which the specified condition and the corresponding format constraint both have to do with the _same_ argument-place of a given predicate.

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain relation to two collections. (relationNotExistsExists BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that for any instance INST1 of COL1, no instance INST2 of COL2 is such that (BINPRED INST1 INST2) holds. It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 

  (not
    (and
      (isa ?INST1 COL1)
      (BINPRED INST1 INST2)
      (isa ?INST2 COL2)))

So relationNotExistsExists (and its defining axiom; see expansion) enables this common type of rule to be stated more tersely.

For example, '(relationNotExistsExists performedBy Hunting_Animal Herbivore)' means that no herbivore hunts animals.
label: Relation Not Exists Exists
relationNotExistsExists

comment:
A MetaPredicate that is a generalization of transitiveViaArgInverse (q.v.) in that it can take any binary predicate (transitive or not) as its second argument. (conservativeViaArgInverse PRED RELN N) means that if both of these hold: 
  (PRED ... ARGN ... )
  (RELN NEW-ARGN ARGN),

then so does 

  (PRED ... NEW-ARGN ...)
(where the argument-sequence ... NEW-ARGN ... is just like ... ARGN ... except for having NEW-ARGN in place of ARGN).

Note that if RELN is a TransitiveBinaryPredicate, the more specialized transitiveViaArgInverse can be used instead. See also conservativeViaArg.
label: Conservative Via Arg Inverse
conservativeViaArgInverse

comment: (postureConnotesFeelingToward POSTURE FEELING THING) means that POSTURE, an instance of Posture_Configuration, in some way communicates FEELING toward THING. More precisely, POSTURE communicates that the animal who is 'in' POSTURE (see animalInPosture) has FEELING towards THING. Note that it is possible that ANIMAL neither has nor wishes to communicate such a feeling, but her being in POSTURE nevertheless suggests this. For example, there are a number of bodily postures that, in Arab cultures, communicate a lack of Respect towards the person to whom one is speaking.

comment: (decreasesCausallyOverPeriod EVENT THING SLOT PERIOD) means that EVENT causes the value of the predicate SLOT applied to THING to be lower immediately after (STIF q.v.) PERIOD than it was immediately before (STIB q.v.) PERIOD. PERIOD must start no earlier than EVENT starts in order to prevent effects preceeding their causes. If PERIOD ends before EVENT, it still must be the case that the value of SLOT applied to THING must be lower immediately following EVENT than it was immediately before EVENT. Like with decreasesImmediately, the decrease need not be monotonic. This predicate is agnostic as to whether the decrease occurs during EVENT or after it. See #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for a map of related predicates.

(rectangularSolidTypeOfSize DIST1 DIST2 DIST3 SOLIDTYPE) means that SOLIDTYPE is the GeometricShapeTypeBySize (q.v.) whose instances are all and only those RectangularParallelepipeds (q.v.) whose dimensional measurements are DIST1 by DIST2 by DIST3.

comment: This is a generalization of learnedCapableOf. (capableOfLearningTo AGT ACT-TYPE ROLE) holds just in case AGT has the required background knowledge that would enable him/her to either immediately play ROLE in acts of type ACT-TYPE, or could learn to do so in a relatively short time. The time required for AGT to learn to do acts of type ACT-TYPE depends on the act type. For instance, nuclear physicists are likely to have the required background knowledge that would enable them to, after some study, design a nuclear weapon. A person with a bachelor's degree in business would likely have the background knowledge required to write a particular kind of report, though he/she may have to examine some previous reports of that nature to understand exactly what to do. The time required for the physicist to learn how to design a bomb and the business person to learn how to write the report probably vary greatly. While a few months may be a short time to learn how to design a weapon, a few days is probably much longer than what is needed to learn to write a report.
label: Capable Of Learning To
capableOfLearningTo

(birthDate #$YassirArafat ?DATE) (HighAmountFn Relevance) FolderWithIntelligenceQueriesForSuggestion) would state that the string "When was Arafat born?" would be translated to the CycLSentence_Askable (birthDate #$YassirArafat DATE) and been deemed to have a high amount of relevance relative to queries that are stored in instances of KEInteractionFolder that are also instances of FolderWithIntelligenceQueriesForSuggestion.

comment:
A VariableArityPredicate that takes one or more abstract character strings. Its first argument is the concatenation of its successive arguments. For any instances STRING1, ..., STRINGn of CharacterString, (concatenateStrings STRING1 ... STRINGn) holds just in case STRING1 is the character-string that is obtained by concatenating STRING2, ..., STRINGn end-to-end in the order from 2 to n.

For example, (concatenateStrings "Bob" "B" "o" "b"), and (concatenateStrings "Bob Dylan" "Bob" " " "Dy" "lan").

Note that some (or all) of STRING2, ..., STRINGn might be identical. Also note that, when applied to a single argument, this predicate always holds, and when applied to two arguments, this predicate holds just in case the two arguments are equal; e.g. (concatenateStrings "Bob" "Bob").
label: Concatenate Strings
concatenateStrings
