genlsExactly

comment: (unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsDuring DRUGTYPE RXFILLTYPE PERIOD NUM) means that NUM 'units' have been filled (by all Prescribers) for DRUGTYPE via DrugPrescriptions of type RXFILLTYPE during PERIOD. RXFILLTYPE may be FillingAPrescription_Retail, FillingAPrescription_MailOrder, FillingANewPrescription, FillingARefillPrescription, intersections of these, or merely FillingAPrescription.
label: Units Of Drug Prescriptions During
unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsDuring

comment: This is the most basic general signification or representation predicate. (signifiesTo THING1 THING2 AGENT) means that, to AGENT, THING1 signifies THING2. To AGENT's mind (or other system of semeiosis), the 'sign' THING1 represents, refers to, denotes, describes or depicts its 'object' THING2. THING2 can be anything, and THING1 can be almost anything, although it is most often a word, phrase, description, string, image or symbol. Very abstractly speaking, AGENT must be capable of representation, or semeiosis, whereby AGENT's relationship to the the 'sign' THING1 causes AGENT to come into a related relationship with the 'object' THING2. Note that this predicate does not state the mechanism by means of which THING1 represents THING2; that can be asserted with more specific predicates. In order to omit the explicit mention of the 'interpretant' or AGENT to whom THING1 means THING2, use the short-form BinaryPredicate signifies. Often there is a convention (intersubjective understanding and agreement) by which one thing represents another, such as the word 'Dog' referring to dogs in English, or the abstract tetrahedron referring to the element Fire in Alchemy. A pile of three rocks on a path can signify 'danger ahead' and the number thirteen can signify bad luck. But there need be no specific convention; Deer tracks in the sand can signify the deer to the tracker, and a picture or photograph may signify what ever it is a picture of to anyone who beholds it, in both cases without any prior convention or agreement. Thus this predicate has more specialized predicates signifiesTo_Icon (which represents by means of resemblance, like a picture or a stalactite), signifiesTo_Index (which represents by causation, as a deer track represents a deer or a weather vane represents the North Wind), and signifiesTo_Symbol (which represents by some convention, as 'dog' represents dogs by the conventions of English). These are three main kinds of sign in the semiotic theory of CharlesPeirce.
label: sign
signifiesTo

comment:
(pairwisePropertyOfCollection MODIFIER COLLECTION THING) states that THING is the property described by MODIFIER. This is a very general predicates and its meaning in a given context is determined by what stands in its arg1. For example, 
        (pairwisePropertyOfCollection Longest_Between COLLECTION DURATION)
means that DURATION is the longest empty duration between members of COLLECTION. That is, it looks at the instances of COLLECTION and for each sequential pair it calculates the duration between them and returns the longest duration as the value for DURATION. Note that COLLECTION must be a collection of temporal things for which the start and end dates are known. .
label: Pairwise Property Of Collection
pairwisePropertyOfCollection

comment:
A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keSuggestionPreds_SpecSpec COL1 BINPRED COL2) means that for every known specialization SPEC1 of COL1, it is suggested that there be some specialization SPEC2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED SPEC1 SPEC2) is known in the knowledge base.

For example,

(keSuggestionPreds_SpecSpec PreparingFoodOrDrink outputsCreated_TypeType FoodOrDrink)

means that for every known specialization PREP-TYPE of PreparingFoodOrDrink it is suggested that there be some specialization FD-TYPE of FoodOrDrink such that (outputsCreated_TypeType PREP-TYPE FD-TYPE) is known in the knowledge base.

See also keSuggestionPredsInverse_SpecSpec.
label: Ke Suggestion Preds Spec Spec
keSuggestionPreds-SpecSpec

comment: (translationAlongWithinDistance MOVE TRAV DIST) means that the moving object OBJ (see objectMoving) in Translation_SingleTrajectory MOVE moves along the Traversal TRAV with the Distance specified by DIST. For example, an airplane may fly along the Great Wall, and a person may walk on the top of an oil pipe, or on the side of a river. But in any case, the 'distance' between OBJ and TRAV should be at most the distance specified by DIST (e.g. (Kilometer 100)). DIST here is an instance of Distance which is greater than or equal to the distance between OBJ and TRAV at each moment during the event MOVE. Note that when DIST equals 'zero-unit' (whatever the UnitOfDistance is), we mean that at every moment during MOVE, OBJ is on TRAV (see onTraversal), and hence we would have (traverses_Complete MOVE TRAV).
label: Translation Along Within Distance
translationAlongWithinDistance

comment: (decontextualizedCollection COL) states that COL is a collection in which membership is context-independent. In effect, any instance of COL is an instance of COL in every microtheory.
label: Decontextualized Collection
decontextualizedCollection

comment: (kePrecisionSuggestionByTypeRestriction_Inverse BROADP NARROWP COL1 COL2) indicates that whenever [1] (BROADP INS1 INS2) is known and [2] COL1, COL2 are respectively the 2nd and 1st arg constraint on NARROWP and [3] INS1, INS2 are instances of, resp., COL1 and COL2, then (NARROWP INS2 INS1) is likely to be true. This predicate is used to suggest plausible specializations to ke'rs via the predicate strengthener. If one of the Collection arguments is irrelevant to the suggested restriction, use the arg constraint for BROADP in that position. E.g. if (kePrecisionSuggestionByTypeRestriction_Inverse BROADP NARROWP BROAD_COL1 COL2) and (arg1Isa BROADP BROAD_COL1), then that collection is ignored by the strengthener.
label: Ke Precision Suggestion By Type Restriction Inverse
kePrecisionSuggestionByTypeRestriction-Inverse

comment: (repeatPrecedingActionAtIntervalNTimes AGENT INTERVAL TIMES) means that AGENT repeats the immediately preceeding action in a plan INTERVAL often and TIMES many times. See also repeatPrecedingActionNTimes.
label: Repeat Preceding Action At Interval N Times
repeatPrecedingActionAtIntervalNTimes

comment: The predicate used to state, for an adjustable-rate loan, the highest amount by which the interest rate can change during any single adjustment period. (interestRateCap_Periodic LOAN PERIOD (Percent N)) means that the interestRate on LOAN cannot either increase or decrease by more than (Percent N) during PERIOD. So if it is also the case that (interestRate LOAN RATE) where RATE is (PerFn (Percent M) DURATION) then RATE may not become more than (PerFn (Percent M + N) DURATION) during PERIOD, or less than (PerFn (Percent M - N) DURATION) during PERIOD.
label: Interest Rate Cap Periodic
interestRateCap-Periodic

comment: This predicate represents the idea that an agent may be enabled to do something not by the occurrence of an event, but simply by finding herself, more or less statically, in a certain situation. Example: having residence in midtown Manhattan enables one to attend performances of the Metropolitan Opera, in the sense of making it more likely that one would be capable of attending such a performance than if one would be if she were, say, in Austin. Therefore, (enables_StaticConduciveFactor SIT AGENT ACT_TYPE) means that SIT makes it more likely that AGENT would succeed at an instance of ACT_TYPE were she to attempt than it would be otherwise -- i.e., if SIT did not obtain.
label: Enables Static Conducive Factor
enables-StaticConduciveFactor
Parse Fodder
parseFodder
comment: (parseFodder STRING) means that STRING is a candidate for parsing.

(investmentAmountDuring PT PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the amount of MonetaryValue AMOUNT was spent on instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE by PartiallyTangible PT during the the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING, where PT acquired those instances in order to use them as inputs to production. PT will commonly be an Agent_PartiallyTangible that is involved in producing goods, such as a Business or ManufacturingOrganization.
label: Investment Amount During
investmentAmountDuring

comment: ARG1 has ARG3 for its ARG2.  For example, Karen's computer has 'A3000' for its <font color="#ff0000">#$ModelNumber</font>.
label: Id String Of Type
idStringOfType

comment:
A KBDependentRelation (q.v.) and specialization of knownSentence (q.v.) that is used to state that a given CycLSentence_Assertible has been asserted in the KB (in some accessible Microtheory). More exactly, (assertedSentence SENT) is true in microtheory MT precisely when SENT canonicalizes into a set of clauses of the same form as the canonicalized form of some assertion in a microtheory accessible to MT. (The predicate is thus true both of assertions entered into the KB by hand and assertions deduced by Cyc from forward rules.) For the more specific claim that SENT is asserted in MT, see the predicate ist_Asserted.

This predicate enables Cyc to select a subset of information when answering queries, filtering out more generic (inferrable-but-not-asserted) information. Thus, for example, the query:

(genls Dog Thing)

will return True (in appropriate microtheories), whereas:

(assertedSentence (genls Dog Thing))

will not.
label: Asserted Sentence
assertedSentence

comment: A predicate mapped in from the NWU Trafficability and Terrain Engine. (shortestRouteByRoadsBetween PATH LOC1 LOC2) means that PATH is the shortest path for wheeled vehicles connecting LOC1 and LOC2, in the sense that there does not exist any other path for wheeled vehicles connecting LOC1 and LOC2 whose length is the same length as PATH or shorter.
label: Shortest Route By Roads Between
shortestRouteByRoadsBetween

comment: (typicalInfectionRoute INFECTION-TYPE ORGANISM-TYPE PART-TYPE) means that if an organism of type ORGANISM-TYPE is penetrated by a pathogen capable of causing infections of type INFECTION-TYPE via a physical part of the organism of the type PART-TYPE, it is highly likely that the organism would contract an infection of type INFECTION-TYPE caused by the invading pathogen, unless the organism were already immune to infections of that type.
label: Typical Infection Route
typicalInfectionRoute

comment: The agent ARG1 may authorize (grant the authority for) the agent ARG2 to perform instances of the action type ARG3.
label: May Authorize
mayAuthorize

comment: (hasPersonalityTraitToDegree AGENT TRAIT DEGREE) means that IntelligentAgent AGENT has the instance of #$Temperament TRAIT to amount DEGREE.
label: Has Personality Trait To Degree
hasPersonalityTraitToDegree

comment: An assertion of the form (scoreRankForGame SCORE RANK GAME) states that, within a given context, there is a non-empty set of instances of GameEvent where the Game GAME was played. Further, SCORE represents the final score that was achieved by some player in at least one of the elements of that set (see agentFinalScoreInGame). Finally, if the set of scores of those games were ranked in order from highest to lowest, then SCORE would be the RANKth element of that list.
label: Score Rank For Game
scoreRankForGame

comment:
This predicate is a generalization of the more specific
predicates of the form 'enables-Removes????Factors'. It may be used to
assert that an event enables an agent to do something when it's clear that
the relevant sense of 'enabling' is that of 'removing generally negative
factors' but it's not equally clear whether the negative factors removed
were incapacitating, disabling or merely contrary. Please check the
documentation for this and related constants thoroughly before settling on
this predicate: assertions involving it are not likely to be helpful in
inference.
label: Enables Removes Unspecified Factors
enables-RemovesUnspecifiedFactors

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat2_3 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the third argument-place of PRED when PRED's second argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ... ARGN) in which ARG2 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg3 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG3' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 2 3
interArgFormat2-3

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates an instance of InformationGathering to a (quoted) instance of CycLSentence to an instance of Relevance. (sentenceHasRelevanceToInformationGathering IG SENT REL) means that SENT is relevant to IG to the degree REL.

Suppose, for example, that IG-001 is an InformationGathering in which someone is gathering information about the current government of Australia. Then the following might hold: 

(sentenceHasRelevanceToInformationGathering IG-001 
   (primeMinister Australia ?WHO) 
   (HighAmountFn Relevance))

(sentenceHasRelevanceToInformationGathering IG-001 
   (capitalCity Australia ?WHAT) 
   (MediumAmountFn Relevance))

(sentenceHasRelevanceToInformationGathering IG-001 
   (countryFaxCode Australia ?WHAT) 
   (NoAmountFn Relevance))
label: Sentence Has Relevance To Information Gathering
sentenceHasRelevanceToInformationGathering

comment: (taxableEquivalentRevenueForPeriod ORG MONEY TIME) means that ORG's taxable-equivalent revenue during TIME is MONEY. Taxable-equivalent revenue is total revenue modulo a taxable-equivalency adjustment for tax-exempt income and investment credits.
label: Taxable Equivalent Revenue For Period
taxableEquivalentRevenueForPeriod

comment: (preventsFromPlayingSpecifiedRole SIT OBJ ROLE SPECIFICATION) means that the occurance of the Situation SIT prevents OBJ from playing the role ROLE in any situation described by the NormativeSpecification SPECIFICATION.
label: Prevents From Playing Specified Role
preventsFromPlayingSpecifiedRole

comment: A instance of DeReAttitudePredicate (q.v.) that can be used to ascribe a "de re" belief: a belief that is about a certain thing "in itself," independently of whichever way the believer (or the ascriber) might conceptualize or describe the thing. (believesOfArg AGENT SENT N) means that AGENT has a de re belief about the thing OBJ denoted by the Nth-place constituent of SENT, that what SENT says about OBJ is true. Since a _de_re_ belief about OBJ is being ascribed, it doesn't really matter _which_ name of OBJ happens to appear in SENT: _any_ expression that denotes OBJ would do; and any such expression could be substituted for the original name of OBJ without changing the truth-value of the believesOfArg sentence. For example, the sentences (believesOfArg #$Meyer (isa #$Patches-Cat TabbyCat) 1) (believesOfArg #$Meyer (likesAsFriend #$Zaiss #$Patches-Cat) 2) mean, respectively, that Meyer believes (de re) of the cat Patches that he is a domestic pet and that Meyer believes (de re) of Patches that Zaiss likes him. Note the difference between these de re belief sentences and the analogous beliefs (q.v.) sentences, which attribute "de dicto" beliefs. While both believesOfArg and beliefs have their second (sentence-taking) argument-places "quoted" (see quotedArgument), only the former predicate has rules asserted of it allowing the sort of substitutions mentioned above. Supposing 'GarysPet' were another CycL term that denoted Patches, that term could be substituted for '#$Patches-Cat' in either of the above example sentences without changing the sentence's truth-value. But a similar substitution is not licensed in the de dicto belief sentence (beliefs #$Meyer (isa #$Patches-Cat TabbyCat)) , reflecting that possibility that Meyer isn't aware that Patches belongs to Gary.
label: Believes Of Arg
believesOfArg

comment: querySentence is an HL level predicate that allows for special handling of a sentence (especially nested sentences) as a top level query during the process of canonicalization. querySentence is not-assertible. It should not be used in any assertions.
label: Query Sentence
querySentence

comment: This is the corresponding predicate of CDASubStringAtOffsetWithLengthFn.
label: Is Sub String Of CDA At Offset
isSubStringOfCDAAtOffset

comment: (typicallyRelnFromType PRED SET-OR-COL-2 SET-OR-COL-1) means that typically (i.e., most and some) elements EL-1 of SET-OR-COL-1 are such that there exists an element EL-2 of SET-OR-COL-2 such that (PRED EL-2 EL-1).
label: Typically Reln From Type
typicallyRelnFromType
subPropertyOf: Most Gen Quant Reln From Type

comment:
(immediatelyAfterInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 starts immediately after SIT2 ends.

Note that (immediatelyAfterInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).
label: Immediately After In Situation Type
immediatelyAfterInSituationType

comment: (multiWordStringDenotesArgInReln LIST NOUN POS PRED ARG) says that (multiWordString LIST NOUN POS TERM), where TERM is the collection of things that are the arg ARG of PRED for any true sentence in which PRED is the arg0. For example, (multiWordStringDenotesArgInReln ("biological") #$Mother-TheWord CountNoun biologicalMother 2) says that one denotation for the phrase 'biological mother(s),' is the collection of things T such that (relationExistsInstance biologicalMother Thing T) -- i.e., the collection of all biological mothers. This predicate is useful for linking nouns in the lexicon to *virtual* KB collections, particularly collections we don't necessarily want to have explicitly represented in the KB.
label: Multi Word String Denotes Arg In Reln
multiWordStringDenotesArgInReln

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a binary predicate relates to a given thing only instances of a certain collection. (relationOnlyInstance PRED COL GIVENTHING) means that, for any thing THING, (PRED THING GIVENTHING) holds only if THING is an instance of COL. This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 
  (implies
    (PRED ?X GIVENTHING)
    (isa ?X COL)) .
Note the the above does not entail that that there is some instance THING of COL such that (PRED THING GIVENTHING) holds.

Compare with relationAllInstance and relationExistsInstance. See also the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Only Instance
relationOnlyInstance

comment: (chanceForRoleBecauseIs AGENT EVTTYPE ROLE PROP VAL) means that in the context of the assertion, the chance for AGENT playing ROLE in a situation of type EVTTYPE is VAL because PROP is true in the context of the assertion.
label: Chance For Role Because Is
chanceForRoleBecauseIs

comment: A relation between a verb sense and the type of transitivity alternations in which it participates.
label: Participates In Alternation
participatesInAlternation

comment: (tourDayMeals TOUR DAY MEALTYPE) means that on DAY, a meal of type MEALTYPE will be provided for those taking TOUR, having already been paid for in advance by the participants as part of the tour package.
label: Tour Day Meals
tourDayMeals

comment:
A quintary instance of InterArgEqualsIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa RELN INDEP-ARGNUM INDEPENDENT-ARG DEP-ARGNUM DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the INDEP-ARGNUMth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the DEP-ARGNUMth argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ... INDEPENDENT-ARG ...), where INDEPENDENT-ARG is the INDEP-ARGNUMth argument to RELN, is semantically well-formed only if the DEP-ARGNUMth argument is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For example, (interArgIsa softwareParameterValueInSpecification 1 InferenceSentenceParameter 2 #$ELSentence-Assertible) means that (softwareParameterValueInSpecification InferenceSentenceParameter VALUE SPEC) is semantically well-formed only if VALUE is an instance of #$ELSentence-Assertible.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. For similar to but less flexible predicates than interArgEqualsIsa, which have already-fixed positions for the independent and dependent arguments, see the ternary interArgEqualsIsa1_2 et al. Cf. interArgIsa.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa
interArgEqualsIsa

comment: (subcollectionOfWithRelationFrom SUPER-COL PREDICATE THING SUB-COL) means that SUB-COL is the collection of all instances INSTANCE of SUPER-COL for which (PREDICATE THING INSTANCE) holds. See the function that corresponds to this predicate, SubcollectionOfWithRelationFromFn.
label: Subcollection Of With Relation From
subcollectionOfWithRelationFrom

comment: Like relatedToVia (relatedToVia_Least OBJ1 OBJ2 SET NUM) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are related via some sequence of NUM steps via the binary relations in the set SET. More precisely, (relatedToVia_Least OBJ1 OBJ2 SET NUM) means that there is a sequence of objects of the length equal to NUM that OBJ1 is the first element of the sequence, OBJ2 is the last element of the sequence, and each element of the sequence is related to its successor (if any) by some predicate in SET, or by the inverse of some predicate in SET. Unlike relatedToVia, relatedToVia_Least returns in the fourth argument the least number of steps by which OBJ1 and OBJ2 can be related using the relations in SET.
label: Related To Via Least
relatedToVia-Least

comment:
An instance of TernaryPredicate. (orgCommunicationTargetsAgentTypeForIncreaseSitType ORGANIZATION AGENT-TYPE SIT-TYPE) means that ORGANIZATION targets at least one of its communications at instances of AGENT-TYPE for the purpose of increasing the number if instances of SIT-TYPE in an instance of AGENT-TYPE plays a doneBy role.

Consider for an example the assertion (orgCommunicationTargetsAgentTypeForIncreaseSitType PhilipMorris_Corporation HumanChild SmokingACigarette). If true, this assertion would mean that the PhilipMorris_Corporation deliberately targets some of its communications to children with the goal that more children would smoke.
label: Org Communication Targets Agent Type For Increase Sit Type
orgCommunicationTargetsAgentTypeForIncreaseSitType
Temporal Microtheories Intersect
temporalMicrotheoriesIntersect
comment: This predicate takes an arbitrary number of single fixed dimension temporal microtheories (e.g., MtTimeWithGranularityDimFn expressions) and is true if and only if there is some TimeInterval subsumed by the intersection of the TimeIntervals of the arguments and which subsumes an instance of the largest TimeParameter of the arguments. So, e.g., (temporalMicrotheoriesIntersect (MtTimeWithGranularityDimFn (YearFn 2004) TimePoint) (MtTimeWithGranularityDimFn (DecadeFn 200) CalendarMonth)) is true.
(predHoldsBetweenRolePlayers EVENT-TYPE ROLE1 ROLE2 BIN-REL) means that in any instance of EVENT-TYPE, the binary relation BIN-REL holds between any player of ROLE1 and any player of ROLE2.
label: Pred Holds Between Role Players
predHoldsBetweenRolePlayers
Deserves Further Inquiry
deservesFurtherInquiry
comment: `(deservesFurtherInquiry SENTENCE)' means that SENTENCE expresses a proposition about which not enough is currently known by Cyc to determine its truth value but which is such that Cyc knows enough information suggesting truth to warrant pursuing further information. The main intended purpose for such an assertion is to guide Cyc's behavior in interactive contexts.
(inhalingToxicityFor STUFF ORGTYPE TOXLEVEL) means that under ordinary circumstances, stuff has the Toxicity TOXLEVEL for instances of ORGTYPE that inhale it.
label: inhaling toxicity
inhalingToxicityFor

comment: An assertion of the form (termRankingPreference FOCUS TERM1 TERM2) asserts that with regard to the instace of CycTermRankingFocus FOCUS, it is desirable that the CycLTerm TERM1 receive a higher ranking than the CycLTerm TERM2. That is, it is expected that, relative to FOCUS, that there are more connections to TERM1 within the relevant instance of CycKB than there are connections to TERM2.
label: Term Ranking Preference
termRankingPreference

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doOutputProgramFunctionHeader PROGRAMMER FILE ALGORITHM) means that PROGRAMMER appends the header of a program function declaration that implements ALGORITHM to the computer source code file FILE. The header typically includes the program function's name and its parameter list.
label: Do Output Program Function Header
doOutputProgramFunctionHeader

comment: An assertion of the form (infantMortalityRateDuring PLACE ORG-TYPE REAL DATE) states that measurements of the population indicate that for every 1000 infants born in the GeographicalRegion PLACE during the Date DATE, REAL of those infants died. For example, an assertion of the form (infantMortalityRateDuring Syria HomoSapiens 3.4 (YearFn 2005)) states that records indicate that during 2005, for every 1000 children that were born in Syria, 3.4 of those same children died. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Infant Mortality Rate During
infantMortalityRateDuring

comment: This predicate defines how a logical field in a logical schema is interpreted and given a physical value in a corresponding physical schema when a specified value appears in a specific comparison predicate argument position.  This overrides the default behavior of assuming that a comparison predicate uses the same encoding for each argument and that when one argument is bound it can use the variable in the other to find a relevant meaning sentecen and logical field indexical with an encoding.
label: Field Encoding Override For Comparison Operator Arg
fieldEncodingOverrideForComparisonOperatorArg

comment: The expression `objectFound_Definite(SEARCH SEEKER OBJECT)' means that the search has succeeded. It says that SEEKER, the performedBy in the SEARCH, has come across the OBJECT which was sought and that SEEKER notices that OBJECT satisfies the searchCriterion_Definite associated with the search. The arg3 position is an opaqueArgument because it is intended to represent the way SEEKER conceptualizes OBJECT in the act of noticing that it satisfies the search criterion.
label: Object Found Definite
objectFound-Definite

comment: A predicate relating instances of ServerProgram with instances of ComputerProgram_CW and instances of Computer. (serverInitiatesProgramOn SERVER PROGRAM COMPUTER) means that SERVER can start a process of PROGRAM usable by remote users of SERVER. Important spec preds of serverInitiatesProgramOn are serverInitiatesServerProgramOn and webServerInitiatesProgramOn.
label: Server Initiates Program On
serverInitiatesProgramOn

comment:
A unary predicate, whose argument-place is "quoted" (see quotedArgument), that is used to state that a given CycL non-atomic term does denote something. Where NAT has the form (FUNC . ARGS), (defined NAT) means that NAT has a denotatum because FUNC (the function denoted by the main functor in NAT) returns a value for the argument sequence ARGS. In other words, FUNC is defined on the sequence ARGS.

Cf. undefined.
label: Defined (unary predicate)
defined

comment:
A specialization of argGenl (q.v.). (nearestArgGenl RELATION NUMBER COL) means that not only is it the case that 
   (argGenl RELATION NUMBER COL)
but also 
   (unknownSentence
     (thereExists ?GENL
        (and
           (argGenl RELATION NUMBER ?GENL)
           (different ?GENL COL)
           (genls ?GENL COL)))).
In other words, COL is a "nearest" -- i.e., non-subsuming -- argGenl constraint for RELATION in the NUMBER-th place.
label: Nearest Arg Genl
nearestArgGenl

comment: (importOriginFractionDuring REGION1 REGION2 THING NR) means that NR is the quotient of the monetary value of the imports by the GeographicalRegion REGION1 from the GeographicalRegion REGION2 during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING (as dividend) and the monetary value of REGION1's imports of all goods and services during the temporal extent of THING (as divisor). THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that imports to the United States accounted for 5 percent of the total value of Oman's imports in 1995, we can say (importOriginFractionDuring Oman UnitedStatesOfAmerica (YearFn 1995) (Percent 5)). See also importAmountDuring.
label: Import Origin Fraction During
importOriginFractionDuring

comment: (phaseLineBoundsRegion LINE REGION1 REGION2) means that LINE is part of the boundary between REGION2 and REGION1.
label: Phase Line Between Regions
phaseLineBetweenRegions

comment: (assistedReaderSourceSpindleHeadForTaskAndUser TASK USER MT) means that MT is the Microtheory that is the collector (see mtSpindleCollector) of the MicrotheorySpindle designed to hold source microtheories whose contents are authored using the CycAssistedDocumentReader by USER while working on TASK.
label: Assisted Reader Source Spindle Collector For Task And User
assistedReaderSourceSpindleCollectorForTaskAndUser

comment: (termToSolveFor Q-SPEC SENT TERM) means that in the context of the query Q-SPEC, the term to be solved for in inference is TERM, a term that occurs in SENT. This predicate is intended to be used together with querySentenceOfQuery (q.v.).
label: Term To Solve For
termToSolveFor

comment: (intentInPlan AGENT PLAN GOAL) means that one of the purposes which AGENT intends for the PlanningDomainMicrotheory PLAN to accomplish is GOAL. This predicate is the plan-analog of purposeInEvent.
label: Intent In Plan
intentInPlan

comment: (generateQuantOverArg PRED QUANT ARG) says that for any sentence S in which PRED is the arg0, the generation code should paraphrase S so as to use the NLQuantAttribute QUANT as a determinter for the NBar generated for the expression in arg place ARG. For example, (generateQuantOverArg relationExistsAll Some_NLAttr 2) says that for any sentence S of the form (relationExistsAll REL ARG2 ARG3), the generation code should paraphrase S so as to include the string 'some X,' where 'X' is the NBar generated for the term appearing in the 2nd argument place.
label: Generate Quant Over Arg
generateQuantOverArg

comment: (viableBridgingCriterionForReferents PEG ANAPHOR PRED) means that the conditions of familiarity and uniqueness presuppositions required for picking the coreferent of ANAPHOR are satisfied by PEG with respect to (some specialization of) the relation PRED. For example (viableBridgingCriterionForReferents PEG1 PEG2 parts) when it is known in the discourse that (isa PEG1 Automobile) and (isa PEG2 SteeringWheel).
label: Viable Bridging Criterion For Referents
viableBridgingCriterionForReferents

comment: The functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical for ColorPerceptionCategoryRangeFn. (colorPerceptionRangeDefinedBy RANGE CATEGORY-1 CATEGORY-2) identifies RANGE as the unique ColorPerceptionCategoryType that is a range of color-perception categories that fall between CATEGORY-1 and CATEGORY-2.
label: Color Perception Range Defined By
colorPerceptionRangeDefinedBy
subPropertyOf: Color Perception Category Range Of Type

comment: (documentBasePath APP COMPUTER PATH) means that the fully qualified directory PATH is the default location for storing document files managed by APP, when APP is running on COMPUTER.
label: Document Base Path
documentBasePath

comment: (nearestDifferentIsa OBJ-1 OBJ-2 NEAR-DIFF) means that NEAR-DIFF is a "nearest" collection of which OBJ-1 is an instance, but OBJ-2 is not. That is, (isa OBJ-1 NEAR-DIFF) holds, but (isa OBJ-2 NEAR-DIFF) does not, and there is no reified Collection OTHER-COL distinct from NEAR-DIFF such that (isa OBJ-1 OTHER-COL) holds, (isa OBJ-2 OTHER-COL) does not hold, and (genls OTHER-COL NEAR-DIFF) holds. Note that this predicate is notAssertible, since it must always be recomputed from the current state of the isa and genls hierarchy. For comparison, see nearestDifferentGenls.
label: Nearest Different Isa
nearestDifferentIsa

Mx4rvWEKXJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Builder Query For Logical Field Type Of SKS
Mx4rv3W2hJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Builder Query For Schematic Element Of SKS
comment: (builderQueryForMeaningSentenceOfSKS SKS PREDICATE QUERY) means that QUERY is the CycLQuerySpecification for the meaning sentence predicate PREDICATE in the StructuredKnowledgeSource SKS.
label: Builder Query For Meaning Sentence Of SKS
builderQueryForMeaningSentenceOfSKS
subPropertyOf: Builder Query For Schematic Element Of SKS

comment: (numberOfInstancesOfCollRelatedToInstancesOfType TYPE INSTANCE TYPE2 NUM BIN-PRED) holds of every NUM such that NUM is the number of instances of TYPE2 that have BIN-PRED to INSTANCE where INSTANCE is an instance of TYPE. For example, the relevant property for Country is eventOccursAt while the relevant property for TerroristGroup_Islamist is performedBy. If Country replaced TYPE and the query were run with some given specialization of Event for TYPE2 with INSTANCE and NUM open, it would return pairs of Countries and numbers such that the number is the number of instances of EVENT-TYPE that occurred in that country. Similarly, a query with TerroristGroup_Islamist replacing THING will net you pairs of terrorist groups that are instances of TerroristGroup_Islamist and the number of attacks they have performed. Note that this predicate will only be well-defined for those types (and their specializations) that we have specifically supported.
label: Number Of Instances Of Coll Related To Instances Of Type
numberOfInstancesOfCollRelatedToInstancesOfType

comment: An instance of both FunctionalPredicate and QuaternaryPredicate. (lowestLethalDoseForOrganismType SUBSTANCE-TYPE ROUTE-TYPE ORGANISM-TYPE DOSE) means that DOSE is the lowest amount of SUBSTANCE-TYPE known to have killed an instance of ORGANISM-TYPE when taken in via ROUTE-TYPE.
label: lowest lethal dose
lowestLethalDoseForOrganismType

comment: (dependsOn SET DEP-SLOT INDEP-SLOT) means that the values for DEP-SLOT are either positively or negatively dependent on the values for INDEP-SLOT, for elements of SET. Unlike the more general correlatedWith (q.v.), dependsOn means that there is some causal link from INDEP-SLOT affecting DEP-SLOT.
label: Depends On
dependsOn

comment: queryTemplate_Reln relates a class of natural language questions (e.g. sentences) to CycL. Unlike queryTemplate, queryTemplate_Reln has a slot for the Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation. For example, (queryTemplate_Reln STemplate objectHasColor ("what" "color" (Be-TheWord Verb) (NPTemplate :obj)) (objectHasColor :obj ?X)) would map "What color is Muffet" to (objectHasColor Muffet ?X).
label: Query Template Reln
queryTemplate-Reln

comment: (citationStringForStyleAndRendering WORK STYLE RENDERING STRING) means that STRING is the canonical string used to cite WORK according to STYLE-SPECIFICATION, for rendering using MARKUP-LANGUAGE.
label: Citation String For Style And Rendering
citationStringForStyleAndRendering

comment: '(equivalentRolePlayers_SitTypeToSubSitType SIT-TYPE ROLE1 SUBSIT-TYPE ROLE2)' means that in any instance SIT of SITTYPE whatever plays ROLE1 also plays ROLE2 in SUBSIT, the subsituation of SIT that is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE, and vice versa.
label: Equivalent Role Players Sit Type To Sub Sit Type
equivalentRolePlayers-SitTypeToSubSitType
subPropertyOf: Inherit Role Players Sit Type To Sub Sit Type
Inherit Role Players Sub Sit Type To Sit Type

comment: (exceptionalGrammaticalGender TYPE THING GENDER) overrides the LanguageGroupingType's usual rules for determining grammatical gender for THING, using NLGenderAttribute instead.
label: Exceptional Grammatical Gender
exceptionalGrammaticalGender

comment: The ternary predicate (cycProblemID CYC-PROBLEM CYC-PROBLEM-STORE SUID) relates an instance of CycProblem qualified by the containing CYC-PROBLEM-STORE, with its internal ID.
label: Cyc Problem ID
cycProblemID

comment: The predicate objectsInMutualContact indicates that two different objects physically touch in a particular PhysicalContactSituation. (objectsInMutualContact SIT OBJ-1 OBJ-2) means that OBJ-1 and OBJ-2 are in contact in the PhysicalContactSituation SIT. For example, a ClothingItem and its wearer are objectsInMutualContact during the wearing. A father and son in a CarryingPiggyback event are objectsInMutualContact. (objectsInMutualContact SIT OBJ-1 OBJ-2) entails (holdsIn SIT (touches OBJ-1 OBJ-2)); touches covers both direct touching and touching indirectly (i.e., through a thin layer, e.g., through clothing).
label: Objects In Mutual Contact
objectsInMutualContact

comment: (situationConstituentWithTypeAndDesc SIT IND TYPE DESC) means that the Individual IND is both a participant in the Situation SIT (situationConstituents) and is an instance of TYPE which can be refrred with the description (or name) DESC.
label: Situation Constituent With Type And Desc
situationConstituentWithTypeAndDesc

comment: If PLACE has latitude LAT and longitude LON, then (locatedInBoundingBoxWithCoordinates PLACE LAT-MAX LON-MIN LAT-MIN LON-MAX) is true precisely if (LAT-MAX > LAT > LAT-MIN) and (LON-MAX > LON > LON-MIN).
label: Located In Bounding Box With Coordinates
locatedInBoundingBoxWithCoordinates

comment: (aggregateCNCResultForRuleWithThresholds RULE COMPOUND-THRESHOLD COMPONENT-THRESHOLD RESULT SEARCH-ENGINE) means that RESULT--a list of various data used in evaluating RULE--was obtained by evaluating RULE wrt. COMPONENT-THRESHOLD and COMPOUND-THRESHOLD. The COMPOUND-THRESHOLD value represents a minimum number of hits which a compound-strings must have for candidate compounds to be regarded as sufficiently evident within a corpus to be of interest. The COMPONENT-THRESHOLD value represents a minimum number of hits which the modifier- and head-strings for candiate compounds must have for candidates to count as vaild tests wrt. the corpus.
label: Aggregate CNC Result For Rule With Thresholds
aggregateCNCResultForRuleWithThresholds

comment: (pointOfContact_Types AGENT_TYPE CONTLOC_TYPE BLDG_TYPE) means that instances of AGENT_TYPE ordinarily have some instance of the Collection BLDG_TYPE as their ContactLocationType CONTLOC_TYPE.
label: Point Of Contact Types
pointOfContact-Types

comment: (infoUnderstoodByReferenceToInfo INFO-1 STRING-A INFO-2 STRING-B) holds just in case the phrase denoted by STRING-A in INFO-1 can be or is likely to be understood by reference to the phrase denoted by STRING-B in INFO-2 within the context of some NLDocument. INFO-1 will most often be denoted by an NLSentence denoting function which specifies the document in which the sentence occurs and STRING-A occurs as a part of the sentence. Likewise for INFO-2 and STRING-B.
label: Info Understood By Reference To Info
infoUnderstoodByReferenceToInfo

comment: (objectID ?OBJ ?MAP ?ID) states that ?OBJ has the associated ?ID according to the mapping ?MAP. Example: (objectID #$Goolsbey US-SSN-Mapping '444-88-9999')
label: Object ID
objectID
Requested Forward
requestedForward
comment: (requestedForward ASSRT) means that some Cyclist requested that the direction of the CycLAssertion ASSRT be turned on forward. By default, rules are required to be stated with backward direction, nonetheless it often seems that a certain rule would be more useful or effective if stated as forward. This predicate is designed to enable easier tracking of such cases.

(smallestSubSystemUnderTraversal SUB SYS TRAV) means that SUB is the smallest subsystem of SYS such that TRAV is a traversal in SUB. (See SubSystemUnderTraversalFn, traversalInSystem and pointClosedSubSystems) Note that 'smallest' here means that no link LINK between X and Y in SYS is a link in SUB if neither (TraversalFn (TheList X LINK Y)) nor (TraversalFn (TheList Y LINK X)) is a subTraversals of TRAV. Note also that since SUB is a point-closed subsystem of SYS, every point in SYS that is on TRAV (see pointOnTraversal) is a point in SUB. Note finally that since SUB is the 'smallest' subsystem of SYS in which TRAV is a traversal, SUB must be a ConnectedPathSystem.
label: Smallest Sub System Under Traversal
smallestSubSystemUnderTraversal
Repropagate Assertion
repropagateAssertion
comment: (repropagateAssertion ASSERTION) tells the system to repropogate the CycLAssertion ASSERTION. Note that repropagateAssertion is an instance of ELRelation_OneWay, and so (repropagateAssertion ASSERTION) expands to (performSubL (ExpandSubLFn (ASSERTION) (pwhen (forward-assertion? ASSERTION) (repropagate-forward-assertion ASSERTION))).

label: First LVAD Insert For Operation With Device Type At Date
firstLVADInsertForOperationWithDeviceTypeAtDate

comment: (distributionOfTypeAlongPath TYPE PATH DIST) is true when instances of TYPE are laid along PATH, each at a distance of DIST from the next. For example, (distributionOfTypeAlongPath Streetlight ViaVeneto (Meter 20)) is true just in case there is a street light in Via Veneto every twenty meters. Note that PATH need not be a Path_Simple (it could be a loop).
label: Distribution Of Type Along Path
distributionOfTypeAlongPath

comment: (comparativeAdvantageInProduction GEO-AGENT REGION PRODUCT-TYPE) means that, of every GeopoliticalEntity with territory in REGION, GEO-AGENT has the lowest opportunity cost in producing a unit of PRODUCT-TYPE (see opportunityCostForAgent).
label: comparative advantage in production
comparativeAdvantageInProduction

comment: (formulaTemplateArgExplanation TEMPLATE TOPIC POS STRING) means that, when dealing with TOPIC, STRING is a detailed explanation for argument position POS in TEMPLATE.
label: Formula Template Arg Explanation
formulaTemplateArgExplanation

comment: eventSubdivisionType(E ET NUM) means that temporal thing [TemporalThing] E is subdivided into a sequence of exactly NUM temporal things of type ET. Each temporal thing in the sequence is contiguousBefore the next one in the sequence. The first in the sequence starts E and the last one finishes E.
label: Event Subdivision Type
eventSubdivisionType

comment: (relationInstanceExistsCount PRED THING COL N) means there exist exactly N instances (INS_1, INS_2, ..., INS_N) of COL such that THING stands in relation PRED to each of them, i.e. (PRED THING INS_1), (PRED THING INS_2), ..., (PRED THING INS_N), all hold. Thus it is equivalent to the more complex form (thereExistExactly NUM ?INST (and (isa ?INST COL) (PRED THING ?INST))). So a ground atomic formula (or "GAF") built upon relationInstanceExistsCount is in effect shorthand (i.e. a "macro") for an equivalent rule with the more complex quantified form. For example, (relationInstanceExistsCount geographicalSubRegions Iran OilField 3) means that Iran has exactly three oil fields. See the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Instance Exists Count
relationInstanceExistsCount

comment: (terrainAdvantage_SideDegree LOC SIDE ADV-AMT) means that the location LOC has the tactical potential to provide the degree of TacticalAdvantage ADV-AMT to SIDE. For example, (terrainAdvantage_SideDegree Hill28 OffendingForce (HighAmountFn TacticalAdvantage)) means that Hill28 has the potential to offer the OffendingForce a high degree of TacticalAdvantage. Note that TacticalAdvantages depend not just on terrain characteristics, but also on force and situation characteristics, and therefore belong to agents in fairly specific classes of real or potential military operations. For this reason, assertions stating the terrainAdvantage_SideDegree for some piece of terrain should be made only within appropriately scenario-specific contexts.
label: Terrain Advantage Side Degree
terrainAdvantage-SideDegree

comment: This relation is the predicate corresponding to FieldAppliedToFn. Specifically, (subFieldsAppliedTo FIELD SUBFIELD TOPIC) means that SUBFIELD is the subFields of FIELD which is devoted to the study of TOPIC.
label: Sub Fields Applied To
subFieldsAppliedTo

comment:
(providesMotiveFor INDIV AGT SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that INDIV provides AGT with a motive for acting in the specified way -- i.e., for playing ROLE in an instance of SIT-TYPE. INDIV will typically be a Situation or a state of affairs (expressed by a CycLSentence_Assertible).

Note that this predicate does not take a particular action as its third argument. It is not used to specify AGT's motive for participating in some actual event (for this, use purposeInEvent or reasonsForAction). Also, note that one can have a 'motive' to do A without ever having the corresponding goal or desire to do it. E.g., AGT might have a motive to kill his business partner (perhaps being cheated in a business deal) even if AGT never actually desires to do this. This is one sense of 'motive' discussed in criminal law contexts -- INDIV provides AGT with a reason to play ROLE in SIT-TYPE, i.e., is the sort of event which often does and/or which reasonably could lead an agent to do this.
label: Provides Motive For
providesMotiveFor

comment: (productTypeFacilitates OBJ-TYPE SIT-TYPE ROLE) holds just in case instances of OBJ-TYPE make it easier (in some sense) to play ROLE in instances of SIT-TYPE. For example, (productTypeFacilitates CreditCard FinancingByBorrowing borrower) holds because having a credit card makes it easier to be the borrower in an instance of FinancingByBorrowing -- you just use the card, there is no need for you to fill out any form to get the money to make the purchase/cash withdrawal.
label: Product Type Facilitates
productTypeFacilitates

comment: (sceneConditionedOnSentenceTruth SCRIPT SCENE SENTENCE) means that a particular instance of SCRIPT will contain an instance of SCENE as a subSituations if the conditions represented by SENTENCE are met.
label: Scene Conditioned On Sentence Truth
sceneConditionedOnSentenceTruth

comment: (brightnessInRange BRIGHT VALUE-1 VALUE-2) means that BRIGHT is a MunsellBrightness with a value somewhere between VALUE-1 and VALUE-2 on the Munsell scale of brightness. Munsell brightnesses are represented using MunsellBrightnessFn. For further information, please see MunsellBrightness and the #$SharedNoteOnMunsellSystemOfColorClassification.
label: Brightness In Range
brightnessInRange

comment: (genTemplate_Constrained RELN CONSTRAINT PHRASE) means that if CONSTRAINT is true, then PHRASE is one way to paraphrase a CycL formula whose arg0 is RELN. CONSTRAINT will typically be stated in terms of generic argument keywords such as :ARG1 and :ARG2, which correspond to arguments in the formula to be paraphrased.
label: Gen Template Constrained
genTemplate-Constrained

comment: This specialization of foreignKeyMap entails an additional constraint on deleting or modifying the rows of the referenced schema. That is (foreignKeyMap_Restrict REFERENCED_SCHEMA REFERENCED_KEY REFERENCING_SCHEMA REFERENCING_FIELD_LIST) means in addition to the constraints inherited from foreignKeyMap, deleting a row of REFERENCED_SCHEMA is not permitted if there is any row of REFERENCING_SCHEMA which references it. Contrast this behavior with foreignKeyMap_Cascade, foreignKeyMap_SetNull, and foreignKeyMap_SetDefault.
label: Foreign Key Map Restrict
foreignKeyMap-Restrict

comment: (sameBinaryRelation OBJ1 OBJ2 PRED JUST) states that an argument for OBJ1 and OBJ2 being analogous is that they are both related by predicate PRED to analogous objects. The justification for the analogous objects is the expression JUST. See also commonalities and sameThing for other vocabulary for expressing the justification of an analogy.
label: Same Binary Relation
sameBinaryRelation

comment: (stateOfDeviceInSituation SIT DEV STATE) means that during the Situation SIT the PhysicalDevice DEV is in the DeviceTypeByState STATE.
label: State Of Device In Situation
stateOfDeviceInSituation

comment: (creationByMethod EX-TYPE METHOD CREATE-TYPE) means that CREATE-TYPE is the collection of creation events in which things of type EX-TYPE are created using the method METHOD. For example, (creationByMethod Table_PieceOfFurniture Assembling FOO) means that FOO is is the collection of events in which instances of Table_PieceOfFurniture are created by Assembling.
label: Creation By Method
creationByMethod

comment: A predicate used to state the bid market price of a particular share of a certain company's Stock (of a particular class, e.g. common or preferred) at a given time. (stockPrice_Ask STOCK PRICE DATE EXCHANGE) means that PRICE is the highest price per share that any prospective buyer of stock in STOCK is willing to pay at DATE on the exchange EXCHANGE. Cf. stockPrice_Ask.
label: bid price
stockPrice-Bid

comment: explanatoryTypeFromContext THING TYPE CONTEXT, is used as part of #$ScenarioGenerationProject to represent the fact that THING is hypothesized because another instance of the same TYPE as THING was hypothesized in CONTEXT. explanatoryTypeFromContext is used within 'meta-expansion modules' (e.g., #$GainingControlScriptConnectorMeta-ExpansionModule) which make hypotheses based on other other hypotheses in order to form more unified hypotheses.
label: Explanatory Type From Context
explanatoryTypeFromContext

comment: (plausibleSentence SENTENCE) means that a reviewer who looked at the CycLPropositionalSentence SENTENCE felt that the information content of the sentence is (subjectively) "likely," given the system's current knowledge. This is not to say that the content of SENTENCE is *correct* - for example, (isa #$Cynthia Married) is plausible, but incorrect. This distinction depends on the context within which the judgement is being made, and is necessarily subjective. See also implausibleSentence.
label: Plausible Sentence
plausibleSentence

comment: This predicate is a specialization of physicalFieldTranslation which translates 'literal' or 'virtual' physicalfield values into 'virtual' physical field values. Here, a 'literal' physical field is one that is actually present in the underlying knowledge source, whereas a 'virtual' physical field is constructed in the mapping process. See also the dual relation physicalFieldEncoding.
label: Physical Field Decoding
physicalFieldDecoding
Will Always Be
willAlwaysBe
comment: willAlwaysBe is a ModalOperator, commonly referred to as a `future-tense operator'. For each #$ELSentence-Assertible PROP, (willAlwaysBe PROP) means that it will always be the case that PROP. For example, (willAlwaysBe `Amy and Bob are friends') means that Amy and Bob will always be friends. willAlwaysBe has a dualOperator: willBe. Note that (willAlwaysBe PROP) implies neither PROP nor (not PROP). Note also that to symbolize sentences like `Amy and Bob will never be friends', use (willAlwaysBe (not `Amy and Bob are friends')). Note, finally, that willAlwaysBe should be used only in instances of TemporalMicrotheory. Strictly speaking, (willAlwaysBe PROP) is true in a temporal microtheory MT with time index t and time parameter p (two `dimensions' in the context space, see mtTimeIndex and mtTimeIndexWithParameter) iff PROP is true in every temporal microtheory MT' with time index t < t' and time parameter p', which has the same values of all other dimensions as MT. Here t < t' means (startsAfterEndingOf t' t). It is easy to verify that (willAlwaysBe PROP) is true in a temporal microtheory MT with time index t and time parameter p iff PROP is true in the temporal microtheory MT' with time index (IntervalStartedByFn t) and time parameter TimePoint, which has the same values of all other dimensions as MT. (See other plain tense operators hasAlwaysBeen, willBe and was, and metric tense predicates was_Metric and willBe_Metric etc.)

An instance of TernaryPredicate. (expatriateCommunityOfTypeInRegion COMMUNITY TYPE AREA) relates COMMUNITY, an instance of ExpatriateCommunity, to the instance of PersonTypeByCulture, TYPE, that comprises COMMUNITY in AREA. Instances of ExpatriateCommunity are groups of people, whose members live in close proximity in AREA and make up a viable unit within AREA such that AREA is not the native country for the majority of COMMUNITY's members.

For example, (expatriateCommunityOfTypeInRegion ExpatCommunity001 EthiopianPerson France) means that ExpatCommunity001 is located in France and it is a community of EthiopianPersons.

That the members of COMMUNITY are originally from the same place, which is different from AREA, provides cohesion to COMMUNITY. Note that 'originally from' is a vague concept. The children born within COMMUNITY may or may not identify with the culture of origin. See also ExpatriateCommunityOfTypeInRegionFn.
label: Expatriate Community Of Type In Region
expatriateCommunityOfTypeInRegion

comment: A ternary predicate that relates a given event to the number of deaths it caused within a specified population. (deathToll EVENT ORGTYPE N) means that N instances of ORGTYPE (some specialization of Organism_Whole) either died in the course of EVENT itself or died as an immediate and direct result of EVENT. Thus, both (deathToll #$BombingOfNagasaki HomoSapiens 40000) and (deathToll IrradiationCausedByBombingOfNagasaki HomoSapiens 100000) are (at least approximately) true.
label: death toll
deathToll

comment: This predicate expresses the relationship between a light verb, the word which co-occurs with the light verb to make an expression, and the semantic interpretation of that phrase.
label: Light Verb Transitive Sem Trans
lightVerb-TransitiveSemTrans

comment: An assertion of the form (allotmentReservesQuantityOfCollectionForInterval ALLOT QUANT COLLECTION INTERVAL) is used to describe a reservation on some resource. In this case, the Allotment ALLOT reserves the Quantity QUANT from every instance of the SetOrCollection COLLECTION during the ContinuousTimeInterval INTERVAL.
label: Allotment Reserves Quantity Of Collection For Interval
allotmentReservesQuantityOfCollectionForInterval

comment: (pcwInformationAbout PCW TOPIC ABOUT-MT) means that the expressions contained in ABOUT-MT capture the portion of the propositional content of PCW that is focally 'about' TOPIC (in the sense of the predicate containsInformationAbout_Focally, qv.).
label: Pcw Information About
pcwInformationAbout

comment: (regionIsEcotoneForEcosystemTypes REGION ECO-TYPE1 ECO-TYPE2) means that the GeographicalRegion REGION is an Ecotone for an Ecosystem of ECO-TYPE1 and for an Ecosystem of ECO-TYPE2, in the sense that it lies between the boundaries of both systems, and is home to many agents in both.
label: ecotone
regionIsEcotoneForEcosystemTypes

comment: (relationAllSpecsExists PRED COL1 COL2) means that for every SUBCOL1 which is a subcollection of COL1, there exists some INS2 which is an instance of COL2, such that (PRED SUBCOL1 INS2) holds.
label: Relation All Specs Exists
relationAllSpecsExists

comment: (forbidden_SitRolePlayerOfType SIT ROLE FORBIDDEN-TYPE) means that no instance of FORBIDDEN-TYPE should play ROLE in SIT. In other words, there should be no FORBIDDEN-INS such that (ROLE SIT FORBIDDEN-INS). Assertions involving this predicate -- which specify what should not be the case -- should be made in a normative context, e.g., one that reflects the contents of a particular CodeOfConduct. Usually, SIT will be subject to such a prohibition in virtue of satisfying some general description, e.g., one stated in the antecedent of a CycLRuleAssertion.
label: Forbidden Sit Role Player Of Type
forbidden-SitRolePlayerOfType

comment: (actsInOfficialCapacityForIn AGENT GOVERNMENT ACT) holds when AGENT acts in a official capacity for GOVERNMENT during ACT.
label: Acts In Official Capacity For In
actsInOfficialCapacityForIn

comment: (doRedirectDNSFrom HACKER MANNER NS COMP) means that, from COMP and in manner MANNER, HACKER exploits the functionality of a name server program in such a way that the program looking at the DNS table on NS directs traffic in a way other than intended by the designer of the network NS is on. See alos doRedirectDNS.
label: Do Redirect DNS From
doRedirectDNSFrom

comment: A FunctionalPredicate that relates conceptual works, agents that interpret them, and a time to the propositions that are in the interpretations. <tt>(contextOfPCWInterpretation PCW CONTEXT AGENT TIME)</tt> means that CONTEXT is the context that contains all the propositions endorsed by AGENT on the record (and their closure) at TIME as part of the inteprpretation of PCW.
label: Context Of PCW Interpretation
contextOfPCWInterpretation

comment: (genlInverseWRTTypes BINPRED1 BINPRED2 COL1 COL2) means that if (BINPRED1 INS1 INS2) where INS1 is an instance of COL1 and INS2 is an instance of COL2, then (BINPRED2 INS2 INS1). See genlPredsWRTTypes for examples of usage.
label: Genl Inverse WRT Types
genlInverseWRTTypes

comment: An instance of both FunctionalPredicate and QuintaryPredicate. (effectiveConcentrationForOrganismType SUBSTANCE-TYPE EFFECT-TYPE PERCENTAGE ORGANISM CONCENTRATION) means that exposure to CONCENTRATION of SUBSTANCE-TYPE will produce EFFECT-TYPE in PERCENTAGE of ORGANISM-TYPE.
label: effective concentration
effectiveConcentrationForOrganismType

comment: A sentence of the form (candidateNCScoreForRuleWithThresholds RULE RATIO THRESHOLD1 THRESHOLD2) states that for the NounCompoundRule RULE, RATIO represents the represents the success ratio for some (implicit) evaluation of the rule (cf. datedCandidateNCTestHasResults). In this case, THRESHOLD1 and THRESHOLD2 represent (respectively) the hit threshold required to count a candidate compound string or a candidate head or modifier string as well-evinced in the search (i.e. as a "success").
label: Candidate NC Score For Rule With Thresholds
candidateNCScoreForRuleWithThresholds

comment: (sendDataOfTypeToProgramOnSystem AGENT INFO PROG SYSTEM) means that AGENT sends INFO to the program PROG running on SYSTEM.
label: Send Data Of Type To Program On System
sendDataOfTypeToProgramOnSystem

comment: (userSkippedSentence SENTENCE) means that some user of an automated review tool skipped SENTENCE, either by pushing a 'skip' button or by simply not answering the question.
label: User Skipped Sentence
userSkippedSentence

comment: (interArgNotReln PRED M N RELN) means that a GAF with PRED as its arg0 can only be asserted if the BinaryPredicate RELN is known _not_ to hold between the Mth and Nth arguments to PRED in the GAF, with the Mth argument appearing as the first argument of RELN and the Nth argument appearing as the second argument of RELN.
label: Inter Arg Not Reln
interArgNotReln

comment: (interArgNotIsa4_5 PRED COL1 COL2) means that, when an instance of COL1 appears as the fourth argument to PRED, the fifth argument in that assertion is constrained to not be an instance of COL2 and vice versa.
label: Inter Arg Not Isa 4 5
interArgNotIsa4-5

comment: (behaviorIncapable_CapabilityCompromised OBJ SITTYPE ROLE) means that OBJ is incapable of playing ROLE in any instance of SITTYPE, as a consequence of malfunctioning or being a defective instance of its type. Thus, (behaviorIncapable_CapabilityCompromised EddieTheAdultEagle Flying_FlappingWings doneBy) means that EddieTheAdultEagle is incapable of flying, though this must be due to some particular thing being wrong with Eddie, since it is generally true that ((TypeCapableFn behaviorCapable) Eagle Flying_FlappingWings doneBy) . Cf. behaviorIncapable and functionalityCompromised.
label: Behavior Incapable Capability Compromised
behaviorIncapable-CapabilityCompromised

comment: (owlExportTermFromContextsWithIsaFilters SET-OF-MTS SET-OF-COLS THING) means that THING is a term suitable for OWL export because it is mentioned in an assertion in one of the contexts in SET-OF-MTS, and is not an instance of any collection that is an element of SET-OF-COLS.
label: Owl Export Term From Contexts With Isa Filters
owlExportTermFromContextsWithIsaFilters

comment: If agent ARG1 uses the item ARG2, then the agent is capable (all other capabilities allowing) of performing instances of the collection ARG3.
label: Enables Event Of Type
enablesEventOfType

comment: (distalToFrom PART-1 PART-2 REF-POINT) means that the PartiallyTangible (often an AnimalBodyRegion) PART-1 lies in a DistalDirection of PART-2, from the point of reference REF-POINT (an AnimalBodyPart -- generally, of a Person). PART-1 and PART-2 are parts of the same body. For example, (distalToFrom FredsThumb FredsElbow FredsTorso) expresses the fact that Fred's thumb is further away from his torso than his elbow is. Note that PART-2 is therefore proximal to PART-1; thus, no distinct predicate is needed to represent `proximal to'
label: Distal To From
distalToFrom

comment: A predicate relating instances of ServerProgram to the port numbers (and transport layer protocols) on which they customarily listen. (portForProgram PROGRAM PROTOCOL PORT) means that running copies of versions of PROGRAM customarily listen on PORT for packets that conform to PROTOCOL. See also portForProgramType.
label: Port For Program
portForProgram

comment: (constantNameAutoGeneratedFromCollection CONSTANT COLLECTION NAME) means that NAME, a present or former name for CONSTANT was automatically generated from COLLECTION.
label: Constant Name Auto Generated From Collection
constantNameAutoGeneratedFromCollection

comment: (realGNPGrowthRateDuring GE THING NR) means that NR is the growth rate of the GeopoliticalEntity GE's real (adjusted for inflation) gross national product during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (THING will often be a calendar time period.) That is, NR is the quotient of the difference between GE's gross national product for the temporal extent of THING and GE's gross national product for the time interval immediately preceding, and of the same duration as, THING (as dividend) and GE's gross national product for the time interval immediately preceding, and of the same duration as, THING (as divisor). For example, to express the fact that Oman's real gross national product growth rate for 1997 was 5.9%, we can say (realGNPGrowthRateDuring Oman (YearFn 1997) .059). See also grossNationalProduct.
label: Real GNP Growth Rate During
realGNPGrowthRateDuring

comment: A quintary instance of InterArgConstraintPredicate (q.v.). (interArgInsIsa RELN k INDEP-INS n DEP-COL) means that, in order for any atomic sentence formed by RELN to be true, if INDEP-INS appears as the k-th argument to RELN, the n-th argument must be a member of DEP-COL. For example, (interArgInsIsa willBe_Metric_CalendarTime 1 CalendarYear 3 TimeOfYearType) means that in order for (willBe_Metric_CalendarTime X k Y PROP) to be true, X is (identical to) CalendarYear only if Y is a member of the collection TimeOfYearType. For a more general explanation of independent and dependent arguments in the present sense, see InterArgConstraintPredicate.
label: Inter Arg Ins Isa
interArgInsIsa

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate that relates a Collection to a ScalarIntervalSlot to a ScalarInterval. (minimumValueForTypeWRTSlot COL SLOT MIN) means that every instance of COL stands in SLOT to a scalar interval greater than or equal to MIN. That is, it is shorthand for the following rule: 
(implies
  (and
    (isa ?THING COL)
    (SLOT ?THING ?QUANT))
  (greaterThanOrEqualTo ?QUANT MIN)).
See also maximumValueForTypeWRTSlot.
label: Minimum Value For Type WRT Slot
minimumValueForTypeWRTSlot

comment: (deadweightLossOfTax MARKET PRODUCT TAX LOSS) identifies LOSS as the monetary loss from the sum of the consumer surplus (see consumerSurplusAtQuantityOfProductType) and the producer surplus (see producerSurplusAtQuantityOfProductType) caused by a tax of amount TAX on PRODUCT in MARKET.
label: deadweight loss
deadweightLossOfTax

comment: (colorRangeOfType TYPE COLOR-1 COLOR-2) means that all instances of TYPE have some color between COLOR-1 and COLOR-2. For example, (colorRangeOfType Granite DarkGrayishOlive_Color GrayishPink_Color) means that individual pieces of granite will have a color somewhere between dark grayish olive and grayish pink. The meaning of 'between' here is determined by the Munsell system of color classification. Each color in this system has distinct values for brightness, chroma, and hue. The range specified by colorRangeOfType is described by three intervals: its brightness extends from the brightness of the darker color to the brighter one, and its chroma extends from the less saturated color to the richer one. The matter of hue is a bit more complex, because hue has a cyclic rather than linear order. The rules governing colorRangeOfType will assume the range of hue will extend from arg2 to arg3. So (colorRangeOfType TYPE PurpleColor RedColor) specifies a range of hues from purple through magenta all the way to red, but (colorRangeOfType TYPE RedColor PurpleColor) specifies a range that goes 'all the way around the color wheel' from red to orange, yellow, green, blue, and purple again - excluding only magenta. Therefore, exercise caution in ordering COLOR-1 and COLOR-2. Please see MunsellHue for information on how the hues are ordered. For further information about color values, see MunsellBrightness, MunsellChroma, and #$SharedNoteOnMunsellSystemOfColorClassification.
label: Color Range Of Type
colorRangeOfType

comment: A TernaryPredicate that relates a PartiallyTangible to an Event to a set of ForceVectors. (setOfForcesActingOnObjectIn PT EVT SET) means that each element of SET is a ForceVector acting on PT throughout EVT, and that no other ForceVectors act on PT at any time during EVT. In other words, SET represents a "full account" of the forces acting on PT in EVT.
label: Set Of Forces Acting On Object In
setOfForcesActingOnObjectIn

lightSource

comment:
(distributesOutOfArg <reln> <pred> <n>) is a directive to the canonicalizer that relation <reln> distrbutes out of a predicate <pred> when it appears as the top-most relation in the predicate's arg <n>. Specifically, it denotes (distributesOutOfArg <reln> <pred> <n>) denotes that the canonicalizer will translate

(<pred> <arg-1> ... <arg-n-1> (<reln> <arg-n1> <arg-n2> ... <arg-nm>) <arg-n+1> ..)

into

(<reln> (<pred> <arg-1> ... <arg-n-1> <arg-n1> <arg-n+1> ...) (<pred> <arg-1> ... <arg-n-1> <arg-n2> <arg-n+1> ...) ... (<pred> <arg-1> ... <arg-n-1> <arg-nm> <arg-n+1> ...))
label: Distributes Out Of Arg
distributesOutOfArg

comment:
This predicate is used to state that the value of a quantity slot decreases for a fixed object throughout an event. (decreasesThroughoutEvent SLOT THING EVENT) is true if and only if for every pair of sub-events SUB1 and SUB2 of EVENT there exist values VAL1 and VAL2 such that if 
(and
  (startsAfterEndingOf SUB1 SUB2)
  (holdsIn SUB1 (SLOT THING VAL1))
  (holdsIn SUB2 (SLOT THING VAL2)))
it follows that 
(greaterThanOrEqualTo VAL2 VAL1)
is true. See also increasesThroughoutEvent and constantThroughoutEvent.

comment: (quantityInfluenceFunctionStrength TIME THING QUANTITY-SLOT FUNCTION-TYPE STRENGTH) means that during TIME the value of QUANTITY-SLOT for successive time slices of THING is subjected to some influence. The strength of this influence is specified by STRENGTH. The higher the STRENGTH of a given influence, the more likely that the time course of actual changes in QUANTITY-SLOT during TIME will follow the shape that elements of FUNCTION-TYPE have. If two influences are present, the actual time course of QUANTITY-SLOT follows resembles the shape of its corresponding FUNCTION-TYPE most. When STRENGTH is unknown or irrelevant use quantityInfluenceFunction. See quantityChangeFunction for making statements about the *actual* time course of some quantity. See also #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for important pointers to related vocabulary.
label: Quantity Influence Function Strength
quantityInfluenceFunctionStrength

comment: (launchFromERHasStationCompromisedWRTCapability OP FACILITY FUNC-TYPE OBJ) means that the rocket launch operation OP involves a range station FACILITY whose functionality, FUNC-TYPE is compromised in a manner that impacts the implementation of OP, due to a problem with OBJ.

launchFromERHasStationCompromisedWRTCapability-WithRoot

comment: A MetaPredicate used for stating that a given predicate behaves transitively, in a specified argument-place, with respect to a given binary predicate. (transitiveViaArg PRED BINPRED N) means that the Nth argument position of PRED is "transitive" with respect to BINPRED. That is, if (PRED ... ARG-N ...) and (BINPRED ARG-N ARG-N-PRIME) hold, then so does (PRED ... ARG-N-PRIME ...). For example, (transitiveViaArg relationAllExists genlPreds 1) holds; thus from (relationAllExists anatomicalParts Mammal Head_AnimalBodyPart) and (genlPreds anatomicalParts physicalParts) it follows that (relationAllExists physicalParts Mammal Head_AnimalBodyPart). See also transitiveViaArgInverse.
label: Transitive Via Arg
transitiveViaArg

comment: (correctlyParsedSentence SENTENCE) means that a reviewer who looked at the CycLPropositionalSentence SENTENCE felt that the information content of the sentence has been correctly parsed from a text source, given the system's current knowledge. This is not to say that the content of SENTENCE is *correct* or *true* - for example, (isa #$Cynthia Married) is correctly parsed from 'Cyndy is married.', but incorrect. This distinction depends on the context within which the judgement is being made, and is necessarily subjective. See also incorrectlyParsedSentence.
label: Correctly Parsed Sentence
correctlyParsedSentence

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relationship with respect to two collections. (relationAllExistsRange BINPRED COL1 COL2 RANGE) means that for any instance INST of COL1 there are between the minimum and maximum of RANGE (see NonNegativeIntegerRange) many instances INST(i) of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST INST(i)) holds. This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 
(implies
  (isa ?INST COL1)
  (thereExistRange RANGE ?INST-I
    (and
      (isa ?INST-I COL2)
      (PRED ?INST ?INST-I)))) .
For example, '(relationAllExistsRange anatomicalParts Dog Hair_Strand Many_Quant)' means that dogs have many hairs. Cf. relationExistsRangeAll, and see #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation All Exists Range
relationAllExistsRange

comment: (aggregateSituationTypeByRole SIT-TYPE ROLE AG-TYPE) means that AG-TYPE is a collection of situations, each instance of which is an aggregate of 2 or more instances of SIT-TYPE in which different objects play ROLE.

For example, Milk, as measured by volume (i.e., by the predicate volumeOfObject), costs about US $3 per gallon.

comment: (immediateRisk EVENT AGENT RESULT-SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that if (doneBy EVENT AGENT), then EVENT contributes to AGENT being at immediate risk for playing the role ROLE in a situation of type SIT-TYPE as a result. See also promotesRisk for less immediate risks, like getting cancer.

immediateRisk

comment:
(specPredOfPredicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg PREDICATE POS-1 N POS-2 M) means that there exists an instance SPECPRED of Predicate such that:

(genlPreds SPECPRED PREDICATE), and

(predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg SPECPRED POS-1 N POS-2 M).

As such, SPECPRED is an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate. Since the complete extent of Predicate is not known, SPECPRED might not be reified in Cyc; specPredOfPredicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg thus allows us to use lexical and commonsense data to hypothesize the existence of a SenseExtendingPredicate. For example, conceptuallyRelated is often used to relate two concepts denoted by the same word (e.g., Dancing and Dance_Party, both of which are denoted by #$Dance-TheWord (with different parts-of-speech). However, conceptuallyRelated serves often as a promissory note, indicating the existence of a more specific relation that hasn't be represented in the KB yet. If (conceptuallyRelated VERB-DENOTATION COUNT-NOUN-DENOTATION) can be proved for enough pairs of values for VERB-DENOTATION and COUNT-NOUN-DENOTATION, this could license concluding 
(specPredOfPredicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg conceptuallyRelated Verb 1 CountNoun 2),
effectively launching a sense-extension hypothesis (c.f., SenseExtensionHypothesisMicrotheory) in which there exists a spec-pred of conceptuallyRelated that does license this sort of sense-extension. For more information, see predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg.
label: Spec Pred Of Predicate Licenses Sense Extension From POS In Arg To POS In Arg
specPredOfPredicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg

comment: (typesDifferInQuantity COL1 COL2 QUANT-TYPE) means that instances of COL1 will differ from instances of COL2 in terms of the value of QUANT-TYPE that they respectively hold.
label: Types Differ In Quantity
typesDifferInQuantity

This predicate does not provide the match itself, if one needs details they must be recomputed.  It does provide the score, for sorting and filtering purposes.

comment: (precedesInGraphicalStructure WHOLE PART1 PART2) means that, within the GraphicalStructure WHOLE, the GraphicalStructure PART1 comes before the GraphicalStructure PART2. There are certain types of GraphicalStructure that always precede certain other types of GraphicalStructure within an inclusive GraphicalStructure. For example, within a CWStructure, an instance of TableOfContents always precedesInGraphicalStructure an instance of TextString that it is an alphabeticalIndexTo.

precedesInGraphicalStructure

comment: (forbidden_SitRelationToType SIT BIN-PRED FORBIDDEN-TYPE) means that there should be no instance FORBIDDEN-INS of FORBIDDEN-TYPE such that (BIN-PRED SIT FORBIDDEN-INS). forbidden_SitRelationToType is a very general prohibition predicate most useful for querying. Statements of prohibitions should usually employ specializations of this predicate. E.g., if BIN-PRED is an instance of BinaryRolePredicate, use forbidden_SitRolePlayerOfType. If FORBIDDEN-INS is a type of Situation (e.g., one no instance of which may be a subEvents of SIT), use forbidden_SitRelationToSitType.

forbidden-SitRelationToType

comment: (verbSemTransTemplate_Canonical COL FRAME PRED-LIST) means that the translation of any verb denotation of a word denoting a specialization of COL, appearing with subcategorization frame FRAME, is the canonical template for that denotation with FRAME and PRED-LIST.

verbSemTransTemplate-Canonical

comment: (relationExistsSpecAll SLOT COL1 COL2) means that for every INS2 which is a instance of COL2, there is some SUBCOL1 which is a subcollection of COL1, such that (SLOT SUBCOL1 INS2) holds.
label: Relation Exists Spec All
