comment: interArgResultGenl_Asserted is a quaternary instance of MetaRelation. It is used to state that a certain complex and partly genls -based relationship holds between a given argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned when the function is applied to the argument. (interArgResultGenl_Asserted FUNC N INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when a term that is asserted to be a specialization of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the Nth argument to FUNC, then (regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be) the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is a specialization of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is asserted to be a specialization of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG(1) ... ARG(N-1) INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is a specialization of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike interArgResultGenl assertions, interArgResultGenl_Asserted assertions will not support assertions of the form (genls VALUE DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) unless it is asserted in the Cyc KB that (genls COL INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL).
label: Inter Arg Result Genl Asserted
interArgResultGenl-Asserted

comment: An assertion of the form (existentialActorType ROLE-SPEC TYPE) is used to represent the existence of actors of the type TYPE within the role represented by the RoleSpecification ROLE-SPEC. If ROLE-SPEC is a RoleSpecification_SubSitType, given the assertions (sitTypeHasSpecification SIT-TYPE ROLE-SPEC) , (specificationSubSitType ROLE-SPEC SUB-TYPE), (specificationRole ROLE-SPEC ROLE), and (specificationStage ROLE-SPEC STAGE), then in any instance of SIT-TYPE in any subsituation of type SUB-TYPE that bears the relation situationFallsUnderStage to the TemporalStageSpecification STAGE, then there exists an instance of TYPE that plays ROLE in that subsituation
label: Existential Actor Type
existentialActorType

comment: (minimumDurationForSubSituationType SIT-TYPE SUB-SIT-TYPE MIN) means that if a situation SUB-SIT is an instance of SUB-SIT-TYPE and is a proper subsituation of SIT, an instance of SIT-TYPE, then SUB-SIT will not last less than MIN.
label: Minimum Duration For Sub Situation Type
minimumDurationForSubSituationType

comment: A type-level version of primaryFunction. (typePrimaryFunction_AgnosticIntentional AGTTYPE SITTYPE ROLE) means that in ordinary or normal circumstances, instances of AGTTYPE have playing ROLE in situations of type SITTYPE as their most important function in some immediate functional context. Like primaryFunction, the relation is agnostic as to whether the functionality derives from the intent of some intentional designer: i.e., the relation is not a spec-pred of typeIntendedBehaviorCapable. This is not to say that usage of typePrimaryFunction_AgnosticIntentional implies that no design exists: the relation is simply agnostic as to whether a design exists or not. For this reason typePrimaryFunction is deemed to be a specialization. In cases where SITTYPE is itself a FunctionalSystem (say, a kind of Cell or a kind of Organization in the FunctionalRoleAnalysisMt), SITTYPE itself specifies the functional context: otherwise, this context is taken to be specified by the Microtheory in which the assertion is made.
label: Type Primary Function Agnostic Intentional
typePrimaryFunction-AgnosticIntentional

comment: (skillRequired ACT-TYPE OTHER-TYPE PERF-LEVEL) means that if one is to successfully perform an instance of some kind of action (ACT-TYPE), then one must be capable of performing instances of another kind of action (OTHER-TYPE) with the performance attribute at a level at least equal to PERF-LEVEL . For example, (skillRequired PlayingVolleyball ServingAVolleyball (LowAmountFn Competence)) holds just in case playing volleyball requires at least a low amount of competence in serving a volleyball.
label: required skill
skillRequired

comment: queryTemplate relates a class of natural language queries (e.g. sentences) to CycL. For example, (queryTemplate STemplate ("what color are" (NPTemplate :obj)) (colorOfType :obj ?X)) would map "what color are frogs?" to (colorOfType Frog ?X).
label: Query Template
queryTemplate

comment: This predicate is used to state sksi 'conditional meaning sentences', i.e. meaning sentences which include an additional query (either a boolean check or with unbound variables) that is asked to check the applicability of a meaning sentence, or to limit its scope. (conditionalMeaningSentenceOfSchema LS1 SENTENCE1 LS2 SENTENCE2) means that SENTENCE2 is a meaning sentence for LS2 only if SENTENCE1 is true in the context of LS1. For example, if we have asserted (conditionalMeaningSentenceOfSchema #$OFAC-main-LS (isa (TheFn PartiallyTangible) Watercraft) #$OFAC-main-LS (massOfObject (TheFn PartiallyTangible) (TheFn Mass))) in the (MappingMtFn #$OFAC-KS), then any query in (ContentMtFn #$OFAC-main-KS) that includes a massOfObject clause will result in bindings from the database that also satisfy the condition (isa ?FOO Watercraft). However note that this additional restriction only applies to the database query. It does not affect the answers which may return from other tactics.
label: Conditional Meaning Sentence Of Schema
conditionalMeaningSentenceOfSchema

comment: (netIncomeForPeriod ORG MONEY TIME) means MONEY is the net income of ORG during TIME.
label: Net Income For Period
netIncomeForPeriod
Pred Trivial For Justification Paraphrase
predTrivialForJustificationParaphrase
comment: (predTrivialForJustificationParaphrase PRED) means that when PRED is the arg0 in a support for a proof, a paraphrase of that proof need not explicitly mention that support, as a human can be expected to consider that rule obvious.

(rankAuthorizes RANK ORGTYPE-BY-EGB ACT-TYPE ROLE) means that a person with rank_Military RANK in ORGTYPE-BY-EGB is authorityCapableOf of playing ROLE in events of type ACT-TYPE. comment:
An instance of TernaryOrderingPredicate that identifies an ordering among two instances of AbstractInformationStructure in some larger structure. 
   (aisPriorToAISInAIS AIS-1 AIS-2 STRUCTURE)
means that AIS-1 occurs prior to AIS-2 within the context STRUCTURE, itself an instance of AbstractInformationStructure. "occurs prior to" in this context means that AIS-1 comes before AIS-2 as understood by the conventions used in interpreting STRUCTURE. So if AIS-1 and AIS-2 are abstract character strings (c.f., CharacterString) of English and STRUCTURE is a document formatted in the typical way that English documents are formatted, then any physical instantiation PRINTOUT of STRUCTURE will be such that an instantiation of (instantiationOfAIS) AIS-1 will appear to the left of or higher than or on an earlier page than an instantiation of AIS-2 on PRINTOUT.

Note that because the same AbstractInformationStructure can appear multiple times in a larger structure, aisPriorToAISInAIS is neither asymmetric (see asymmetricInArgs) in its first and second argument-places, nor irreflexive (see interArgDifferent) in those argument-places. Thus where STRUCTURE is an abstract information structure for the book Green Eggs and Ham, the following will hold true: (aisPriorToAISInAIS "Sam I am" "Sam I am" STRUCTURE). This feature makes aisPriorToAISInAIS somewhat unusual as an instance of TernaryOrderingPredicate; contrast with cisPriorToCISInStructure.
label: Ais Prior To AIS In AIS
aisPriorToAISInAIS

(collectionBackchainEncouraged COLLECTION)

means that rules that conclude

(isa <anything> COLLECTION)

are most likely going to have to be used in order to prove literals of the form

(isa <anything> COLLECTION),

and rules that conclude

(genls <anything> COLLECTION)

are most likely going to have to be used in order to prove literals of the form

(genls <anything> COLLECTION).

This directs the inference engine to use such rules even if HL predicate transformation is disabled. Note that it will not necessarily use rules of the form

([isa|genls] <anything> <variable>)

where <variable> might bind to COLLECTION, and it will not necessarily use rules of the form

([isa|genls] <anything> SPEC), where (genls SPEC COLLECTION).

See also backchainEncouraged for the analogue of this predicate applicable to predicates rather than collections.
label: Collection Backchain Encouraged
collectionBackchainEncouraged

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain relationship with respect to a given thing and a given collection. (relationInstanceExistsMany BINPRED THING COL) means that there are many instances INST(i) of COL such that (BINPRED THING INST(i)) holds. It is equivalent to (relationInstanceExistsRange BINPRED THING COL Many_Quant), and thus to the more complex form (for which it can in effect be used as shorthand):

(thereExistRange Many_Quant ?INST (and (isa ?INST COL2 (BINPRED THING ?INST))) .

For example, `(relationInstanceExistsMany anatomicalParts #$Patches-Cat Hair_Strand)' means that Patches has many hairs. See also relationInstanceExistsMin, relationInstanceExistsMax, relationInstanceExistsCount, and #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Instance Exists Many
relationInstanceExistsMany

comment:
A binary predicate that relates a pair of SetOrCollections to their union. (setOrCollectionUnion2 UNION CLASS1 CLASS2) entails that, for any thing THING, THING is an elementOf UNION if and only if THING is an element of CLASS1 or an element of CLASS2. Furthermore, we stipulate that (i) if both CLASS1 and CLASS2 are sets (see Set_Mathematical) then UNION is a set and (ii) if both CLASS1 and CLASS2 are Collections then UNION is a collection. If one of them is a set and the other a collection then UNION will either be a set or a collection, though in many cases we might not be able to determine which, and can only conclude that UNION is a SetOrCollection.

Also see setOrCollectionUnion and setOrCollectionIntersection2.
label: Set Or Collection Union 2
setOrCollectionUnion2

comment: (relatedToVia OBJ1 OBJ2 SET NUM) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are related via some sequence of NUM or fewer steps via the binary relations in the set SET. More precisely, (relatedToVia OBJ1 OBJ2 SET NUM) means that there is a sequence of objects of the length equal to or less than NUM and such that OBJ1 is the first element of the sequence, OBJ2 is the last element of the sequence, and each element of the sequence is related to its successor (if any) by some predicate in SET, or by the inverse of some predicate in SET. For instance, if (likesAsFriend BillClinton TonyBlair) and (knows TonyBlair GeorgeWBush) are true, then (relatedToVia BillClinton GeorgeWBush (TheSet likesAsFriend acquaintedWith) 2) is true (given that (genlPreds knows acquaintedWith) is true). Note that a predicate in SET may be used to relate more than one pair: if (likesAsFriend BillClinton TonyBlair) and (likesAsFriend TonyBlair GeorgeWBush) are true, then (relatedToVia BillClinton GeorgeWBush (TheSet likesAsFriend acquaintedWith) 2) is true.
label: Related To Via

comment:
A ternary MetaPredicate that is used to state that two predicates stand in a genlPreds -like relation to each other with respect to a specified correlation between their argument-places. The first predicate's arity might be the same as, greater than, or less than that of the second predicate; and the argument-place correlation is encoded by a list of non-negative integers whose length is equal to the arity of the second predicate. The encoding scheme is roughly this: the position of a given integer within the list represents that same argument-position within the second predicate, while the size of the integer represents the corresponding argument-position within the first predicate.

First, suppose that SPECPRED's arity is greater than or equal to that of GENLPRED. In that case, each integer in ARGNUMLIST should be greater than 0, and (genlPredsWRTArgs SPECPRED GENLPRED ARGNUMLIST) means that, whenever SPECPRED holds of a given argument-sequence SPEC-SEQ, then GENLPREDS holds of the sequence GENL-SEQ, defined as follows: where the Ith item in ARGNUMLIST is the integer N, the Ith item in GENL-SEQ is the same as the Nth item in SPEC-SEQ. For example, 

  (genlPredsWRTArgs touchesWith touches (TheList 3 2))
entails 
  (implies
    (touchesWith #$MingXu Steak8 Fork25)
    (touches Fork25 Steak8) .
Second, suppose that SPECPRED's arity is less than that of GENLPRED, and the difference in their arities is M. In that case, the integer 0 should appear in ARGNUMLIST in exactly M different places, and (genlPredsWRTArgs SPECPRED GENLPRED ARGNUMLIST) means that, whenever SPECPRED holds of a given argument-sequence SPEC-SEQ, there are M things OBJ-1, ..., OBJ-M such that GENLPREDS holds of the sequence GENL-SEQ, defined as follows: where the Ith item in ARGNUMLIST is the integer N (for N > 0), the Ith item in GENL-SEQ is the same as the Nth item in SPEC-SEQ; and where the Ith item in ARGNUMLIST is the Jth appearance of 0 in ARGNUMLIST (for 1 <= J <= M), the Ith item in GENL-SEQ is OBJ-J. For example, 
  (genlPredsWRTArgs transports transportsVia (TheList 1 2 0))
entails 
  (implies
    (transports #$Klein Clutch5)
    (thereExists ?X (transportsVia #$Klein Clutch5 ?X)) .

See also genlPredsWRTTypes.
label: Genl Preds WRT Args
genlPredsWRTArgs

comment: A ternary instance of RelativeLocationalPredicate. (distanceBetween PLACE1 PLACE2 DIST) means that the Distance between PLACE1 and PLACE2 is DIST. More precisely, DIST is the length of the shortest path through the space (when there is such a space) separating PLACE1 and PLACE2. Usually, a straight line between a point on PLACE1 and a point on PLACE2 will constitute the shortest such path. However, there are some circumstances in which this will not be the case; for instance, if PLACE1 and PLACE2 are GeographicalRegions, the shortest path between them may be a great circle, rather than a straight line. See also distanceAlongPath.
label: Distance Between
distanceBetween

comment: (feelsTowardsPersonType AGENT PERSONTYPE QUANT) says that AGENT has the quantity of feeling QUANT towards PERSONTYPE. This predicate is useful in conveying notions of Prejudice and preference -- notions for which feelsTowardsObjectToDegree are not especially well-suited; having feelings towards a group is by no means identical to having feelings towards each member of that group. Examples of how to use this predicate: To say that the KKK feels a great deal of hostility towards people of African descent, one can say '(feelsTowardsPersonType #$KuKluxKlan EthnicGroupOfNewWorldBlacks (MediumToVeryHighAmountFn Hostility)) .' To say that each individual Klansmen is so hostile, we can use the rule, '(implies (hasMembers #$KuKluxKlan ?HICK) (feelsTowardsPersonType ?HICK EthnicGroupOfNewWorldBlacks (MediumToVeryHighAmountFn Hostility))).' See the salientAssertions to get a sense of how feelings towards a group relate to the individual members of that group.
label: Feels Towards Person Type
feelsTowardsPersonType

comment: A quintary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa based relationship holds between a given argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArgResultIsaReln FUNC N RELATION RELATION-NAT-TERM-ARG RELATION-COLLECTION-ARG) means that, if there is a sentence asserted in the KB relating NAT-TERM and COLLECTION via RELATION and NAT-TERM is the RELATION-NAT-TERM-ARGth argument in the sentence and COLLECTION is the RELATION-COLLECTION-ARGth argument, then when NAT-TERM appears as the Nth argument to FUNC, then (regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be) the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of COLLECTION. That is: if (RELATION ... NAT_TERM ... COLLECTION ...) or (RELATION ... COLLECTION ... NAT_TERM ...) is an asserted sentence, and (FUNC ARG(1) ... ARG(N-1) NAT_TERM ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of COLLECTION. Obviously, COLLECTION must be a collection; so RELATION's RELATION-COLLECTION-ARGth argument-place is likely to be isa constrained (see argIsa) to Collection or some specialization thereof.
label: Inter Arg Result Isa Reln
interArgResultIsaReln

comment: An assertion of the form (taskHasPrereqWRTPostCond TASK PRE-STATE POST-STATE) is used to relate a type of PurposefulAction, TASK, to two instances of TaskState, PRE-STATE and POST-STATE. This predicate is intended for complex tasks that are related to multiple prerequisites and multiple post conditions. If it is the case that a postcondition only depends only a subset of the preconditions, this predicate allows for a representation of that connection. equivalenceCollectionWRT

comment: (fastestInSetToLocation LOC1 LOC2 OBJ SET) means that OBJ is the element of SET that would in the context of the assertion take the least time of all the elements in SET to get from LOC1 to LOC2.
label: Fastest In Set To Location
fastestInSetToLocation
Evaluated Sentence
evaluatedSentence
comment: (evaluatedSentence SENTENCE) means that a reviewer has looked at the CycLPropositionalSentence SENTENCE and felt that the information content of the sentence could be described by some specPred of evaluatedSentence. No assertions should be made on this predicate, as its extent should be entirely concludable via genlPreds.

(nearestIsaOfType OBJ TYPE COL) means that COL is a "nearest" collection of which OBJ is an instance and which is of type TYPE. That is, (isa OBJ COL) holds, (isa COL TYPE) holds, and there is no reified Collection NEARER-COL distinct from COL such that (isa OBJ NEARER-COL), (isa NEARER-COL TYPE), and (genls NEARER-COL COL) hold. Note that nearestIsaOfType is non-assertible (see notAssertible), since its extension at any given time depends upon (and so must be recomputed from) the current state of the Cyc Knowledge Base.
label: Nearest Isa Of Type
nearestIsaOfType
Alive BLO
alive-BLO
comment: '(alive_BLO BLO)' means that BLO is living.

label: Macro Capable
macroCapable
comment: An element of ComputerProgram_CW is macroCapable if it includes the ability to define macros within its functionality. A macro typically enables easy execution of a complex command by remapping keystrokes or menu selections.

(explosivePowerEquivalent DEV DEV-TYPE NUM) means that a single instance of ExplosiveDevice DEV has the same explosive force as NUM amount of DEV-TYPE. This predicate is useful for rating the explosive power of individual Bombs, etc., in terms of some common measure, such as pounds of TNT or numbers of Bomblet_M77s. Cf. explosivePowerEquivalent_Type.
label: Explosive Power Equivalent
explosivePowerEquivalent

comment:
(nounStringOccursAsObjectForVerbStringsInCorpus STRING USAGES SOURCE) means that USAGES represents all observed usages of the noun with nonplural string STRING as an object in the instance of InformationStore SOURCE. USAGES must take the form of an extensional list (see List_Extensional) of infinitive verb-strings. A given verb can appear more than once in a list to reflect multiple occurrences with the noun.

For example, (nounStringOccursAsObjectForVerbStringsInCorpus "apple" (TheList "eat" "eat" "slice" "toss") NewYorkTimes2001TextCorpus) means that in the New York Times 2001 corpus, the noun 'apple' occurred twice as the object of the verb 'to eat,' once as the object of the verb 'to slice,' and once as the object of the verb 'to toss.'

See also nounStringOccursAsSubjectForVerbStringsInCorpus.
label: Noun String Occurs As Object For Verb Strings In Corpus
nounStringOccursAsObjectForVerbStringsInCorpus
Number Of Acts Of Type By Agent In Region During Period
numberOfActsOfTypeByAgentInRegionDuringPeriod

comment:
A declarative hook into a graphical model information extraction tool developed by <font color="#ff0000">#$Mahler</font>. Given two strings such as 'Kennedy' and 'Cuba', a query with this predicate will return as bindings for the third argument a set of strings such as 'missiles' 'Soviet Union' which in some sense account for the
relationship between the two arguments as it can be gleaned from the textual
corpus targeted by this predicate
label: Connecting Terms
connectingTerms

comment: (viableProposedCoreferentInUDS UDS PEG1 PEG2) means that PEG2 is a possible antecedent for PEG1 in the discourse structure UDS: more precisely, (i) PEG1 is a discourse anaphor in UDS (cf. anaphoricDiscourseReferentInUDS), (ii) PEG2 is an available referent marker in UDS (cf. availableCoreferentInUDS), and (iii) PEG2 has not been excluded by other semantic or syntactic constraints.
label: Viable Proposed Coreferent In UDS
viableProposedCoreferentInUDS

comment: (candidateSetOfValuesForBinPredWRTArg BIN-PRED THING SET NUM) means that when THING is in arg NUM in BIN-PRED SET is a set of candidate values for the remaining arg position such that there is a good chance that at least some of the members are such that (BINPRED THING-IN-ARG-NUM MEMBER-OF-SET-IN-OTHER-ARG) is a true sentence. For example (candidateSetOfValuesForBinPredWRTArg typicalLocationTypeOfType ElectricalToaster (TheSet Kitchen LivingRoom Bedroom DiningRoom) 1) holds because the set involved is a decent candidate set of possible location types that toasters might be found.
label: Candidate Set Of Values For Bin Pred WRT Arg
candidateSetOfValuesForBinPredWRTArg

comment: (inheritRolePlayers_SubSitTypeToSubSitType_Unique SITTYPE ROLE1 SUBSITTYPE1 ROLE2 SUBSITTYPE2) means that in any instance of SITTYPE whatever single entity plays ROLE1 in the instantiation of SUBSITTYPE1 is identical to the entity that plays ROLE2 in the instantiation of SUBSITTYPE2. For a similar predicate without the uniqueness presupposition, see the more general inheritRolePlayers_SubSitTypeToSubSitType.
label: Inherit Role Players Sub Sit Type To Sub Sit Type Unique
inheritRolePlayers-SubSitTypeToSubSitType-Unique
subPropertyOf: Inherit Role Players Sub Sit Type To Sub Sit Type

comment: This predicate relates objects such as buildings (or the lots on which they stand) that are located diagonally across a street intersection from each other. (caterCornerTo OBJ1 OBJ2 XING) means that OBJ1 and OBJ1 are located out in the open on diagonally-opposite street corners of XING. For example, if OBJ1 is on the northwest corner of XING, then OBJ2 must be on the southeast corner. See also atStreetIntersection and streetCornerOf.
label: Cater Corner To
caterCornerTo

comment: If SPACE is a TopologicalSpace with base set BASE and SET is a subset of BASE, then the frontier of SET is the intersection of the closure of SET with the closure of the complement of SET in BASE In CycL, this relation is expressed as (frontierOfSetInTopologicalSpace FRONTIER SET SPACE).
label: Frontier Of Set In Topological Space
frontierOfSetInTopologicalSpace

comment: ARG4 is the amount of time which ARG1 usually goes without playing the role ARG3 in a situation of type ARG2.
label: Max Abstinence Time
maxAbstinenceTime
Identifying Feature Via Rel All Exists
identifyingFeatureViaRelAllExists

comment: (productTypeLicensedForUse PRODUCTTYPE ROLE EVTTYPE) means that there exists a License_LegalAgreement that specifies that if PRODUCT is an instance of PRODUCTTYPE, it is OK for PRODUCT to play the role ROLE in instances of EVTTYPE.
label: Product Type Licensed For Use
productTypeLicensedForUse

comment: (hyphenString STRINGS WORD PART TERM) means, just as with multiWordString, that the translation of the phrase or word containing STRINGS and WORD, with part of speech PART, is TERM. (See multiWordString for further usage notes). In addition, this predicate specifies that STRINGS and WORD may occur in THREE juxtapositions: they may be separated not only 1: by a space, but also 2: with a hyphen or 3: run together with no space at all. For example, (hyphenString (TheList "time") #$Zone-TheWord CountNoun TimeZone)denotes that "time zone", "time-zone", and "timezone" are all acceptable forms of the word. In generation, by default, the hyphenated form will be used (e.g. "time-zone")
label: Hyphen String
hyphenString

comment: (nthSubSituationOfType NTH-SUBSITUATION SUPER-SITUATION N TYPE) says that the instance of Situation NTH-SUBSITUATION is the Nth proper subsituation (see properSubSituations) of SUPER-SITUATION that is an instance of the collection TYPE. For example, (nthSubSituationOfType SecondInningOfBaseballGame001 BaseballGame001 2 BaseballInning) says that the second inning of the baseball game denoted by BaseballGame001 is the second instance of BaseballInning of that game.
label: Nth Sub Situation Of Type
nthSubSituationOfType

comment: (reasonableTrafficableRouteToFor PATH OBJ AGT) means that PATH is a reasonable route for AGT, between OBJ and AGT. For example, if one were planning to drive a car from Dallas to Los Angeles for no other purpose than to arrive in L.A., it would not make sense to detour through Panama or Canada: reasonabl;e routes would mainly be on trafficable roads mainly east and south of L.A. and mainly west and north of Dallas (since L.A. is to the west and north of Dallas).
label: Reasonable Trafficable Route To For
reasonableTrafficableRouteToFor

comment: A predicate for enumerating predicates which must be wrapped around a reformulator rule for it to be used. (useMetaPredicateInReformulation SPEC PRED INT) means the reformulator should use only those reformulator rules wrapped by MetaPredicate PRED. The value of PRED is passed to the CycLReformulator parameter :meta-predicates as a list. The value of INT is the place where RULE appears in the list.
label: Use Meta Predicate In Reformulation
useMetaPredicateInReformulation

comment: (importFromQuotaDuring REGION1 PRODUCT-TYPE REGION2 THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the import quota of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE for the GeographicalRegion REGION1 from the GeographicalRegion REGION2 during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (Of course, the existence of import quotas is the exception rather than the rule.) THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of automobile imports, for example, AMOUNT might be an Integer indicating the number of cars that may be imported. In the case of oil imports, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil REGION1 is allowed to import from REGION2. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of import, under the quota, of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION1 from REGION2 during the temporal extent of THING. Oil imports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day.
label: Import From Quota During
importFromQuotaDuring

comment: (vulnerableTo_TypeType THREAT-OBJ-TYPE OBJECT-TYPE HARM-TYPE) means that instances of the collection THREAT-OBJ-TYPE generally pose harm results of type HARM-TYPE to instances of OBJECT-TYPE. The purpose of this predicate is to represent knowledge about object-object vulnerabilities at the type level. Note that this is a type-level predicate in the first and second argument places and that care needs to be taken in developing rules that draw vulnerableTo conclusions from vulnerableTo_TypeType GAFs so that we do not overpopulate the KB with potentially questionable vulnerableTo judgments.
label: Vulnerable To Type Type
vulnerableTo-TypeType

comment: (producerSurplusAtQuantityOfProductType MARKET PRODUCT-TYPE SURPLUS QUANTITY) identifies SURPLUS as the monetary value of selling an isntance of PRODUCT-TYPE in MARKET at the marketClearingPrice, above what they would have been willing to sell that number of PRODUCT-TYPE had they only produced QUANTITY of it.
label: Producer Surplus At Quantity Of Product Type
producerSurplusAtQuantityOfProductType

comment: (chemicalBondBetween CHEMICALBOND CHEMICALOBJECT1 CHEMICALOBJECT2) means that CHEMICALBOND, an instance of chemical bond, connects CHEMICALOBJECT1 and CHEMICALOBJECT2.
label: Chemical Bond Between
chemicalBondBetween

comment: (organizationOfPartyInLegislativeOrganization LEG-ORG PARTY ORG) means that ORG is the organization of persons serving in LEG-ORG who are members of PARTY.
label: Organization Of Party In Legislative Organization
organizationOfPartyInLegislativeOrganization

comment: (closeToWRTScale INT1 INT2 SCALE) says that the ScalarIntervals INT1 and INT2 bear the approximately relationship to each other, in so far as the standard by which we make the comparison is SCALE. For example, (closeToWRTScale (Foot_UnitOfMeasure 300) (Foot_UnitOfMeasure 301) HeightOfBuilding) says that 300 feet and 301 feet are very close values where heights of buildings are concerned.
label: Close To WRT Scale
closeToWRTScale

comment: (foreignKeyMap REFERENCED_SCHEMA REFERENCED_KEY REFERENCING_SCHEMA REFERENCING_FIELD_LIST) means that i) the elements of REFERENCING_FIELD_LIST are physicalFields of REFERENCING_SCHEMA; ii) REFERENCED_KEY is the primaryKey of REFERENCED_SCHEMA; and iii) REFERENCING_FIELD_LIST is a foreign key in REFERENCING_SCHEMA which corresponds to the REFERENCED_KEY of REFERENCED_SCHEMA. It is important to note that REFERENCED_KEY must be a primaryKey of the REFERENCED_SCHEMA, however the same is not true of REFERENCING_FIELD_LIST and REFERENCING_SCHEMA. In fact they may not even satisfy nonNullFields. This predicate also entails a constraint on the ways in which rows in REFERENCING_SCHEMA can be updated. Specifically, no row of REFERENCING_SCHEMA may reference a nonexistant row of REFERENCED_SCHEMA. So updates or inserts which attempt to do this are rejected. There are additional constraints that must be considered when modifying sources interpreted by schemas with foreign key references. See the mutually exclusive specializations foreignKeyMap_Cascade and foreignKeyMap_Restrict.
label: Foreign Key Map
foreignKeyMap

comment:
This relates a schema integration to a predicate and the set of explicitly defined relationship defining schemas relating source object defining schemas using the predicate. That is, (schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputExplicitRDSSet INTEGRATION PREDICATE SOURCE-RDS-SET) means that:

1. SOURCE-RDS-SET is the set of explicitly defined RelationshipDefiningSchemas that state relationships between the input object defining schemas in INTEGRATION;

2. PREDICATE is the predicate that states the meaning of the relationship between the participating object defining schemas.
label: Schema Integration Predicate For Input Explicit RDS Set
schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputExplicitRDSSet
subPropertyOf: Schema Integration Predicate For Input RDS Set

comment: (argIsaArg PRED N M) means that for a formula involving PRED in arg0 to be well formed the Nth argument to PRED must be an instance of the Mth argument. This is especially useful in enforcing disjointness constaints for specPreds of isa.
label: Arg Isa Arg
argIsaArg

comment: (startOffset BIG LITTLE N) means that LITTLE is a (case-sensitive) substring of BIG that can be found N characters from the start of BIG.
label: start offset
startOffset

comment: (eventTypeRequiresAgentTypeForRole AGENT-TYPE EVENT-TYPE ROLE) holds just in case anything playing the role ROLE in EVENT-TYPE is required to be an instance of AGENT-TYPE. This is intended to be a English parsing/generation friendly way of stating: (interArgIsa ROLE 1 EVENT-TYPE 2 AGENT-TYPE).
label: Event Type Requires Agent Type For Role
eventTypeRequiresAgentTypeForRole

comment: (forbiddenSubSituationType CODE SIT SITUATION-TYPE) means that SIT is prohibited by CODE from containing an instance of SITUATION-TYPE as one of its subSituations. Usually, SIT will be subject to such a constraint in virtue of satisfying some general description (e.g., one specified in a rule antecedent), since codes of behavior normally generalize over event-types, often very complicated ones.
label: prohibition
forbiddenSubSituationType

comment: Used when knowledge enterers are agnostic about whether a given case counts as an exemplar usage of the constant. In assertions of the form (examples_Borderline CONSTANT EXAMPLE COMMENT), EXAMPLE is english text describing a single example. COMMENT is optional commentary about that example. Why do we allow ourselves to be undecided about certain cases? Explicit vagueness may help later users understand the amount of leeway they have in tailoring a constant for a particular unforseen use. For example, User1 may reify ConstantA for usage X. User2 may come along ConstantA years later wanting to use it for usage Y. Assume that usage Y requires some fact to be true about ConstantA about which User1 was agnostic. examples_Borderline is useful for indicating this agnosticism and not requiring the knowledge enterer to waste time deciding on membership for every possible exemplar they can think of.
label: Examples-Borderline
examples-Borderline
Sibling Disambiguation Collection Type
siblingDisambiguationCollectionType
comment: (siblingDisambiguationCollectionType TYPE) means that the Learning Reader should give cookies to parses whose nearestIsaOfType TYPE are shared with other parses.

marketShareForPrescriptionsByDoc

For instance, (programIndexTypeNameString PostgreSQL HashTable_DataStructure 'hash') means that in PostgreSQL's implementation of the SQL_Language, the HashTable_DataStructure is called 'hash'.

This predicate is especially useful for reasoning about probability assignments. See the documentation for increasesSitSlot_Subjective for examples, and for comparing this predicates to similar ones like increases_Generic and decreases_Generic.

temporalIntersection

comment: (weaponUsesAmmunitionInAttack ATTACK WEAPON THING) holds iff, during an AttackOnTangible, a Weapon uses some PartiallyTangible as ammunition. The ammunition is 'used' primarily in the sense of being the arg2 of launchesProjectile, but also covers cases where the ammunition is stuff-like (e.g., Napalm) or simply energy (e.g., many Weapons in the PropositionalConceptualWork_ScienceFictionGenre).

comment: (numberOfPrescriptionsByDocDuring DOC DRUGTYPE RXFILLTYPE PERIOD NUM) means that Prescriber DOC has had NUM prescriptions of type RXFILLTYPE filled for DRUGTYPE during PERIOD. RXFILLTYPE may be FillingAPrescription-Retail, FillingAPrescription_MailOrder, FillingANewPrescription, FillingARefillPrescription, intersections of these, or merely FillingAPrescription.

numberOfPrescriptionsByDocDuring

comment: (disabilityToPlayRole CONDITION ACT-TYPE ROLE) means that an animal with the PhysiologicalConditionType CONDITION is not physically capable of playing the Role ROLE in actions of type ACT-TYPE. For example, (disabilityToPlayRole Blindness VisualPerception doneBy) means that a blind animal cannot see.

disabilityToPlayRole

comment: The predicate fiscallyCapableOf indicates that an agent has the economic prerequisites needed for playing a certain role in a certain type of situation or event. (fiscallyCapableOf AGENT SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that a particular Agent_PartiallyTangible AGENT has the financial resources needed to play ROLE in normal instances of SIT-TYPE.
label: Fiscally Capable Of
fiscallyCapableOf

comment: (militaryRank_CountryAndBranchOfService PERSON RANK COUNTRY BOS-TYPE) means that PERSON has the military rank RANK in COUNTRY's branch of service BOS-TYPE.

militaryRank-CountryAndBranchOfService

comment: (programFunctionResultInBodyAction FUNCTION ACTIONPRED ACTIONARG) means that the result of FUNCTION is passed as the ACTIONARG argument of an action sentence with functor ACTIONPRED, which computes the body of the function.
label: Program Function Result In Body Action
programFunctionResultInBodyAction

comment: An assertion of the form (actFulfillsNthIterationForAssignment ACTION Nth ASSIGN) asserts that the instance of Action ACTION partially satisfies the IteratedAssignment ASSIGN by being the Nth instance of the sort of action specified by ASSIGN. The total number of instances of the relevant sort of action is represented using the predicate assignmentIterationCount.
label: Act Fulfills Nth Iteration For Assignment
actFulfillsNthIterationForAssignment

comment: A quaternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly genls based relationship holds between a given argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArgResultGenls FUNC N INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when a subcollection of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the Nth argument to FUNC, then (regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be) the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is a subcollection of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is a subcollection of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG(1) ... ARG(N-1) INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is a subcollection of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArgResultGenl _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but less flexible ternary interArg1ResultGenls et al.
label: Inter Arg Result Genl
interArgResultGenl
Variable Mapping Table For GLF Arc In Diagram
variableMappingTableForGLFArcInDiagram

comment: (keyStatsForMemberCorporation SET-OR-COLL CORP CHANGE DV) holds just in case CORP is an instance of SET-OR-COLL and the change in stock price for CORP since last close is CHANGE and DV is the "dollar value meaning it is the amount of money spent on CORP's stock on an average day.

keyStatsForMemberCorporation

comment: (literacyRateForGroupInRegion REGION GROUP RATE) means that the literacyRate of GROUP in REGION is RATE.

literacyRateForGroupInRegion

comment: (predatorTypeHasPreyTypeInEcosystem PREDATOR-TYPE PREY-TYPE SYSTEM) means that many instance of PREDATOR-TYPE consume instances of PREY-TYPE as resources in SYSTEM (consumerOfResourceTypeInSystem). More specifically, this means that instances of PREDATOR-TYPE are capable of enacting (doneBy) subevents in the autocatalytic 'lifetime' of SYSTEM (autocatalyticProcessImplementsSystem) in which instances of PREY-TYPE are inputsDestroyed.
label: Predator Type Has Prey Type In Ecosystem
predatorTypeHasPreyTypeInEcosystem

label: Initiate Packet Transfer Of Type To Program From To
initiatePacketTransferOfTypeToProgramFromTo

comment: (standardPartConstrains STAND THE SPART) states that anything which satisfies TheProduct in standard STAND must have all its parts which satisfy THE in STAND satisfy TheProduct in SPART.  SPART must be an intangibleParts of STAND. For example, (standardPartConstrains IBM-PC-AT-Standard TheProcessor Intel-80286-Standard)
label: Standard Part Constrains
standardPartConstrains

comment: `(symptomInstanceOnsetRateInCondition SYM AIL RATE) means that SYM is a subevent and symptom of AIL and it has/had an onset rate of RATE.
label: Symptom Instance Onset Rate In Condition
symptomInstanceOnsetRateInCondition

comment: (candidateSubSituationType SITTYPE SIT SUBSITTYPE SUBSIT) means that 1) it is possible that (and (isa SIT SITTYPE) (isa SUBSIT SUBSITTYPE) (subSituations SIT SUBSIT)), 2) some evidence for the conjunction exists, and 3) at least one of the conjuncts is still an unknownSentence in the context of the assertion. It also presupposes (properSubSituationTypes SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE).
label: Candidate Sub Situation Type
candidateSubSituationType

comment: (negativelyCorrelatedWith ?SET ?SLOT1 ?SLOT2) means that the values for ?SLOT1 and the values for ?SLOT2 are negatively correlated, when they are applied to elements of ?SET. In other words, ?SLOT1 is low when ?SLOT2 is high (and vice versa: high when low) for an arbitrary element of ?SET. High and low are with respect to the range of all values of ?SLOT1 respectively ?SLOT2 for elements of ?SET. Note that negativelyCorrelatedWith and positivelyCorrelatedWith don't entail a particular directionality of the causal relationship between ?SLOT1 and ?SLOT2. It might go either direction, or there may be no direct causal link, with instead values of ?SLOT1 and ?SLOT2 actually being independent but subject to some common causal mechanism.
label: negative correlation
negativelyCorrelatedWith

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates UnitOfMeasure (q.v.) functions. (multiplicationUnits UNIT1 UNIT2 PRODUNIT) means that PRODUNIT is the unit-of-measure that always returns the product of the values returned by UNIT1 and UNIT2 for two respective arguments (or argument-sequences) when it is itself applied to the product of those arguments (or sequences). That is, whenever (UNIT1 . ARGS1) = VALUE1 and (UNIT2 . ARGS2) = VALUE2, then (PRODUNIT (TimesFn ARGS1 ARGS2)) = (TimesFn VALUE1 VALUE2).

For example, (multiplicationUnits Mile Mile SquareMile) holds, and thus (TimesFn (Mile 2) (Mile 3)) is equal to (SquareMile 6).

The predicate multiplicationUnits corresponds to (see functionCorrespondingPredicate) both of the functions UnitProductFn and PerFn (qq.v.). Thus,

(multiplicationUnits UNIT1 UNIT2 PRODUNIT)

is equivalent to

(equals PRODUNIT (UnitProductFn UNIT1 UNIT2))

is equivalent to

(equals UNIT1 (PerFn PRODUNIT UNIT2)) .
label: Multiplication Units
multiplicationUnits

comment: (postChangeValueOfQuantity TEMPORAL-THING THING SLOT VALUE) means that the instance of TemporalThing TEMPORAL-THING changed the value of SLOT applied to THING to VALUE. To specify what the value of SLOT applied to THING is changed from, use preChangeValueOfQuantity. preChangeValueOfQuantity, postChangeValueOfQuantity, and changesQuantityByAmount can be used together to perform arithmetical calculations about the value of SLOT applied to THING with respect to TEMPORAL-THING.
label: Post Change Value Of Quantity
postChangeValueOfQuantity

comment:
A unary KBDependentRelation (q.v.) that takes instances of CycLSentence as arguments. (unknownSentence SENTENCE) means that SENTENCE is not currently "known" by the Cyc system to be true. More precisely, the inference engine cannot prove SENTENCE using only removal (see CycRemovalModule) from the current state of the knowledge base. SENTENCE might actually be known to be false (see the specialization contradictorySentence), or its truth-value might be simply unknown in the present sense.

Note that, as a KB dependent relation, unknownSentence is notAssertible (q.v.).
label: Unknown Sentence
unknownSentence

comment: (grossNationalProduct GE THING MONEY) means that the instance of MonetaryValue MONEY is a measure of the value of all the goods and services produced by the citizens and resident corporations of the GeopoliticalEntity GE during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. These goods and services include those produced in foreign commercial activities. A country would be a typical instance of GE. THING will often be a time period -- for example, a calendar year such as (YearFn 1997) or a calendar quarter such as (QuarterFn 4 (YearFn 1997)); but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. See also grossDomesticProduct.
label: gnp
grossNationalProduct

comment: This is the corresponding predicate of the function FileOnSystemAtFn.
label: Is File On System At
isFileOnSystemAt

comment: An assertion (roleMapping_Branch SIT-TYPE TYPE BRANCH-SET LINK-LIST) is used to represent a role-mapping relation among actors within instances of specs of Situation. Specifically, it is used to represent situations where multiple actors fill a set of common roles, but where those actors are only a subset of the actors who fill some other roles in other scenes. The argument BRANCH-SET is used to represent the first set of roles. BRANCH-SET is a set of lists with the following structure: (TheSet (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE-1 ROLE-1) ... (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE-N ROLE-N) ...). Assertions using this predicate behave similarly to roleMapping_Equivalence in terms of their arguments SIT-TYPE TYPE and BRANCH-SET. Thus, in an instance of SIT-TYPE, if an actor of TYPE plays ROLE-1 in a subSituations of type SUBSIT-TYPE-1, then that actor will play ROLE-N in a subSituations of type SUBSIT-TYPE-N and vice-versa. The difference comes in the relation to the argument LINK-LIST. LINK-LIST also represents a role within a scene, and LINK-LIST could be an element of LIST for some assertion of the form (roleMapping_Equivalence SIT-TYPE TYPE LIST), where SIT-TYPE and TYPE are the same as above. Thus, the LINK-LIST could be used to connect the BRANCH-SET to a single role and scene pair, or to an entire set of roles and scenes that are another actor path for TYPE within SIT-TYPE. As an example, consider the process of staying overnight at a hotel. If the guests are all one family, all of the members of the family will arrive, stay over night, and depart. However, only a subset of the family will perform the actions of checking in and checking out. In order to capture this structure, you can place the checking in event type on one branch and checking out event type on another branch (presuming that there is no guarantee that the same actor will perform both actions) and have those branches connect up to a path that involves the other activities associated with staying at a hotel. If there are multiple roles in scenes associated with a branch, then they should all be listed as a sublist which is an element of the argument BRANCH-SET.
label: Role Mapping Branch
roleMapping-Branch

comment: (adverbSemTransTemplate COL FRAME TRANS) means that the translation of any adverb denotation of a word denoting an instance of COL, appearing with subcategorization frame FRAME, is TRANS.
label: Adverb Sem Trans Template
adverbSemTransTemplate

comment: (revenueForPeriodByAccountingCOC ORG MONEY TIME COC) means MONEY is the amount earned as revenue (e.g. net sales) by ORG during TIME based on the accounting principles allowed by the AccountingCOC COC.
label: Revenue For Period By Accounting COC
revenueForPeriodByAccountingCOC

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates a PartiallyTangible to a Direction to a Speed. (speedOfObjectInDirection OBJ DIRECTION SPEED) means the speed at which OBJ is moving in DIRECTION is SPEED. This does not imply that the net movement of OBJ is in DIRECTION. Rather, it means that if OBJ continues at the same velocity for TIME, and SPEED = DISTANCE/TIME, then OBJ will be located DISTANCE further in DIRECTION after TIME.

For example, suppose that the net velocity (see velocityOfObject) of Car001 is Northwest_Directly at 100 KilometersPerHour. Then we have: 

(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 Northwest_Directly (KilometersPerHour 100))
(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 North_Directly (KilometersPerHour 70.71)
(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 West_Directly (KilometersPerHour 70.71)
(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 South_Directly (KilometersPerHour -70.71)
(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 East_Directly (KilometersPerHour -70.71)
(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 Southeast_Directly (KilometersPerHour -100))
(speedOfObjectInDirection Car001 Southwest_Directly (KilometersPerHour 0))
etc.
That is, after one hour, Car001 will be located 100 km further Northwest, about 71 km further North, about -71 km further South, 0 km further Southwest, etc.
label: Speed Of Object In Direction
speedOfObjectInDirection

comment: (identicalInValue THING1 THING2 TYPE) holds just in case THING1 and THING2 are the same with respect to some instance of TYPE. In many cases, this means that they are both instances of the same instance of TYPE. For instance, (identicalInValue RedBall-01 JonsEscort Color) holds because both RedBall-01 and JonsEscort are instances of RedColor which is an instance of Color. In other words, it means RedBall-01 and JonsEscort are the same color. Use this predicate to state that two things share a property but can't specify the exact value they share. identicalInValue and differentInValue cannot both be correctly asserted of the same two things. See also resemblesInValue.
label: Identical In Value
identicalInValue

comment: (entailsRoleInPlanOfType SYS-SLOT PLAN-TYPE SYS-ROLE AGENT-ROLE) means that if an agent plays the role SYS-SLOT in a functional system which in turn plays the role SYS-ROLE in a plan of type PLAN-TYPE, then said agent plays the role AGENT-ROLE in said plan.
label: Entails Role In Plan Of Type
entailsRoleInPlanOfType

comment: (fieldValueDependsOn ?LF ?VAL-LF ?DEP-LF ?VALUE) means that whether ?LF has a value for a particular record depends on the what the represented value of ?DEP-LF is. If ?DEP-LF has ?VALUE, then ?LF takes on the represented value of ?VAL-LF. See also dependentFields.
label: Field Value Depends On
fieldValueDependsOn

comment: (fieldDecoding LOGICAL_SCHEMA LOGICAL_FIELD PHYSICAL_SCHEMA TERM) means either that TERM is the logical field value that is conventionally denoted by the value taken by the physical field in PHYSICAL_SCHEMA corresponding to the logical field LOGICAL_FIELD in LOGICAL_SCHEMA, or that it simply is this value in the case where the logical field value is itself a code string.
label: Field Decoding
fieldDecoding

comment: (faultOfSoftwareObject_ReportIndexed FAULT REPORT LIST), where LIST is the list (PROGRAM-OR-SERIES-1 ... PROGRAM-OR-SERIES-N), means that, according to the computer vulnerability report REPORT, versions (see subSoftwareObjects) of PROGRAM-OR-SERIES-N in concert with versions of PROGRAMS-OR-SERIES-Nminus1 ... in concert with versions of PROGRAM-OR-SERIES-1 manifest FAULT.
label: Fault Of Software Object Report Indexed
faultOfSoftwareObject-ReportIndexed

comment: This is a ternary version of the binary predicate monetaryValueOfThing, which allows assertions regarding a thing's value to be relativised to those to whom it is so valuable. (monetaryValueOfThingTo THING VALUE AGENT) means that the TemporalThing THING (which may be goods or services) has a MonetaryValue VALUE to the Agent_PartiallyTangible AGENT. THING might have VALUE to AGENT for a number of different reasons -- it may have been appraised as such, or bought for such, or it may just be what the agent is willingToPay. See also costTo.
label: Monetary Value Of Thing To
monetaryValueOfThingTo

comment: (numberOfPrescriptionsByDocPayerTypeDuring ?DOC ?PRODUCT-TYPE ?PAYER-TYPE ?TIME ?NUM) means that during the time interval ?TIME, there were ?NUM prescriptions for ?PRODUCT-TYPE made by ?DOC, which were paid for by a HealthCarePayer of type ?PAYER-TYPE. For example, (numberOfPrescriptionsByDocPayerTypeDuring DrSmith ZoloftProduct StateMedicaidAdministrationOrganization (YearFn 1998) 27) means that DrSmith made 27 prescriptions for Zoloft in 1998 which were paid for by Medicaid.
label: Number Of Prescriptions By Doc Payer Type During
numberOfPrescriptionsByDocPayerTypeDuring

comment: (contactInsiderAtOrganization AGENT INSIDER ORG) means that AGENT contacts INSIDER at ORG.
label: Contact Insider At Organization
contactInsiderAtOrganization

comment: (proximityConstraints SIT ROLE1 ROLE2 RANGE) means that Distance_Absolute RANGE is the range of distance that object OBJ can be from the location in which something plays ROLE2 in Situation SIT in order for OBJ to play the role ROLE1 in SIT. Cf. proximityConstraints_Type.
label: Proximity Constraints
proximityConstraints

comment:
(genlPredsWRTTypes BINPRED1 BINPRED2 COL1 COL2) means that if (BINPRED1 INS1 INS2) where INS1 is an instance of COL1 and INS2 is an instance of COL2, then (BINPRED2 INS1 INS2).

genlPredsWRTTypes facilitates the expresssion of pseudo-genlPreds relationships between BinaryPredicates BINPRED1 and BINPRED2 when their argument constraints are not in the appropriate genls relationship for (genlPreds BINPRED1 BINPRED2) to be asserted.

At a more specific level, genlPredsWRTTypes can serve as a useful rule macro predicate. For instance, suppose we wanted to say that all people of a certain nationality, Italian, for instance, are, as a general rule, acquainted with all of their neighbors. We could assert (genlPredsWRTTypes neighbors acquaintedWith ItalianPerson Person). If there is a bi-directional genlPreds for the given argument types, use the more specific equivPredsWRTTypes. See also genlInverseWRTTypes.
label: Genl Preds WRT Types
genlPredsWRTTypes

comment: (inheritSomeRolePlayersOfType_SitTypeToSubSitType SIT-TYPE ROLE1 SUBSIT-TYPE ROLE2 TYPE) means that some instance(s) of TYPE playing ROLE1 in instances of SITTYPE play ROLE2 in the instance of SUBSIT-TYPE that is a sub-situation of SIT-TYPE.
label: Inherit Some Role Players Of Type Sit Type To Sub Sit Type
inheritSomeRolePlayersOfType-SitTypeToSubSitType

comment: (capitalizationOfExchangeOnMarketForYear EXCHANGE MARKET CAPITALIZATION YEAR) means that the market capitalzation of the stock exchange EXCHANGE at the stock market MARKET in YEAR is CAPITALIZATION,
label: Capitalization Of Exchange On Market For Year
capitalizationOfExchangeOnMarketForYear

comment: (odorSmelledByAgent ODOR THING AGENT) means that the odor ODOR from the object or event THING is smelled by the PerceptualAgent AGENT.
label: Odor Smelled By Agent
odorSmelledByAgent

comment:
A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keSuggestionPredsInverse_SpecIns COL1 BINPRED COL2) means that for every known specialization SPEC1 of COL1, it is suggested that there be some instance INS2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED INS2 SPEC1) is known in the knowledge base.

For example,

(keSuggestionPredsInverse_SpecIns SportsEquipment gameEquipmentType SportsGame)

means that for every known specialization EQ-TYPE of SportsEquipment, it is suggested that there be some instance GAME of SportsGame such that (gameEquipmentType GAME EQ-TYPE) is known in the knowledge base.

See also keSuggestionPreds_SpecIns.
label: Ke Suggestion Preds Inverse Spec Ins
keSuggestionPredsInverse-SpecIns

comment: (planHypotheticalInstanceOfType SPEC INS TYPE) means that INS is a hypothesized instance of TYPE generated for reasoning about the consequences of carrying out SPEC, an instance of GoalOrientedSpecification.
label: Plan Hypothetical Instance Of Type
planHypotheticalInstanceOfType

comment: The corresponding predicate to LevelOfSubstanceTypeInSysTypeFn. (conditionWithLevelOfSubstanceTypeInSysType SYS-COND SUB-TYPE SYS-TYPE LEVEL) means the SYS-COND is the condition of an instance of SYS-TYPE with a level LEVEL of SUB-TYPE in it.
label: Condition With Level Of Substance Type In Sys Type
conditionWithLevelOfSubstanceTypeInSysType

comment: (equivalentRolePlayers_SitTypeToSubSitType_Unique SITTYPE SITTYPE-ROLE SUBSITTYPE SUBSITTYPE-ROLE) means that in an instance of SITTYPE, the individual who plays the role SITTYPE-ROLE is the same as the individual who plays the role SUBSITTYPE-ROLE in the sub-situation that is an instance of SUBSITTYPE. The predicate assumes existence and uniqueness of role-players.
label: Equivalent Role Players Sit Type To Sub Sit Type Unique
equivalentRolePlayers-SitTypeToSubSitType-Unique
subPropertyOf: Inherit Role Players Sit Type To Sub Sit Type Unique

label: Equal Or Greater Quantity Value Needed
equalOrGreaterQuantityValueNeeded

comment: (missionRequiresNSubSystemsInSetForSystem MISSION N SET SYSTEM) means that MISSION requires at least N many of the systems in the set SET to be functioning, to support the functioning of the further required system, SYSTEM..
label: Mission Requires N Sub Systems In Set For System
missionRequiresNSubSystemsInSetForSystem

comment: The organization ARG2 reported a projected total of ARG4  units/doses dispensed/sold for the product type ARG1 during the time interval ARG3.
label: Total Projected Amount For Org During
totalProjectedAmountForOrgDuring

comment:
(startsAfterEndOfInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 and SIT2 are not temporally disjoint. (see also subSitTypesTemporallyDisjointInSitType).

Note that (startsAfterEndOfInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).
label: Temporal Bounds Intersect In Situation Type
temporalBoundsIntersectInSituationType

comment: (structureMap ?Src ?Src-Mt ?Tgt ?Tgt-Mt ?Src-Desc ?Tgt-Desc) returns a structure-mapping of the formulae in ?Src-Mt pertaining to the source concept ?Src that are isomorphic with formulae in ?Tgt-Mt that pertain to the target domain concept ?Tgt. The mappings are condensed as formulae, so ?Src-Desc becomes bound to an and of all the matching formulae in the source domain, while ?Tgt-Desc becomes bound to an and of all the matching formulae in the target domain. see also structureMaps.
label: Structure Map
structureMap
Checked Via Adj Tool
checkedViaAdjTool
comment: (checkedViaAdjTool WORD DATE) means that WORD was run through the AdjTool on DATE. Meta-assertions using this predicate are used in the AdjTool algorithm: 1. For any words in the lexicon not tagged with checkedViaAdjTool, run TOE script to assert all possible adjectival forms. 2. List all words and their adjectival forms that have not been checked via the tool (i.e. not tagged in step 4). 3. User checks those that should be unasserted. For each of these the tool adds a corresponding addition to the #$testAnswersCycL of the corresponding KBIT, e.g. KBIT-WordsWithoutAdj-EdForms. 4. Tag all words checked in the session. 5. Run KBIT to check for words without adj forms that don't have the #$testAnswersCycL exceptions.

This quaternary predicate is the logical analogue to foreignKeyMap and is used to generate fieldDecoding and fieldEncoding assertions. (foreignObjectMap ODS OF LS LF) means that the LogicalField LF in the LogicalSchema LS is a foreign reference to the LogicalField OF in the ObjectDefiningSchema ODS.
label: Foreign Object Map
foreignObjectMap

comment: (candidateClarificationQuestion UTTERANCE STRATEGY QUESTION) says that according to the ClarificationStrategy STRATEGY, QUESTION is an appropriate clarification question to ask in response to the LinguisticExpressionPeg UTTERANCE.
label: Candidate Clarification Question
candidateClarificationQuestion

comment: A quintary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly genls based relationship holds between a given argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArgResultGenlReln FUNC N RELATION RELATION-NAT-TERM-ARG RELATION-COLLECTION-ARG) means that, if there is a sentence asserted in the KB relating NAT-TERM and COLLECTION via RELATION and NAT-TERM is the RELATION-NAT-TERM-ARGth argument in the sentence and COLLECTION is the RELATION-COLLECTION-ARGth argument, then when NAT-TERM appears as the Nth argument to FUNC, then (regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be) the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is a subcollection of COLLECTION. That is: if (RELATION ... NAT_TERM ... COLLECTION ...) or (RELATION ... COLLECTION ... NAT_TERM ...) is an asserted sentence, and (FUNC ARG(1) ... ARG(N-1) NAT_TERM ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is a subcollection of COLLECTION. Obviously, COLLECTION must be a collection; so RELATION's RELATION-COLLECTION-ARGth argument-place is likely to be isa constrained (see argIsa) to Collection or some specialization thereof.
label: Inter Arg Result Genl Reln
interArgResultGenlReln

comment: (terrainAdvantage_SideDimensionDegree LOC SIDE ADV-DIM ADV-AMT) means that the location LOC has the potential to provide some TacticalAdvantage, where SIDE indicates whether the advantage is offensive or defensive, ADV-DIM indicates the tactical dimension of the advantage, and ADV-AMT indicates the degree of the advantage. For example, (terrainAdvantage_SideDimensionDegree Hill37 OffendingForce ConcealmentLimitingTerrain (MediumAmountFn TacticalAdvantage)) means that Hill37 has the potential to give the OffendingForce a medium level of TacticalAdvantage by limiting concealment. Note that TacticalAdvantages depend not just on terrain characteristics, but also on force and situation characteristics, and therefore belong to agents in fairly specific classes of real or potential military operations. For this reason, assertions stating the terrainAdvantage_SideDimensionDegree for some piece of terrain should be made only within appropriately scenario-specific contexts.
label: Terrain Advantage Side Dimension Degree
terrainAdvantage-SideDimensionDegree

comment: A predicate relating instances of Firewall_Network with port/protocol pairs and instances of Computer in the firewall's network. (unfilteredPortsForNetwork FIREWALL PROTOCOL NUM NETWORK) means that FIREWALL lets through all packets that conform to PROTOCOL coming from outside the network bound for port number NUM on any computer on NETWORK.
label: Unfiltered Ports For Network
unfilteredPortsForNetwork

comment: This predicate relates a customary path such as a street to two objects that are on opposite sides of the path, whether or not the objects are anywhere near each other. (oppositeOnPath OBJ1 OBJ2 PATH) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are both onPath_Alongside PATH, but are located on opposite sides of PATH. For more specific predicates that imply that the objects are nearer to each other, see oppositeOnPath_Generally and oppositeOnPath_Directly.
label: on opposite side of path
oppositeOnPath

comment: A predicate used to identify an object's placement in a mathematical ordering. (nthInOrdering ORDERING THING N) says that THING is the Nth object in the ordering ORDERING. THING must be an element of the baseSet for ORDERING.
label: position in ordering
nthInOrdering

comment: (maximumDurationForSubSituationType SIT-TYPE SUB-SIT-TYPE MAX) means that if a situation SUB-SIT is an instance of SUB-SIT-TYPE and is a proper subsituation of SIT, an instance of SIT-TYPE, then SUB-SIT will not last longer than MAX.
label: Maximum Duration For Sub Situation Type
maximumDurationForSubSituationType

comment:
A quaternary predicate relating a logical schema, logical field, collection, and integer. (logicalSchemaFieldIndexicalOfTypeWithMultiplicity SCHEMA INDEXICAL TYPE N) means that:

1. INDEXICAL is a logical field indexical of SCHEMA (See logicalFieldIndexicals);

2. INDEXICAL is an indexical of a field of type TYPE (See indexicalForLogicalField and fieldIsa);

3. INDEXICAL is the Nth indexical in SCHEMA corresponding to a field of type TYPE.

See also the function corresponding to the second argument of this predicate, TheLogicalFieldValueFn.
label: Logical Schema Field Indexical Of Type With Multiplicity
logicalSchemaFieldIndexicalOfTypeWithMultiplicity

comment: (fiscalYearForAgent AGT START END) means that one of the fiscal years recognized by AGT runs from the starting date START to the ending date END.
label: Fiscal Year For Agent
fiscalYearForAgent

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa1_2 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the first argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the second argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN INST ARG2 ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG2 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For example, (interArgIsa1_2 performedBy PurposefulAction IntelligentAgent) means that, if ACT is a purposeful action, then (performedBy ACT AGENT) is semantically well-formed only if AGENT is an intelligent agent. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.

Use interArgCondIsa1_2 to conclude that arg2 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL instead of having that as a constraint.
label: Inter Arg Isa 1 2
interArgIsa1-2

comment: A ternary predicate, each usage of which relates an instance of AspatialInformationStore, an instance of CommunicationConvention and an instance of InformationBearingThing. (usesCommConventionForInfo INFO CC IBT) means that the information-bearing thing IBT contains the information INFO, and INFO was encoded using the convention CC. This predicate might be used, for instance, to assert that a particular GraveMarker conveys the information that a certain individual is buried beneath it in RunicWriting. INFO need not be propositional, however. See also the binary predicate usesCommunicationConvention and the ternary predicate usesCommunicationConventionForWork (which relates an InformationStore, a CommunicationConvention and a ConceptualWork).
label: Uses Comm Convention For Info
usesCommConventionForInfo

comment: (ailmentTypicallyAcquiredBy INFECTIONTYPE ORGTYPE ACTIONTYPE) means, colloquially, that organisms of type ORGTYPE commonly acquire infections of type INFECTIONTYPE via actions of type ACTIONTYPE. To put it more precisely, it means that if organisms of type ORGTYPE are susceptible to a type of Microorganism that causes infections of type INFECTIONTYPE, and an organism of type ORGTYPE is the nonDeliberateActors in an action of type ACTIONTYPE, the likelihood that the organism will acquire an infection of type INFECTIONTYPE is highAmountOf.
label: Ailment Typically Acquired By
ailmentTypicallyAcquiredBy

comment: (iterationTerminalEventType SCRIPT SCENE EVT-TYPE) means that in SCRIPT, SCENE is comprised of iterations of an event type that terminate when an instance of EVT-TYPE is brought about by the occurrence of SCENE.
label: Iteration Terminal Event Type
iterationTerminalEventType

comment: (dateOfMostRecentOccurrenceOfTypePriorToOperation OP TYPE DATE) means that there is an instance of TYPE with date DATE that is situationally associated with the #$CCFEvent OP and that starts prior to OP, and there is no other known instance of TYPE which is part of the same situational complex as OP and whose date is later than DATE and before the minOpEntryDate of OP.
label: Date Of Most Recent Occurrence Of Type Prior To Operation
dateOfMostRecentOccurrenceOfTypePriorToOperation

comment: (joinDependency ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4) indicates that ARG1 equals ARG2 when ARG3 equals ARG4; all arguments are instances of LogicalField. ARG1 and ARG3 are fields in one LogicalTableSchema, while ARG2 and ARG4 are fields in another.
label: Join Dependency
joinDependency

comment: (portionOf SET1 SET2 NUM) means that the portion of members of SET1 that are also members of SET2 is NUM. In other words, the fraction of the cardinality of SET1 and the cardinality of the intersection of SET1 and SET2. For example, (portionOf (ResidentFn Netherlands) UnemployedPerson X) means that unemployment in the Netherlands is X.
label: percentage
portionOf

comment: (collectionSubsetsByCardinality COL CARD COL-OF-SUBSETS) means that COL-OF-SUBSETS is the collection of all subsets of COL that have cardinality CARD.
label: Collection Subsets By Cardinality
collectionSubsetsByCardinality

comment: (nearestIsaRelevanceEvent DATE THING EVT) means that EVT was the event of Cyc declaring, on DATE, that the nearest isa of THING was relevant.
label: Nearest Isa Relevance Event
nearestIsaRelevanceEvent

comment: (nearestCommonSpecs COL-1 COL-2 NEAR-SPEC) relates collections COL-1 and COL-2 to the nearest unsubsumed collections NEAR-SPEC of which are subsets of both COL-1 and COL-2. This predicate is notAssertible, since it must always be recomputed from the current state of the genls heirarchy. For comparison, see also nearestCommonIsa and nearestCommonGenls.
label: Nearest Common Specs
nearestCommonSpecs

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa5_1 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the fifth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the first argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 INDEPENDENT-ARG ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG1 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 5 1
interArgEqualsIsa5-1

comment: (predicateRestrictsWhen PRED SPECPRED COL) means than when INST is an instance of COL and bears a binary relation to X in PRED (i.e. (PRED INST X) or (PRED X INST) holds) then INST also bears this relation to X in SPECPRED. Note that the following holds: (genlPreds SPECPRED PRED).
label: Predicate Restricts When
predicateRestrictsWhen

comment: This predicate expresses a dependency between two unit-slot pairs. (dependsOn_Pairwise THING1 SLOT1 THING2 SLOT2 DIR) means that the value of the QuantitySlot SLOT1 for THING1 is dependent on the value of SLOT2 for THING2, in direction DIR. For instance, to say that Saudi Arabia's gross domestic product is positively dependent on the price of oil: (dependsOn_Pairwise SaudiArabia grossDomesticProductOf PetroleumProduct basicPriceForType #$Positive). See also positivelyDependsOn and negativelyDependsOn for collection-level generalizations of this predicate.
label: Depends On Pairwise
dependsOn-Pairwise

comment: (referenceInWorkTo WORK TEXT REFERENT) means that the StructurallySpecificWork WORK contains (see containsStructure_CW) TextString TEXT, which TEXT is a reference that points to REFERENT, an instance of IntelligentAgent or an instance of StructurallySpecificWork external to WORK. Not any mention of a person or work is a reference. The sentence 'Bill Clinton served two terms as the American president.' does not contain a reference in the sense of referenceInWorkTo. referenceInWorkTo indicates that a TextString formally and purposefully points to some other work or person for the purpose of attribution, support, or location. For TextStrings that refer to other TextStrings that are contained within the same StructurallySpecificWork, see crossReferenceInWorkTo.
label: Reference In Work To
referenceInWorkTo
Wn Synset Example Phrase With Position
wnSynsetExamplePhraseWithPosition

comment:
A MetaRelation and specialization of functionCorrespondingPredicate_Generic that is used to state that the relationship of the given function to its arguments is expressed by the given predicate.

(functionCorrespondsToPredicate FUNC PRED N) means that FUNC maps a given argument-sequence ARGS (say of length M) to the value VAL only if PRED holds of the (M+1 length) sequence ARGS-N-VAL, where ARGS-N-VAL is just like ARGS except for having VAL as its Nth member and having ARGS's Nth to Mth members as its (N+1)th to (M+1)th members. If PRED is a FunctionalPredicate, with its Nth argument-place being a "functional" one (see functionalInArgs), then the more specific relationship, functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical (q.v.) applies.

For example, (functionCorrespondsToPredicate MovieNamedFn properNameStrings 1) implies that (properNameStrings (MovieNamedFn "Gandhi") "Gandhi"), but (properNameStrings MahatmaGandhi "Gandhi") does not mean that MahatmaGandhi and (MovieNamedFn "Gandhi") represent the same thing. See also functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical, functionCorrespondingPredicate, functionCorrespondsToShuffledPredicate, and functionCorrespondsToShuffledPredicate_Symmetric.
label: Function Corresponds To Predicate
functionCorrespondsToPredicate

comment: An assertion of the form (literacyRateOfDuring PLACE PERSON-TYPE PERCENT DATE) states that measurements made of the population of the GeographicalRegion PLACE for the Date DATE indicate that the sub-population that is a set of #$PERSON-TYPE have a literacy rate of PERCENT. For example, an assertion of the form (literacyRateOfDuring Syria FemaleHuman (Percent 67) (YearFn 2005)) indicates that records indicate that during 2005, female citizens of Syria had a 67% literacy rate. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Literacy Rate Of During
literacyRateOfDuring

comment: A predicate used to construct specialized lexicons for a classification system, such as an ontology (see Ontology) or taxonomy (see Taxonomy). (conflateToInSystem THING-1 THING-2 SYSTEM) means that for purposes of mapping natural language to nodes in the system SYSTEM, natural language references to THING-1 should be interpreted as references to THING-2. For example, (conflateToInSystem CalendarQuarter FiscalQuarter #$InvestmentRelatedThingTaxonomy) means that references to CalendarQuarter (e.g., "quarter") should be understood as referring to FiscalQuarter. Such assertions result in additions to the lexicon for the system in question, which also makes it possible for the system and lexicon to be separated from the Cyc KB as a bundle, preserving the mappings in question.
label: Conflate To In System
conflateToInSystem

comment: (<font color="#ff0000">#$focalPositionForKEInteractionResoruce</font> FT POS RES) means that the term in position POS is the focal term in FT when it occurs as part of RES.
label: Focal Position For KE Interaction Resource
focalPositionForKEInteractionResource

comment: A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa5_1 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the fifth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the first argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 INST ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG1 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations.
label: Inter Arg Isa 5 1
interArgIsa5-1

comment: A predicate used to state the asked market price of a particular share of a company's Stock (of a particular "class", e.g. common or preferred). (stockPrice_Ask STOCK PRICE DATE EXCHANGE) means that PRICE is the lowest price per share that any owner or dealer of stock in STOCK is willing to sell for at DATE on the exchange EXCHANGE. Cf. stockPrice_Bid.
label: share price
stockPrice-Ask
Ke Salient Predicate
keSalientPredicate
comment: (keSalientPredicate PRED) says that PRED is salient in any #$RKFInteractionContextMicrotheory that sees the Microtheory where (keSalientPredicate PRED) is asserted. If a predicate PRED is salient in some RKF context R, then an example assertion involving PRED as the arg 0 will be made available for the SME to clone.

(exposedTo ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4) means that ARG1 is aware of/has been exposed to the individual object ARG2 at least in the way and/or to the degree specified by ARG3, and that the exposure occured in the event ARG4.
label: Exposed To In Event
exposedToInEvent
Use Reformulation Rule For DND Conversion
useReformulationRuleForDNDConversion

comment: The predicate playsRole is used to indicate the way that something participates in a particular situation. (playsRole SIT THING ROLE) means that in the Situation SIT, the item THING plays the Role ROLE. E.g., instances of HangGlider play the role of vehicle in instances of RecreationalActivity.
label: Plays Role
playsRole

comment: (dataForValveOfEventRecordsStenosisSeverity VALVE-DATA EVENT STENOSIS-SEVERITY) means that according to the VALVE-DATA associated with EVENT (an instance of CardiacCatheterization or Echocardiogram) the focal valve has the stenosis severity STENOSIS-SEVERITY.
label: Data For Valve Of Event Records Stenosis Severity
dataForValveOfEventRecordsStenosisSeverity

comment:
A MetaRelation predicate that relates two functions to the function that is their composition. (compositionOfFunctions COMP FUNC1 FUNC2) means that COMP is the composition of FUNC1 and FUNC2. That is, for any element DOM-EL inDomainOf FUNC1, the value of COMP applied to DOM-EL is the same as the result obtained by applying FUNC1 to DOM-EL, and then applying FUNC2 to that result. Symbolically, (COMP DOM-EL) = (FUNC2 (FUNC1 DOM-EL)).

For example, a function called "MaternalGrandfatherFn" could be construed as the composition of MotherFn with FatherFn: A is the maternal grandfather of B if and only if A is the father of the mother of B.

Note that in the general description above, the domain of COMP is identical to the domain of FUNC1, and the range (see RangeOfFunctionFn) of COMP is a (proper or otherwise) subset of the range of FUNC2. (Strictly speaking, the range of COMP is the set of elements of the range of FUNC2 that are the values for some element or other of the range of FUNC1 taken as arguments for FUNC2.) This means of course that COMP and FUNC1 must have the same arity (or both must be VariableArityFunctions); also the arity of FUNC2 must be 1.

See also the corresponding FunctionCompositionFn.
label: Composition Of Functions
compositionOfFunctions

comment: A TernaryPredicate relating a specialization of Stock, a MonetaryValue, and a Date. (priceOfShareAtTime STOCK PRICE DATE) means that the price of a share of STOCK on DATE is PRICE.
label: price quote
priceOfShareAtTime

comment: A predicate used for probability statements. (conditionallyIndependent_GivenSet PROPOSITION1 PROPOSITION2 SETOFPROPOSITIONS) means that, in the applicable Microtheory, PROPOSITION1 and PROPOSITION2 are conditionally independent of each other given the truth of all the propositions in the set SETOFPROPOSITIONS. That is, given the truth of the propositions in the set, the truth or falsehood of either of the two propostion arguments does not increase or decrease the derivedProbability that the other is true. They are, in a sense, irrelevant to each other when the propositions in SETOFPROPOSITIONS is known to be true. In most microtheories, generally, the conditionallyIndependent_GivenSet statement means that when all we know in the Microtheory are its accessible domainAssumptions, and the assertions in SETOFPROPOSITIONS, then the truths of the two formulae are probabilistically independent. See also conditionalProbability and conditionallyIndependent. To declare two propositions independent given a single proposition (which could be a conjunction), use conditionallyIndependentSentences. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.
label: Conditionally Independent Given Set
conditionallyIndependent-GivenSet

comment: (kePossibleRelation TERM1 TERM2 FORMULA) states that FORMULA would be a semantically well-formed way of relating the two terms TERM1 and TERM2. For example, (kePossibleRelation Canada France (bordersOn Canada France)) states that one way of possible relating Canada to France would be to say that they border on each other. Note that the FORMULA is not restricted to being known true, or even not known to be false, merely not trivially rejected by argument constraints. See also admittedSentence.
label: Ke Possible Relation
kePossibleRelation

comment:
(wordSenseExtension WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION) means that the use of the word WORD with speech part SPEECH-PART-2 to mean EXTENSION is an extension of one sense of WORD -- in particular the sense of WORD with speech part SPEECH-PART-1 and denotation DENOTATION. For example, 
(wordSenseExtension #$Chicken-TheWord CountNoun Chicken MassNoun Chicken_Meat)
