closestEventOfTypePriorTo

comment:
(temporalIndexForSentenceInMt TIME-INTERVAL PAR SENT MT) holds just in case SENT is true in MT at TIME-INTERVAL to the granularity determined by PAR. That is, iff SENT holds in MT at every time interval t that is subsumed by TIME-INTERVAL that subsumes some instance of PAR.

More formally:

(temporalIndexForSentenceInMt TIME-INTERVAL PAR SENT MT)

iff

(ist (MtSpace MT (MtTimeWithGranularityDimFn TIME-INTERVAL PAR)) SENT).
label: Temporal Index For Sentence In Mt
temporalIndexForSentenceInMt
Do Close Local Variables Scope
doCloseLocalVariablesScope
comment: A variable arity complex action predicate. (doCloseLocalVariablesScope PROGRAMMER FILE . VARIABLES) means that PROGRAMMER appends code to the end of computer file FILE that closes a scope in which VARIABLES are available. Compare with doOpenLocalVariablesScope.

A RuleMacroPredicate. (most_GenQuantRelnToType BINPRED SOC1 SOC2) means that most elements of SOC1 bear BINPRED to an element of SOC2 -- i.e., most elements ELEM1 of SOC1 are such that, for some element ELEM2 of SOC2, (BINPRED ELEM1 ELEM2). It is equivalent to the more complex form: 
(most SOC1
  (TheSetOf ?X
    (thereExists ?Y
      (and
        (elementOf ?Y SOC2)
        (BINPRED ?X ?Y))))).
For example, (most_GenQuantRelnToType knowsAbout UnitedStatesPerson UnitedStatesPresident) means that most Americans know about some U.S. president.

When SOC1 and SOC2 are Collections, use the more specialized relationMostExists.
label: Most Gen Quant Reln To Type
most-GenQuantRelnToType

comment: An instance of TemporallyQualifiableRelation. (expenseForType AGENT TYPE AMOUNT)<T> means that at the interval T (but not necessarily at any sub-interval of T), AMOUNT is the amount of money (MonetaryValue, q.v.) that counts as AGENT's total expenses for instances of TYPE. See expenseDuringPeriodForType for a temporally decontextualized version of expenseForType.
label: Expense For Type
expenseForType

comment: The corresponding predicate for the function ResourceRequestForOfDuringFn.
label: Resource Request For Of During
resourceRequestForOfDuring

comment: (verbSemTransTotal VERB NUM FRAME TRANS) means that the complete translation of word sense number NUM of VERB, appearing with subcategorization frame FRAME, is TRANS.
label: Verb Sem Trans Total
verbSemTransTotal

comment: If P, Q, R, and S are four points lying in a common plane, then (inCircle P Q R S) is true if and only if (counterClockwise P Q R) is true and S lies inside of the circle passing through P, Q, and R.
label: In Circle
inCircle

comment:
A MetaRelation and a generalization of functionCorrespondingPredicate (q.v.). functionCorrespondingPredicate_Generic differs from the more specific predicate both in that (i) its second argument-position is constrained only to be a Predicate rather than a FunctionalPredicate and (ii) it can hold between a function and a predicate even when the second is a more broadly defined relation than the first. Thus, for example, if FUNC is unary and is defined for THING (see inDomainOf), (functionCorrespondingPredicate_Generic FUNC PRED 2) entails (PRED THING (FUNC THING)). That is, FUNC's returning some VALUE for THING is a sufficient (though not a necessary) condition for PRED's holding between THING and VALUE.

When reifying an instance of Function_Denotational it is generally considered good ontological engineering practice also to reify a (or to find an already-existing) corresponding Predicate, as this enables one to describe more explicitly the relationship between the members of the function's domain and the associated members of its range (see relationDomain and relationRange). functionCorrespondingPredicate_Generic's particular reason-for-being is twofold. First, there are some functions for which the intuitively most appropriate-to-reify corresponding predicate is not functional (see functionalInArgs) in the relevant argument place. This is the case, for example, with the predicate streetIntersectionOf (which "corresponds" to the function StreetIntersectionFn), since it is possible for two given streets to intersect each other at more than one place. Second, the predicate might have more general argument-type constraints (see ArgTypePredicate) than the function. For example, one of the function's arguments might be constrained to be an instance of PartiallyTangible, while the corresponding argument of the predicate might plausibly be constrained to be an instance of the more general SpatialThing_Localized. In either of the above situations functionCorrespondingPredicate_Generic can be used to relate such functions to "corresponding" predicates, even though functionCorrespondingPredicate could not. Still, it is usually preferable to use the more specific functionCorrespondingPredicate or (even better) functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical when possible.
label: Function Corresponding Predicate Generic
functionCorrespondingPredicate-Generic

comment: (keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestion TERM) says that TERM is never to be offered as a precision/generalization suggestion during a UIA interaction.
label: Ke Irrelevant Precision Suggestion
keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestion

comment: (assignedEffortTime TASK AGENT TIME) says that an authorized person (usually the project manager of some parent task of TASK) has assigned AGENT to spend approximately TIME amount of time on TASK.
label: hours assigned
assignedEffortTime

comment: (few_GenQuantRelnFromType RELN COL2 COL1) means that for few of the instances X of COL1 there is an instance INST of COL2 such that (RELN INST X) holds.
label: Few Gen Quant Reln From Type
few-GenQuantRelnFromType

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relation with respect to a given thing and a given collection. (relationInstanceExistsMin BINPRED THING COL N) means that there exists at least N instances (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) of COL that THING bears the relation PRED to, such that (PRED THING INST(i)) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(thereExistAtLeast N ?INST (and (isa ?INST COL) (BINPRED THING ?INST))) .

For example, `(relationInstanceExistsMin physicalParts MyLeftHand Thumb 1)' means that my left hand has at least one thumb. Cf. relationExistsMinInstance, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Instance Exists Min
relationInstanceExistsMin

comment: (clockwise POINT-1 POINT-2 POINT-3) means that the straight line traversal originating at POINT-1, passing through POINT-2, and terminating at POINT-3 is in the clockwise direction. Equivalently, the straight line traversal originating at POINT-2, passing through POINT-1, and terminating at POINT-3 is in the counterclockwise direction. Consequently, this predicate is an ELRelation with expansion (counterClockwise POINT-2 POINT-1 POINT-3).
label: clockwise

comment: A negationPreds of sksiSentence, sksiUnknownSentence is used in inference to translate CycL queries into SQL queries that employ the SQL subquery expression "NOT EXISTS SELECT ...". (sksiUnknownSentence SENT) is true if and only if SENT can be entirely translated into one or more SQL queries to some StructuredKnowledgeSource that is applicable within the context of the inference, and the SQL query "NOT EXISTS SQL-SENT" returns true for every SQL translation SQL-SENT of SENT and for every such structured knowledge source.
label: Sksi Unknown Sentence
sksiUnknownSentence
background scenario which is currently being worked on
backgroundScenarioWorkedOn
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: background scenarios which is currently being worked on

comment: (sourceSchemaObjectID SOURCE SCHEMA OBJECT ID) relates an OBJECT in SOURCE to its unique identifier ID when SOURCE is interpreted logically by SCHEMA. See also the functions SourceSchemaObjectFn and SourceSchemaObjectIDFn.
label: Source Schema Object ID
sourceSchemaObjectID

comment: The functionCorrespondingPredicate for EvaluationOfAssertionByOnFn. (evaluationOfAssertionByOn EVALUATION ASSERT AGENT INT) identifies EVALUATION as the unique instance of Evaluating in which AGENT evaluates ASSERT at the time denoted by INT (which is the number of seconds elapsed since January 1, 1970).
label: Evaluation Of Assertion By On
evaluationOfAssertionByOn

comment:
A ternary FacetBasisPredicate (q.v.) that relates a collection to a binary predicate to a FacetingCollectionType such that the latter facets the collection on the basis of the predicate. (facetOfCollectionBasedOnBinaryPred COL BINPRED FACET) means that both (facets_Generic COL FACET) and (facetBasedOnBinaryPred FACET BINPRED) hold.

See also the corresponding function FacetOfCollectionBasedOnBinaryPredFn. And see facetOfCollectionBasedOnTypeBinaryPred and facetOfCollectionBasedOnBinaryPredInverse.
label: Facet Of Collection Based On Binary Pred
facetOfCollectionBasedOnBinaryPred
Backchain Encouraged
backchainEncouraged
comment: (backchainEncouraged PREDICATE) means that rules that conclude PREDICATE are most likely going to have to be used in order to prove literals involving PREDICATE. In other words, when performing inferences about literals involving PREDICATE, rules that conclude PREDICATE should be heuristically favored. See also backchainRequired, backchainDiscouraged, and backchainForbidden.

(receivesTreatmentFor ORGANISM TREATMENT AILMENT) means that ORGANISM, an instance of Organism_Whole, receives the TREATMENT, an instance of MedicalTreatmentEvent, for AILMENT, an instance of AilmentCondition, that it is the bodilyDoer of..
label: Receives Treatment For
receivesTreatmentFor

comment: Where CONFLICT is an ordered pair of assertions, (instanceDiffersFromPrototypicalInstance_Conflict INST TYPE SCRIPT CONFLICT) means that the pair of assertions in CONFLICT is such that the first assertion references INST, and the second assertion is in the deductive closure produced by forward-propagating the assertions in SCRIPT on a hypothesized instance of TYPE, and if INST were substituted for the hypothesized instance occurring in the second assertion, a contradiction would result.
label: Instance Differs From Prototypical Instance Conflict
instanceDiffersFromPrototypicalInstance-Conflict

comment: This predicate is the most general relation that is used to describe the logical or physical schema field value translations that determine the structural mapping between a knowledge source's physical and logical schemata. The argument constraints on this relation admit physical to physical, logical to physical, physical to logical, and logical to logical schema field value transformations. Each of these admitted translation types is specialized as its own predicate and the totality of these spec preds partition the graph of fieldTranslation.
label: Field Translation
fieldTranslation

comment: (typesCorrectlyBasePairedDuring N-TYPE1 N-TYPE2 EVT-TYPE) means that during instances of GeneticInformationTransferEvent, EVT-TYPE, instances of the two instances of NucleotideType, N-TYPE1 and N-TYPE2 stand in the relation of being base-paired correctly. Hydrogen bonds between some Nucleotides are more stable than others -- the stable ones are correctly base-paired. They are considered correctly base-paired with respect to the goal or norm of transmitting a cell's genes without alteration during a GeneticInformationTransferEvent.
label: Types Correctly Base Paired During
typesCorrectlyBasePairedDuring

comment: (uninterestingForArgInReln THING NUMBER RELATION) says that for any formula FORMULA of the form (RELATION ... THING ...) where THING appears in the NUMBERth argument place of FORMULA, FORMULA is uninteresting.
label: Uninteresting For Arg In Reln
uninterestingForArgInReln

comment: An assertion of the form (predicateInputModesForDetermination PRED N TYPE DET BIN-PRED) means that relative to the InductiveLogicProgrammingDetermination DET, the Nth argument of the Predicate PRED should bear the relationship BIN-PRED to TYPE.
label: Predicate Input Modes For Determination
predicateInputModesForDetermination

comment: (mereologicalSumOf2 SUM PART1 PART2) means that SUM is the mereological sum of PART1 and PART2, i.e., SUM, PART1 and PART2 are Individual such that PART1 is a part of SUM, PART2 is a part of SUM and any Individual which is a part of SUM at least have a part with PART1 or PART2 or both.
label: Mereological Sum Of 2
mereologicalSumOf2

comment: This predicate relates a Vaccine and a Microorganism to a probablity of effectiveness of the Vaccine in preventing infection by a members of that Microorganism. (<;vaccineEffectiveness> VACCINE MICROORGANISM PROBABILITY) means that vaccine VACCINE has a probability PROBABILITY of preventing infection by microorganism MICROORGANISM.
label: Vaccine Effectiveness
vaccineEffectiveness
Tactical Line From GIS
tacticalLine-FromGIS
comment: (tacticalLine_FromGIS TLINE) means that TLINE is an instance of TacticalLine, according to some GeographicInformationSystem to which Cyc has access.

This predicate is similar to resultSetCardinality in that it is used by the SKSI code to estimate the cost of querying the fields of a physical schema. More precisely, let SCHEMA denote a physical schema, let PF-1, PF-2, ..., PF-N, denote the physical fields of SCHEMA, and let SELECT_SET and WHERE_SET denote two disjoint subsets of (TheSet PF-1 PF-2 ... PF-N) and ..... Then (resultSetCardinality SCHEMA SELECT_SET WHERE_SET CONSTRAINTS NUM) means that NUM is the average cardinality of the result set returned from a query in which the fields in SELECT_SET left unbound and the fields of WHERE_SET are bound and the constraints expressed the CycL sentence in CONSTRAINTS are all satisfied.
label: Result Set Cardinality With Constraints
resultSetCardinalityWithConstraints

comment: A SpaceRegionPredicate and RelativeLocationalPredicate. (mutuallyOverlappingCircles CIRCLE1 CIRCLE2 CIRCLE3) means that the three CircularRegions CIRCLE1, CIRCLE2, and CIRCLE3 share a common part (see #$partOfSpaceRegion).
label: Mutually Overlapping Circles
mutuallyOverlappingCircles

comment: This is a type-constrained version of the primitive role equivalence predicate, equivRolePlayers. (equivRolePlayersOfType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2 ROLE1 ROLE2 ACTOR-TYPE) means that where SIT is an instance of SIT-TYPE, any actor of type ACTOR-TYPE that plays the role ROLE1 in an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE1 that is a subSituations of SIT is equivalent to any actor that plays the role ROLE2 in an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE2 that is a subSituations of SIT.
label: Equiv Role Players Of Type
equivRolePlayersOfType

comment: (unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsByDocTypePayerDuring DOCTYPE DRUGTYPE RXFILLTYPE PAYER PERIOD NUM) means that DOCTYPEs had NUM prescriptions of type RXFILLTYPE filled for DRUGTYPE and payed by PAYER during PERIOD. RXFILLTYPE may be FillingAPrescription_Retail, FillingAPrescription_MailOrder, FillingANewPrescription, FillingARefillPrescription, intersections of these, or merely FillingAPrescription.
label: Units Of Drug Prescriptions By Doc Type Payer During
unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsByDocTypePayerDuring

comment:
A QuaternaryPredicate. Where VOTING is a Voting, CANDIDATE is a Person, POSITION is a PersonTypeByPositionInOrg, and ORG is an Organization, (votesForCandidateForPositionInOrg VOTING CANDIDATE POSITION ORG) means that in performing VOTING, the performer of VOTING votes for CANDIDATE for POSITION in ORG. For example, 
(votesForCandidateForPositionInOrg BobsVotingIn2004Election GeorgeWBush
President_HeadOfGovernmentOrHeadOfState UnitedStatesOfAmerica)
means that in performing BobsVotingIn2004Election, the performer of BobsVotingIn2004Election (i.e. Bob) votes for George W. Bush for president of the United States.
label: Votes For Candidate For Position In Org
votesForCandidateForPositionInOrg

comment: (advisorToOn ARG1 ARG2 ARG3) means that ARG1 is the advisor of ARG2 in a matter ARG3 .
label: Advisor To On
advisorToOn

comment: (availableToAgentTypeForEventType AGENT-TYPE OBJECT EVENT-TYPE) means that OBJECT is typically available for agents of type AGENT-TYPE to use in events of type EVENT-TYPE. If an instance of AGENT-TYPE is capable of using OBJECT in an instance of EVENT-TYPE, nothing prevents that agent from choosing to use OBJECT in that event. Note that if OBJECT is available to an instance of AGENT-TYPE in an instance of EVENT-TYPE, that instance of AGENT-TYPE may still, for other reasons, be incapable of using OBJECT in that instance of EVENT-TYPE. Compare this predicate to availableForEvent and availableToAgentTypeForEvent.
label: Available To Agent Type For Event Type
availableToAgentTypeForEventType

comment: ARG3 is a circular layer, or barrier, between ARG1 and ARG2.
label: Circular Between
circularBetween

comment: This instance of ELRelation is an abbreviated version of inheritRolePlayersOfType_SubSitTypeToSubSitType (q.v.); (inheritRolePlayersOfType_SingleRole_SubSitTypeToSubSitType SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE1 ROLE SUBSITTYPE2 TYPE) is shorthand for (inheritRolePlayersOfType_SubSitTypeToSubSitType SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE1 ROLE SUBSITTYPE2 ROLE TYPE).
label: Inherit Role Players Of Type Single Role Sub Sit Type To Sub Sit Type
inheritRolePlayersOfType-SingleRole-SubSitTypeToSubSitType
Rewrite Expansion
rewriteExpansion
comment: (rewriteExpansion RULE) means that the left-hand side of RULE describes a way to rewrite the right-hand side of RULE. RULE must be an instance of CycLRuleAssertion in which the right and left-hand sides each consist of precisely one literal.

(sOEActionTypePermitted COMPONENT GRAPH ACTION-TYPE ROLE) means that an instance of ACTION-TYPE (which is a specialization of ComputerUserInteraction_SOE) may (given the current structure and semantics of the graph GRAPH of which COMPONENT is a component) be performed on COMPONENT ( an instance of GLFGraphComponent).
label: SOE Action Type Permitted
sOEActionTypePermitted

comment: (keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestion_TermGenl TERM) says the precision suggestor should never offer to generalize over TERM. So for example, if a SME asserts, (genls TERM COLL) for some Collection COLL, the precision suggestor should not offer to replace TERM with any of its specs. Likewise, if (keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestion_TermGenl PRED), and a SME asserts (relationAllExists PRED COL1 COL2), the precision suggestor should not offer to replace PRED with any of its genlPreds.
label: Ke Irrelevant Precision Suggestion Term Genl
keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestion-TermGenl

comment: This is the corresponding predicate for the function InterActorRelnSpecFn.
label: Inter Actor Reln Spec For Sit Type
interActorRelnSpecForSitType

comment: ARG3 is a list of substrings representing the parts of ARG2 which correspond to the assertion ARG1. ARG4 is a list of the starting indices within the actualTextOfPIT of ARG2 corresponding the positions of the ARG3 substrings.
label: Sub Text Mapping
subTextMapping
Has Always Been
hasAlwaysBeen
comment: hasAlwaysBeen is a ModalOperator, commonly referred to as a `past-tense operator'. For each #$ELSentence-Assertible PROP, (hasAlwaysBeen PROP) means that it has always been the case that PROP. For example, (hasAlwaysBeen `Amy and Bob are friends') means that Amy and Bob have always been friends. hasAlwaysBeen has a dualOperator: was. Note that (hasAlwaysBeen PROP) implies neither PROP nor (not PROP). Note also that to symbolize sentences like `Amy and Bob have never been friends', use (hasAlwaysBeen (not `Amy and Bob are friends')). Note, finally, that hasAlwaysBeen should be used only in instances of TemporalMicrotheory. Strictly speaking, (hasAlwaysBeen PROP) is true in a temporal microtheory MT with time index t and time parameter p (two `dimensions' in the context space, see mtTimeIndex and mtTimeIndexWithParameter) iff PROP is true in every temporal microtheory MT' with time index t' < t and time parameter p', which has the same values of all other dimensions as MT. Here t' < t means (startsAfterEndingOf t t'). It is easy to verify that (hasAlwaysBeen PROP) is true in a temporal microtheory MT with time index t and time parameter p iff PROP is true in the temporal microtheory MT' with time index (IntervalEndedByFn t) and time parameter TimePoint, which has the same values of all other dimensions as MT. (See other plain tense operators willAlwaysBe, was and willBe, and metric tense predicates was_Metric and willBe_Metric etc.)

A predicate for enumerating instances of RLModule to applied recursively before other modules are tried, and the order in which they are to be applied. (applyModuleFirstInReformulation SPEC MODULE INT) means the reformulator should use module MODULE when invoked by SPEC. The value of MODULE is passed to the CycLReformulator parameter :apply-first-recursively as a list. The value of INT is the place where MODULE appears in the list.
label: Apply Module First In Reformulation
applyModuleFirstInReformulation

comment: (relativeDensity STUFF1 TEMP1 STUFF2 TEMP2 RATIO) means that the ratio of STUFF1's density at TEMP1 to STUFF2's density at TEMP2 is RATIO. This concept is also known as "specific gravity".
label: Relative Density
relativeDensity
Pre Reformulation For Unknown Terms
preReformulationForUnknownTerms
comment: (preReformulationForUnknownTerms RULE) tells the fact entry tool to use RULE to pre-reformulate an assertion's unknown terms.

A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa based relationship holds between the third argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg3ResultIsa FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the third argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 ARG2 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg3ResultIsa _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultIsa.
label: Inter Arg 3 Result Isa
interArg3ResultIsa

comment: (modalFeatureTransfers PRED-1 PRED-2 OPERATOR) means that when (PRED-1 . ARGS) holds, (OPERATOR (PRED-2 . ARGS)) also holds, where OPERATOR is a modal operator. For example, (modalFeatureTransfers foundingAgent createdBy willAlwaysBe) means that when (foundingAgent ORGANIZATION AGENT) holds, (willAlwaysBe (createdBy ORGANIZATION AGENT)) holds.
label: Modal Feature Transfers
modalFeatureTransfers

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate that relates a predicate to a pair of collections such that each instance of the first (second) collection is related by the predicate to (from) some instance of the second (first) collection. Thus, (collRelation PRED COL1 COL2) is true if and only if both of these are true: 
  (relationAllExists PRED COL1 COL2)

  (relationExistsAll PRED COL1 COL2)
For example, 
  (collRelation groupMembers PlanetarySystem Sun)
means that (i) every planetary system includes a sun and (ii) every sun is a member of a planetary system.

collRelation is used to represent plural sentences. For instance, "The cats slept" means that for some (non-empty non-singleton) class of cats and some (non-empty) class of sleeping events, each cat in the cat-class was in the bodilyDoer relation to some event in the sleeping-class, and each sleeping was in the inverse relation to some cat in the cat-set.
label: Coll Relation
collRelation
label
comment: A natural-language representation for a concept that is both human readable and readable by the Cyc inference engine. These terms are not guaranteed to refer to the same concept across time but are guaranteed to be consistent within a particular OWL export. Use "cycAnnot:externalID" for unambiguously referring to a concept across OWL exports or across Cyc inference engines.

This predicate relates two things located in a city or town in terms of the number of blocks away they are from each other. (distanceInBlocksOfStreet OBJ1 OBJ2 N) means that in order to get from OBJ1 to OBJ2 by the shortest route using city streets, one must travel a total of N instances of BlockOfStreet. OBJ1 and OBJ2 must each be onPath some instance or other of Street_Generic, and if they are on different streets, those streets must be (directly or indirectly) connected to each other within the same StreetSystem. Since the lengths of street blocks vary considerably, a given distance in street blocks cannot be generally associated with any specific absolute distance. Still, this predicate is useful for rough estimates of, and comparisons between, distances.
label: Distance In Blocks Of Street
distanceInBlocksOfStreet
Rendering Properties For Node In System
renderingPropertiesForNodeInSystem

comment: (hasCardinalityManyDeviceTypeComponents SYSTEM NUMBER DEVICE-TYPE) means that NUMBER many instances of DEVICE-TYPE are components of SYSTEM.
label: Has Cardinality Many Device Type Components
hasCardinalityManyDeviceTypeComponents

comment: (productionValueOfIndustryDuring REGION COL THING MONEY) means that the instance of MonetaryValue MONEY is a measure of the value of all the goods and services produced by the specialization of the Industry_Localized COL in the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. Note that COL can range from a broad economic sector, such as agriculture, manufacturing, or services to a more specific segment of the economy such as the automobile industry. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event.
label: Production Value Of Industry During
productionValueOfIndustryDuring
Relevant Path
relevantPath
comment: In Workarounds problems, (relevantPath ?PATH) means that PATH is the path on which the interdicted will move at the end of the workaround operations. Generally, relevantPath will be an emplaced bridge or the gap containing a fording site.

(queryStringForUserInSession STRING USER SESSION) says that in the course of the interactive computer session SESSION, USER, the user in session, posed a question to the system, the string for which has been recorded as STRING.
label: Query String For User In Session
queryStringForUserInSession
Decontextualized Predicate
decontextualizedPredicate
comment: (decontextualizedPredicate PRED) states that PRED is a predicate which is context-independent. In effect, any use of PRED can be lifted into any microtheory. Predicates which are labelled with decontextualizedPredicate typically have an argument which either implicitly or explicitly provides the implied context. A good example of such a predicate is ist.
(mtDimensionComplementValue MT DIM POLY-MT) means that the PolyadicMicrotheory, POLY-MT, is the part of MT left once the DIM dimension has been factored out. cf mtDimensionValue.
label: Mt Dimension Complement Value
mtDimensionComplementValue

comment: (istMakesLikelihood INDPROP DEPPROP PROB) means that the truth of INDPROP in the context of the assertion makes the likelihood that DEPROP is also true in the context of the assertion PROB.
label: Ist Makes Likelihood
istMakesLikelihood

comment:
An instance of QuaternaryPredicate. (pathTraversableFromToBy PATH FROM TO TYPE) implies that (i)the Path_Simple PATH connects FROM and TO (so that (pathBetween PATH FROM TO)) holds), and (ii) PATH is capable of serving as a pathway for instances of TYPE between FROM and TO.

Note that this predicate is _not_ commutative in its second and third arguments, since a type of movement from one location to another might not be reversible. For example, one can get to the top of a stairway from the bottom, but not to the bottom from the top, by ascending that stairway (see the collection AscendingStairs).
label: Path Traversable From To By
pathTraversableFromToBy

comment: (unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsByDocDuring DOC DRUGTYPE RXFILLTYPE PERIOD NUM) means that Prescriber DOC has had prescriptions of type RXFILLTYPE filled for NUM 'units' of DRUGTYPE during PERIOD. For TabletDrugs, the 'unit' is a single Tablet, while for fluids, creams, and inhalents, the 'unit' is mg of active ingredient. RXFILLTYPE may be FillingAPrescription-Retail, FillingAPrescription_MailOrder, FillingANewPrescription, FillingARefillPrescription, intersections of these, or merely FillingAPrescription.
label: Units Of Drug Prescriptions By Doc During
unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsByDocDuring

comment: (waitingListFor WAIT_LIST PRED EVENT_TYPE) means that the instance of WaitingList, WAIT_LIST, is a list of items waiting to play the role PRED in an event of type EVENT_TYPE. Normally an agent on a waiting list wishes to play the role PRED in an event of type EVENT_TYPE and is intentionally on the waiting list. This is not always the case: consider a waiting list to be a maleficiary of a firing squad.
label: Waiting List For
waitingListFor

comment: (<font color="#ff0000">#$keIrrelevantTermCPOFTerm</font> TERM) should be used for all terms created for CPOF that are generally not meant to be seen in a UIA interaction.  This includes terms created only for specific demos and deliverables such as BPVI.
label: Ke Irrelevant CPOF Term
keIrrelevantCPOFTerm

comment: An instance of QuaternaryPredicate. comment: This QuaternaryPredicate is used to state the CycL and English (template) versions of queries used by various Cyc database applications and prototypes. ARG1 is the type of object the query is about. ARG2 is the type of information the query is asking for (the type of information the answer will consist of). ARG3 is a CycL query expression. ARG4 is a list consisting of a keyword followed by an English query (template) string. The keyword may be :text or :tabular. It indicates how the query answer should be formatted. If the keyword is :text, the English query string should contain the Cyc variable ?subject, which denotes the object being profiled (the object the query is about). This object will be an instance of ARG1. If the keyword is :tabular, the English query string will be followed by two lists: a list of field (column) name strings, and a list of Cyc variables. Each field name string corresponds to one of the variables. The corresponding elements must occur in the same positions in their respective lists. This arcane syntax allows the answer to be formatted as a table, if so desired.
label: Profile DB Queries
profileDBQueries

genlMtSpecification

comment: (possessedWeaponRange_Max AGENT WEAPON-TYPE RANGE) means that the weapons of type WEAPON-TYPE that AGENT possesses have the maximal range RANGE. For example, suppose that AGENT possesses TYPE(1)-missiles, ..., TYPE(n)-missiles, whose maximal ranges (see weaponEffectiveRange-Max) are, respectively, RANGE(1), ..., RANGE(n). Then, if these are the only types of missiles that AGENT possesses, we have (possessedWeaponRange_Max AGENT Missile RANGE) where RANGE is the maximal one among RANGE(1), ..., RANGE(n). Actually, RANGE is the same as (Maximum (TheSetOf TYPE (and (genls TYPE Missile) (relationInstanceExistsMany possesses AGENT TYPE))) (FunctionToArg 2 weaponEffectiveRange_Max)).

Normally, the unification would take place in a formula built truth-functionally from FORMULA-1 and FORMULA-2. This predicate makes no assumptions about how that larger formula is constructed.

comment: (physicallyCapableOf OBJ SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that OBJ can physically play ROLE in a situation of SIT-TYPE. This does not imply that OBJ is capable of doing so in the sense of know-how (see skillCapableOf), nor does it mean that OBJ has the resources to do so (see resourceCapableOf). For instance, (anatomicallyCapableOf MarthaThePassengerPigeon Flying_FlappingWings doneBy), but if Martha were caged, then (not (physicallyCapableOf MarthaThePassengerPigeon Flying_FlappingWings doneBy)). Similarly, if Martha's feet were stuck in lime, she would also not be physically capable of flying. It is this sense of capability that this predicate is meant to express.

comment: A ternary predicate that relates a type of chemical substance to the types of atoms and the number of atoms of each type that make up its instances. (completeAtomicComposition_List SUBST ELEMENT-LIST SUBSCRIPT-LIST), where ELEMENT-LIST and SUBSCRIPT-LIST are lists of the same length, means that instances of SUBST are composed of the types of atom listed in ELEMENT-LIST, in the respective proportions corresponding to the numbers in SUBSCRIPT-LIST. ELEMENT-LIST is of the form (TheList ATOM-TYPE-1 ... ATOM-TYPE-N), where each ATOM-TYPE-K (for K >= 1 and <= N) is an instance of ElementStuffTypeByNumberOfProtons and each NUMBER-K is a positive integer. As an example, (completeAtomicComposition_List CarbonDioxide (TheList Carbon Oxygen) (TheList 1 2)) is true, and entails (atomicComposition (q.v.) CarbonDioxide Oxygen 2).
label: complete atomic composition list
completeAtomicComposition-List

comment:
A unary predicate, whose argument-place is "quoted" (see quotedArgument), that is used to state that a given CycL non-atomic term does not denote anything. Where NAT has the form (FUNC ARG1..ARGN), (undefined NAT) means that NAT has no denotatum because FUNC (the function denoted by the main functor in NAT) returns no value for the argument sequence ARG1..ARGN.

Typically, NAT will be semantically well-formed (see CycLNonAtomicTerm_Assertible) but will fail to denote because FUNC is a PartialFunction (q.v.) that is not defined for ARG1...ARGN. For example, (undefined (QuotientFn 5 0)) holds because division is undefined for divisor zero. Similarly, (undefined (BorderBetweenFn Canada Mexico)) holds because Canada does not border Mexico, and so there is no such border as that which the term (BorderBetweenFn Canada Mexico) purports to describe.
label: Undefined
undefined

comment: (marketSupplyShortage MARKET PRODUCT QUANTITY) means that in MARKET there is a shortage of QUANTITY instances of PRODUCT.
label: supply shortage
marketSupplyShortage

comment: (importFromThroughAmountDuring REGION1 PRODUCT-TYPE REGION2 PT THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE imported by the GeographicalRegion REGION1 from the GeographicalRegion REGION2 through the instance of PartiallyTangible PT (on their way from REGION2) during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. PT might, in the case of oil imports, for instance, be a GeographicalRegion or a Pipeline. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of automobile imports, for example, AMOUNT might be an Integer indicating the number of cars imported. In the case of oil imports, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil imported (by REGION1 from REGION2 through PT), or it might be an instance of MonetaryValue indicating the monetary value of all the oil imported. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of import of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION1 from REGION2 through PT during the temporal extent of THING. Oil imports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day or in terms of so many dollars per day (again, indicating the monetary value of the oil).
label: Import From Through Amount During
importFromThroughAmountDuring

comment:
genlPredsWRTQuotedArgs is used to express a genlPreds -like relationship between a predicate SPEC-PRED that has at least one quoted argument place (see quotedArgument) and a predicate GENL-PRED of the same arity that

1) has argIsa/argGenl constraints that are at least as general as those of SPEC-PRED,

2) is not quoted in at least one of the argument places in which SPEC-PRED is, and

3) is only quoted in argument places in which SPEC-PRED is also quoted.

As such, GENL-PRED need not have any quoted argument places.

In (genlPredsWRTQuotedArgs SPEC-PRED GENL-PRED SET), SET is the set of integers that correspond to quoted argument places in SPEC-PRED that are not quoted in GENL-PRED, thereby indicating a recipe for deriving a sentence GENL-SENT whose arg0 is GENL-PRED from a sentence SPEC-SENT whose arg0 is SPEC-PRED: First, each argument in SPEC-SENT occuring in the Nth argument place, where N is neither 0 nor a member of LIST, will occur in the Nth argument place in GENL-SENT. All other non-0 arguments in SPEC-SENT, which by definition occur in the Mth argument place, where M is an element of SET, will appear as explicitly quoted arguments in GENL-SENT, in those same argument places. For example, 

   (genlPredsWRTQuotedArgs cycLActors situationConstituents (TheSet 2))
entails that whenever 
   (cycLActors ExaminingTheCycLTermHashDollarDog Dog)
holds, 
   (situationConstituents ExaminingTheCycLTermHashDollarDog (Quote Dog)).
follows.
label: Genl Preds WRT Quoted Args
genlPredsWRTQuotedArgs

comment: (feelsTowardsEvent AGT EVT EMOTYPE DEGREE) means that the IntelligentAgent AGT feels a feeling of the EmotionalQuantityType EMOTYPE towards the Event EVT, with intensity DEGREE. Note: the first argument can be a non-human intelligent agent, such as a dog or a company, because we often ascribe feelings and emotions to them, and they often behave consistently with having such feelings and emotions. See also feelsTowardsObjectToDegree.
label: Feels Towards Event
feelsTowardsEvent

comment: (unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsByDocTypeDuring DOC-TYPE DRUG-PROD PRESC-TYPE PERIOD NUM) means that, during the TimeInterval PERIOD, MedicalCareProfessionals of type, DOC-TYPE, had DrugPrescriptions for NUM units of DRUG-PROD filled.

unitsOfDrugPrescriptionsByDocTypeDuring
Patient ID For Patient Treated Ternary
patientIDForPatientTreated-Ternary

comment:
An instance of #$CompletenessGroundsPredicate (q.v.) that is used to state, about a collection or predicate whose extent is inferentially complete (see #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate), that the completeness derives mainly from a conventional stipulation, rather than from the nature of the items in the extent themselves.

For example, (completelyAssertedCollection DayOfWeekType) holds, and so does (completeByConvention DayOfWeekType). In contrast, completeByConvention does not hold of the completely-decidable collection Integer. Cf. completeByNature.

See also the specializations completeByExternalConvention and completeByCycConvention.
label: Complete By Convention
completeByConvention

comment: (sentenceIsFalse SENTENCE) means that a reviewer who looked at the CycLPropositionalSentence SENTENCE felt that the information content of the sentence is (subjectively) False.
label: Sentence Is False
sentenceIsFalse

comment: (citySectionBoundedBy SECTION ST(1)...ST(N)) means that SECTION is an urban region that is completely bounded by parts of each of the streets ST(1) - ST(N). The relative order (but not the absolute position) of the 2nd and higher arguments here is important: it should be physically possible to circle SECTION completely once in a generally clockwise fashion by starting along ST(1) and turning, successively, onto ST(2), ST(3), ..., ST(N), and finally back onto ST(1). In practice, the number of streets N will usually be between 3 and 5 (and the shape of the region returned roughly an N-gon), though N can be as small as 1 if ST(1) is a loop. To have this predicate correctly relate a given street-bounded city section SECTION to the N streets that border it, one can fill its second argument-place with any of these N streets, and then continue to fill in the other argument-places according to the order in which one would travel along the other N-1 streets if one were circling SECTION in a generally clockwise fashion (i.e. by making mostly right-hand turns). See also CitySectionFn, cityGridSectionBoundedBy, and cityBlockBoundedBy.
label: City Section Bounded By
citySectionBoundedBy

comment:
This predicate is used to state that a certain directed path goes from one given point to another. (pathFromToInSystem PATH X Y SYS) means that, in SYS, PATH goes from X to Y, and this does not go against the directions of any of PATH's constituent links.

To be precise, where SYS is a semi-directed path system, PATH is a path in SYS, and both X and Y are points in SYS, pathFromToInSystem can be defined inductively as follows:

(i) For each link LINK in SYS, (pathFromToInSystem LINK X Y SYS) iff (linkFromToInSystem LINK X Y SYS).

(ii) For each link LINK in SYS, and for any points A and B in SYS such that either (betweenOnPath B A Y LINK) or (betweenOnPath A X B LINK) holds, (linkFromToInSystem LINK X Y SYS) holds iff (pathFromToInSystem (SubPathBetweenFn PATH A B) A B SYS) holds.

(iii) If both (pathFromToInSystem PATH1 X Y SYS) and (pathFromToInSystem PATH2 Y Z SYS) hold, and if no point in SYS except Y is on both PATH1 and PATH2, then (pathFromToInSystem PATH X Z SYS) holds, where PATH is the concatenation of PATH1 and PATH2.
label: Path From To In System
pathFromToInSystem

comment:
A ternary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate and a specialization of completeExtentEnumerableForValueInArg (q.v.) that can apply to a predicate and a specified value for a specified argument-place. (completeExtentAssertedForValueInArg PRED VALUE N) means that for every sequence of arguments that PRED holds of and whose Nth member is VALUE, there is an explicit assertion to that effect in the Cyc Knowledge Base. Thus, if asked a query of the form (PRED ... VALUE ...), where VALUE appears in the Nth argument-position and all of the other positions (>= 1) are filled with variables, the Inference Engine -- simply via lookup of assertions in the KB -- can return an extensionally complete list of binding-sequences for those variables. That is, for every sequence SEQ in PRED's extension whose Nth member is VALUE (and for nothing else), the returned list contains a sequence of bindings (i.e. CycL terms) whose members denote, pointwise, the members of SEQ excepting VALUE.

For example, (completeExtentAssertedForValueInArg hasMembers InternationalMonetaryFund 1) holds, as all the members of the International Monetary Fund are asserted to be such in the KB.

If PRED's extent is completely asserted for VALUE in the Nth argument and a given sequence of bindings <TERM1, ..., TERM(N-1), TERM(N+1), ...> (whose length matches the arity of PRED, if fixed) is not returned for the above query, that fact consitutes a strong argument for the truth of the negation (not (PRED TERM1 ... TERM(N-1) VALUE TERM(N+1) ...)). But note that it is not a conclusive argument: the normally-reliable "unique name assumption" might fail here, and a term TERMi could conceivably denote something that Cyc can prove a member of something in the extent of PRED only under some _other_ CycL name it has. For suppose Pace resides in Texas, but nobody has told that to Cyc. The KB contains the assertion '(cityInState CityOfDallasTX Texas_State)'; but it might nevertheless fail to contain the equally true sentence '(cityInState CityOfDallasTX (StateOfResidenceFn #$Pace))'.

See also completeExtentAsserted.
label: Complete Extent Asserted For Value In Arg
completeExtentAssertedForValueInArg
subPropertyOf: Complete Extent Enumerable For Value In Arg

comment: A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keStrongSuggestionPreds_SpecsOfType COL BINPRED TYPE) means that for every known (i.e. Cyc-reified) instance INST of COL, it is strongly suggested that there be some reified specialization SPEC of TYPE such that (BINPRED INST SPEC) is known in the Knowledge Base.

Use likesRoleInEventType to represent an Agent_PartiallyTangible's relation to collections of Events.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: will have liked role in game

likesRoleInActivityCW

comment: A TernaryPredicate that relates an Agent_Generic to an Agent_Generic to a CycLSentence_Assertible. (givesSupportToAgentForGoal AGT1 AGT2 PROP) means that AGT1 provides support to AGT2's effort to make PROP the case. For example, (givesSupportToAgentForGoal Alice Bob (educationLevel Bob PhDLevel)) means that Alice supports Bob in his effort to obtain a PhD.

comment:
(sentencesInducedByProgram_OverSubsetsOfPopulatedPreds PROG PRED-COUNT COMBO-COUNT MT SENTENCE-SET)) means that, after the ILP program PROG iterates through the extent in microtheory MT of each of the PRED-COUNT predicates in the sets of size COMBO-COUNT, PROG has sufficient evidence to induce the sentences in the set SENTENCE-SET.

At the code level, the size of PRED-COUNT is typically set to 6, and the size of COMBO-COUNT is typically set to 3. These are generally the values that should be passed: using any other values could be very expensive.
label: Sentences Induced By Program Over Subsets Of Populated Preds
sentencesInducedByProgram-OverSubsetsOfPopulatedPreds

comment:
A binary LogicalConnective (q.v.) that corresponds to the material implication operator of propositional calculus. The implies relation takes two CycLSentence_Assertibles as its arguments; and the syntactic result of applying the term 'implies' to two sentences is itself a sentence, called a "conditional" or "implication". A sentence of the form (implies ANTECEDENT CONSEQUENT) is true if and only if ANTECEDENT is false or CONSEQUENT is true (or both). Equivalently: it is not the case that ANTECEDENT is true and CONSEQUENT is false. For example, 

  (implies
    (knows Muffet #$Patches-Cat)
    (likesAsFriend Muffet #$Patches-Cat))

means that if Muffet knows Patches then she likes him.

Cf. the predicate sentenceImplies, which is not a logical connective, and is primarily used in rules involving quantification over CycL sentences.
label: Implies (relationship)
implies

comment:
A KBDependentRelation (q.v.) and specialization of knownSentence (q.v.) that is used to state that a given CycLSentence_Assertible is virtually asserted in some StructuredKnowledgeSource currently available via SKSI in some accessible Microtheory.

This predicate enables Cyc to select a subset of information when answering queries, filtering out the assertions which only exist in the KB proper.
label: Sksi Sentence
sksiSentence

comment: If SPACE is a topological space with base set BASE (see baseSetOfTopologicalSpace), NEIGHBORHOOD is a subset of BASE, and SET is a subset of NEIGHBORHOOD, then NEIGHBORHOOD is a neighborhood of SET if and only if there exists an open set OPENSET of SPACE which is a subset of NEIGHBORHOOD and contains SET as a subset. In CycL, this relation is expressed as (neighborhoodOfSetInTopologicalSpace SET NEIGHBORHOOD SPACE).
label: Neighborhood Of Set In Topological Space
neighborhoodOfSetInTopologicalSpace

comment: (halfReaction SUBST1 SUBST2 VOLTAGE) means that the half reaction representing the reduction of SUBST1 into SUBST2 has standard reduction potential VOLTAGE. SUBST1 and SUBST2 must be composed entirely of the same ElementStuffTypeByNumberOfProtons. SUBST1 must have a more positive electronic charge than SUBST2. Note that this is a significant but useful restriction of the general concept of half reactions.
label: half-reaction reduction
halfReaction

comment: (hasVerbAsMember VERBCLASS LEXICALWORD SENSENUMBER) means that VERBCLASS has LEXICALWORD with sense SENSENUMBER as a member. This predicate is used to link up verbs with the classes to which they belong. See Beth Levin's text *English Verb Classes and Alternations* for more on how to group verbs into classes -- the NL Dept. library has a copy. When using this predicate, remember that while a particular verb may belong to many different verb classes, a particular verb sense belongs to only one VerbClass. The following example asserts that sense 0 of the lexical word #$Give-TheWord is a member of the Give_VerbClass. (Note: To find out which sense you need, look at the denotation and various semTrans-type assertions the word is involved in.) (hasVerbAsMember Give_VerbClass #$Give-TheWord 0)
label: Has Verb As Member
hasVerbAsMember

comment: (providerPerformsProceduresDuring-Count ROLE SURG PROC-TYPE DATE INT) means that the surgeon or group of surgeons SURG played the role ROLE in exactly INT surgical procedures that were instances of COLL during the time period DATE.
label: Provider Performs Procedures During Count
providerPerformsProceduresDuring-Count
subPropertyOf: Agent Plays Role In Events During Count

comment: (suggestionGenlClassOrderedBy TERM REL NUM) means that if a specialization of TERM has suggestions generated for it, then it is reasonable to generate alternate hierarchical suggestion views with those suggestions using REL as the ordering relation. One example use is in generating hierarchical drop down menus for the CAE or FET. Arg3 indicates the direction of the ordering, e.g. terms ordered via genls are typically ordered more general to more specific; from arg2 to arg1, while terms ordered via physicalPartTypes are ordered from whole to part; from arg1 to arg2.
label: Suggestion Genl Class Ordered By
suggestionGenlClassOrderedBy

comment: termTemplate_Reln relates a class of natural language utterances to CycL terms. Unlike termTemplate, there is a slot for the Cyc Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation. For example, (termTemplate NPTemplate PicturesFn ("pictures" "of" (NPTemplate :obj)) (PicturesFn :obj)) would map "pictures of The Beatles" to (PicturesFn TheBeatles_MusicGroup).
label: Term Template Reln
termTemplate-Reln
unspecified unit structure
structureOfUnitUnspecified
comment: In the context of a particular COA, (structureOfUnitUnspecified UNIT) means that the number and type of the subunits of UNIT are not specified. UNIT is represented in the sketch of the COA as a non-TOGG (Task Organized Combination Graphics) unit and its #$combatForceValueOfUnit can be derived directly from its MilitaryUnitSpecialtyType and #$MilitaryEchelon level.

(muchGreaterThanWRTScale LARGE SMALL SCALE) says that the ScalarInterval LARGE is much greater than the ScalarInterval SMALL, in so far as the standard by which we make the comparison is SCALE. For example, (muchGreaterThanWRTScale (Foot_UnitOfMeasure 60) (Foot_UnitOfMeasure 15) LengthOfBoat) says that 60 feet is much greater than 15 feet where lengths of boats are concerned.
label: Much Greater Than WRT Scale
muchGreaterThanWRTScale

comment:
A ternary FacetBasisPredicate (q.v.) that relates a collection to a type-level binary predicate to a FacetingCollectionType such that the latter facets the collection on the basis of the inverse of the predicate. (facetOfCollectionBasedOnBinaryPredInverse COL BINPRED FACET) means that both (facets_Generic COL FACET) and (facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse FACET BINPRED) hold.

See also facetOfCollectionBasedOnTypeBinaryPred.
label: Facet Of Collection Based On Type Binary Pred Inverse
facetOfCollectionBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse

comment: (tourTransitTransporterType TOUR MOVETYPE TRANSPORTERTYPE) means that TOUR is supposed to include a TransportationEvent of type MOVETYPE using a transporter of type TRANSPORTERTYPE.
label: Tour Transit Transporter Type
tourTransitTransporterType

comment: (humanMeasurements PERSON SIZE-TYPE SIZE) holds just in case PERSON is SIZE with respect to the dimension given by SIZE-TYPE. Since SIZE is the collection of people who wear that size, it follows that (isa PERSON SIZE).
label: Human Measurements
humanMeasurements

comment: (cycVersionWithFeatureSetSystemAndKB PROG SET SYS-STRING KB) means that PROG is the version of CycProgram created from all and only the CycProgramFeatures that are elements of SET in the Cyc system number STRING, with the instance of CycKB KB. Cf. CycVersionWithFeatureSetSystemAndKBFn.
label: Cyc Version With Feature Set System And KB
cycVersionWithFeatureSetSystemAndKB

comment: (nthTokenInTokenization TOKENIZATION I TOKEN) denotes that within the context of the particular TOKENIZATION, the TOKEN has the position I, where I is an integer between 0 and the value N denoted by (numberOfTokensInTokenization TOKENIZATION N).
label: Nth Token In Tokenization
nthTokenInTokenization

comment: (numberOfPrescriptionsByDocTypePayerDuring DOCTYPE DRUGTYPE RXFILLTYPE PAYER PERIOD NUM) means that DOCTYPEs had NUM prescriptions of type RXFILLTYPE filled for DRUGTYPE and paid by PAYER during PERIOD. RXFILLTYPE may be FillingAPrescription_Retail, FillingAPrescription_MailOrder, FillingANewPrescription, FillingARefillPrescription, intersections of these, or merely FillingAPrescription.
label: Number Of Prescriptions By Doc Type Payer During
numberOfPrescriptionsByDocTypePayerDuring

comment: (minimizeExtentForArg PREDICATE THING N) means that if we can't prove some positive literal in which THING is the Nth arg to PREDICATE, there is a very weak argument -- an assumption -- for the negation of that literal. Assumptions are weak arguments that lose against any other kind of argument. See also minimizeExtent.
label: Minimize Extent For Arg
minimizeExtentForArg

comment: (phoneticVariantOfSuffix SUFFIX STRING BASE-TYPE) means that STRING is the suffixString of the LexicalSuffix SUFFIX whenever it is combined with a BaseWordForm having phonetic feature BASE-TYPE. Example: (phoneticVariantOfSuffix Fy_TheSuffix "ify" (BaseWordFormsEndingWithLetterSequenceFn "y"))
