(effectOfActionIf_Props ACTION COND EFFECT) means that if COND is true in the context in which ACTION occurs, then ACTION makes EFFECT true. This predicate was designed to be used in the specification of planning domains (see PlanningDomainMicrotheory). ACTION should be an atomic sentence with an ActionPredicate as the formula operator (i.e. in the arg0 position). See also the binary predicate effectOfAction_Props.
label: Effect Of Action If Props
effectOfActionIf-Props

comment: (averageIncubationPeriod INFECTION-TYPE ORG-TYPE TIME-QUANTITY) means that, on average, the duration of the time period between the initial onset of an infection of type INFECTION-TYPE and the point at which the infection becomes clinically symptomatic for an instance of ORG-TYPE is TIME-QUANTITY.
label: Average Incubation Period
averageIncubationPeriod

comment: (distanceTravelledByInInterval OBJ INT DIST) means that during the time interval INT, OBJ travels the distance DIST.
label: Distance Travelled By In Interval
distanceTravelledByInInterval

comment: (temporallyBetween TEMP-THING EARLY LATE) means that TEMP-THING starts after the end of EARLY and ends before the start of LATE. EARLY and LATE are restricted to instances of TemporallyExtendedThing.
label: between
temporallyBetween

comment: (supplyThroughAmountDuring PT1 COL PT2 THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the Collection COL with which the instance of PartiallyTangible PT1 is supplied through the instance of PartiallyTangible PT2 (on their way from their origin) during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. Like the predicate suppliedWith (q.v.), supplyThroughAmountDuring is very general. In various assertions PT1 might, for instance, be a Cell, a Person, a Business, or a GeographicalRegion; and PT2 might, for example, be a Hose, a Railway, a GeographicalRegion, or a BloodVessel. The range of possible supplies is similarly broad. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. If AMOUNT is a Rate, AMOUNT indicates the average rate of supply of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE to PT1 through PT2 during the temporal extent of THING.
label: Supply Through Amount During
supplyThroughAmountDuring
Non Functional External Synonomy
nonFunctionalExternalSynonomy
comment: (nonFunctionalExternalSynonomy ASSERT) means that the synonymous external concept assertion declared by ASSERT is non-functional, in the sense that there is an additional valid synonymous external concept assertion, ASSERT2, such that both ASSERT and ASSERT2 map the same things to different external concepts in a single external knowledge source.

(useReformulationRuleForSimplification RULE) indicates that in the mt in which this is asserted or a specMt thereof, the CycLSimplifier (part of the CycCanonicalizer) will use RULE to help simplify CycLExpressions.
label: Use Reformulation Rule For Simplification
useReformulationRuleForSimplification

comment: (productCompetitors ARG1 ARG2 ARG3) means that the agents ARG1 and ARG2 are competing to be the providers/sellers of a product type ARG3.
label: Product Competitors
productCompetitors

comment: (subcollectionOfWithRelationToType SUPER-COL PREDICATE TYPE SUB-COL) means that SUB-COL is the collection of all instances INSTANCE of SUPER-COL for which (PREDICATE INSTANCE THING) holds for some instance (THING) of TYPE. See the function that corresponds to this predicate, SubcollectionOfWithRelationToTypeFn.
label: Subcollection Of With Relation To Type
subcollectionOfWithRelationToType

comment: This predicate acts as a switch for Factivore source requirements. (sourcesForTopicInProject TOPIC SOURCE-TYPE PROJECT) means that when a Factivore user is logged into the system with a current project of PROJECT, all templates gathered into the user's session under TOPIC will require the user to enter source information, and the sources used will be instances of SOURCE-TYPE. For example, (sourcesForTopicInProject #$TKBTemplate-Attack #$FactEntrySourceType-TKB #$TKBProject) means that, if the user's current project is #$TKBProject, the Factivore will require source information for all templates that describe instances of #$TKBTemplate-Attack, and that the sources used will be instances of instances of #$FactEntrySourceType-TKB.
label: Sources For Topic In Project
sourcesForTopicInProject

comment: genFormat_Precise is similar to genFormat, but is intended to allow generation of more verbose and/or precise English from CycL formulas such that the resulting English can be uniquely identified with the single CycL formula from which it was produced.
label: Gen Format Precise
genFormat-Precise

comment: (documentURLBasePath APP COMPUTER BASEPATH) means that an instantiation of APP is installed on COMPUTER, and that BASEPATH is the default base URL of all document files managed by APP on COMPUTER. The absolute URL of a file can be determined by appending its full relative pathname to its base URL. The full relative pathname for a file 'FILE' can be determined by combining the relative directory pathname for 'FILE' (c.f. documentRelativeBasePath) with the relative file pathname (c.f. accessFilenameOfAIS) of 'FILE'.
label: Document URL Base Path
documentURLBasePath

comment: sniffAccountLoginInformation is an instance of ActionPredicate that relates an instance of IntelligentAgent to an instance of UserAccount and an instance of Computer. (sniffAccountLoginInformation AGENT ACCOUNT COMPUTER) means that AGENT sniffs the password for ACCOUNT using a PasswordSnifferProgram on COMPUTER.
label: Sniff Account Login Information
sniffAccountLoginInformation

comment: The predicate normativeSpecificationDescribesRelnToIns is used for partially specifying the satisfaction conditions for an instance of NormativeSpecification Specifically, it associates an instance of NormativeSpecification SPEC with a BinaryPredicate RELN and an instance of Thing THING, to state the part of satisfying SPEC involves a situation SIT such that (RELN SIT THING). This predicate works in conjunction with normativeSpecificationDescribesSituationType, which specifies the isa constraints for SIT; indeed (normativeSpecificationDescribesSituationType SPEC TYPE) is equivalent to and shorthand for (normativeSpecificationDescribesRelnToIns SPEC isa TYPE). See completeSpecification for more information on how to characterize the satisfaction conditions for a normative specification. See also normativeSpecificationDescribesRoleForInd, which is a more specific version of normativeSpecificationDescribesRelnToIns, dealing with instances of BinaryRolePredicate and SomethingExisting.
label: Normative Specification Describes Reln To Ins
normativeSpecificationDescribesRelnToIns

comment:
An ArgConstraintPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to put a certain kind of binary-relation-based constraint on a predicate with respect to a given argument-place. The constraint thereby imposed entails that different CycL terms can be substituted one for the other in that place (keeping the predicate's other arguments fixed) while preserving truth only if the terms' respective denotata stand in the specified symmetric binary relation. (Note that this places a necessary, and not a sufficient, condition on such a substitution's preserving truth.)

(intraArgReln PRED N BINPRED) means that whenever PRED holds of two argument-sequences that differ only in their Nth members, then those respective Nth members stand in the symmetric relation BINPRED. Among the most common predicates to play the role of BINPRED in intraArgReln sentences asserted to the Cyc Knowledge Base are quantityIntersects, intersectsWith, and coextensionalSetOrCollectionOrRelations. See also argCardinality and interArgReln.
label: Intra Arg Reln
intraArgReln

comment: (parseVisualizationTable WIDTH P-COUNT V-COUNT TOTAL-COUNT TABLE) means that TABLE is an HTML table source string graphically illustrating that of TOTAL-COUNT items to parse, P-COUNT were parsed, and V-COUNT had validated parses.
label: Parse Visualization Table
parseVisualizationTable

comment: (bondLengthBetweenAtoms ATOM1 ATOM2 DISTANCE) means that a chemical bond [ChemicalBond] exists between the two specified atoms and that the distance between their centers is DISTANCE.
label: bond length between atoms
bondLengthBetweenAtoms

comment: (propertyPredicatesPredicateOfArg PROPERTY PREDICATE ARGNUM) means that if PROPERTY holds of a term TERM, then PREDICATE holds of some set of arguments of which TERM is the ARGNUMth.
label: Property Predicates Predicate Of Arg
propertyPredicatesPredicateOfArg

comment: (annualDeathRateInDueTo PLACE EVENT_TYPE FRACTION) means that FRACTION (a number between 0 and 1) of the residents of PLACE, die due to events of type EVENT_TYPE annually. EVENT_TYPE could be a type of disease, accident, crime, natural disaster, or War.
label: Annual Death Rate In Due To
annualDeathRateInDueTo

comment: (predHoldsBetweenProperSubSits SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2 BIN-PRED) means that if SIT is an instance of SIT-TYPE, SUBSIT1 is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE1, SUBSIT2 is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE2, and (properSubSituations SIT SUBSIT1) and (properSubSituations SIT SUBSIT2), then (BIN-PRED SUBSIT1 SUBSIT2).
label: Pred Holds Between Proper Sub Sits
predHoldsBetweenProperSubSits
Non Existent Specified
nonExistent-Specified
comment: (nonExistent_Specified TERM) states the assumption that TERM has been explicitly stated to not exist. This predicate is primarily used for reasoning in hypothetical contexts about the ramifications of some existing term not actually existing. See also nonExistent and nonExistentSpecification

(forbidden_SitTypeRolePlayerOfType SIT-TYPE ROLE FORBIDDEN-TYPE) means that in no instance of SIT-TYPE should any instance of FORBIDDEN-TYPE play ROLE. That is, there should be no instance INS of SIT-TYPE and FORBIDDEN-INS of FORBIDDEN-TYPE such that (ROLE INS FORBIDDEN-INS). Assertions involving this predicate -- which specify what should not be the case -- should be made in a normative context, e.g., one that reflects the contents of a particular CodeOfConduct.
label: Forbidden Sit Type Role Player Of Type
forbidden-SitTypeRolePlayerOfType

comment: (softwareOnComputerHasFault SOFTWARE COMP FAULT) means that SOFTWARE, as it is installed and configured on COMP, manifests FAULT.
label: Software On Computer Has Fault
softwareOnComputerHasFault

comment: (productionCapacityDuring PT PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the NonNegativeScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the greatest possible amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE that could be produced by the instance of PartiallyTangible PT during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. PT might, for example, be a Country or a Business. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. If AMOUNT is a Rate, AMOUNT indicates what would be the average rate of production of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by PT during the temporal extent of THING if PT were producing PRODUCT-TYPE at the limit of its capacity.
label: Production Capacity During
productionCapacityDuring

comment: An assertion of the form (roleMapping_Collaboration SIT-TYPE TYPE LIST) is used to represent the relationship between actors of TYPE within instances of SIT-TYPE. The relevant set of actors is captured by SET, a set of lists, each element of which is a list of two elements. The first element is a sub-collection of Situation that SIT-TYPE has as at least a candidate scene (see: candidateProperSubSituationTypes) and the second element is a BinaryRolePredicate. Specifically, it asserts that if SET contains as elements (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE1 ROLE1) and (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE2 ROLE2) then, in any instance of SIT-TYPE, for any two actors that are instances of TYPE, where one is playing ROLE1 in the sub-eventof type SUBSIT-TYPE1 and the other is playing ROLE2 in the sub-event of type SUBSIT-TYPE2, those two actors are collaborators for the duration of the instance of SIT-TYPE.
label: Role Mapping Collaboration
roleMapping-Collaboration

comment: (genlPredsWRTTypes TERNPRED1 TERNPRED2 COL1 COL2 COL3) means that if (TERNPRED1 INS1 INS2 INS3) where INS1 is an instance of COL1, INS2 is an instance of COL2, and INS3 is an instance of COL3, then (TERNPRED2 INS1 INS2 INS3). This allows us to specify a pseudo-genlPreds relationship between two TernaryPredicates when their argument constraints are not in the appropriate genls relationship. See also genlPredsWRTTypes, which applies to BinaryPredicates.
label: Genl Preds WRT Types Ternary
genlPredsWRTTypes-Ternary

comment: (itemBenchmarkedAgainst COMPARING SUBJECT BENCHMARK) means that SUBJECT is compared to BENCHMARK, for purposes of gaining information about SUBJECT. See also comparisonSubject and benchmarkRole.
label: Item Benchmarked Against
itemBenchmarkedAgainst

comment: This predicate is used to mark a physical object or piece of stuff as being undesirable in a certain location, from the perspective of a certain Agent_PartiallyTangible. The unwanted matter is a PartiallyTangible, the location a SpatialThing_Localized. Examples: a Cockroach in a HumanOccupationConstruct; Dirt on SomethingToWear; a ToxicSubstance in Food or Drink; a Virus or Bacterium anywhere in the WholeBody of the viewpoint Agent_PartiallyTangible. See also wasteProducts.
label: Unwanted Matter
unwantedMatter

comment: (computerUserHasUsed USER PROGRAM_MODULE N) means that the ComputerUser, USER, has used running instantiations of PROGRAM_MODULE N times, with N a PositiveInteger.
label: Computer User Has Used N Times
computerUserHasUsedNTimes

comment: (rankTypeOfGeoAgent RANK-TYPE COUNTRY BOS-TYPE) means that the class of MilitaryPersonTypeByRanks RANK-TYPE is composed exclusively of ranks used in COUNTRY's branch-of-service-type BOS-TYPE. E.g., (rankTypeOfGeoAgent IranianArmyRank Iran Army_BranchOfService).
label: Rank Type Of Geo Agent
rankTypeOfGeoAgent
Joinleft
join-left
comment: join_left is an ELRelation_OneWay designed to approximate a SQL left join in CycL. It is a VariableArityPredicate whose arguments are CycLSentence_Askables. (join_left ARG1 ARG2 ... ARGN) expands into a disjunction of increasingly long conjunctions of initial segments of its arguments: (or ARG1 (and ARG1 ARG2) ... (and ARG1 ARG2 ... ARGN)). So a join_left sentence is true just in case some non-empty initial segment of its arguments is true
(programRunByOn PROG AGENT COMP) means that AGENT runs PROG on COMP.
label: Program Run By On
programRunByOn

comment: This predicate represents the primitive relation of type level role inequivalence for complex situation types. (differentRolePlayers SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2 ROLE1 ROLE2) means where SIT is a complex situation of type SIT-TYPE, any actor that plays the role ROLE-FROM in any instance of SUBSIT-TYPE-FROM that is a subSituations of SIT is known to be different from any actor that plays the role ROLE-TO in any instance of SUBSIT-TYPE-TO that is a subSituations of SIT.
label: Different Role Players
differentRolePlayers

comment: (typicalBehaviorInSitType AGT SITTYPE ACTTYPE) says that if AGT is in an instance of SITTYPE it is expected_ToBe that AGT will play the doneBy role in some instance of ACTTYPE that is temporally subsumed by the instance of SITTYPE in question. Note that it is possible for there to be many different ACTTYPEs that are typical for an agent in a particular SITTYPE.
label: Typical Behavior In Sit Type
typicalBehaviorInSitType

comment: (hairColor ANIMAL BODYPARTTYPE COLOR) means that the hair that ANIMAL has on its BODYPARTTYPE has the Color COLOR. For example, (hairColor SantaClaus Chin WhiteColor) holds. ANIMAL is normally a Mammal, but certain Invertebrates also have hair.
label: Hair Color (ternary predicate)
hairColor

comment: During the time interval ARG4, the amount of money specified in ARG3 is paid out of an account owned/controlled by ARG1 to cover the expense incurred in an instance of action type ARG2.
label: Expense During Period For Type
expenseDuringPeriodForType

comment: (editFileOfTypeOn AGENT FILE-TYPE COMP) means that AGENT edits a file of type FILE-TYPE found on the computer COMP.
label: Edit File Of Type On
editFileOfTypeOn

comment: (doGetAccessToAccountOnFrom AGENT ACCOUNT COMPUTER1 COMPUTER2) means that, from COMPUTER2, AGENT gets access to ACCOUNT on COMPUTER1, which is a node in ACCOUNT's AccountSystem. See also doGetAccessToAccountOn.
label: Do Get Access To Account On From
doGetAccessToAccountOnFrom

comment: (querySentenceForTermSummaryPredicate SUMMARY-PRED FOCAL-TERM QUERY-SENTENCE) means that QUERY-SENTENCE is a query sentence whose answers, if any, will reveal facts about FOCAL-TERM in the summary category covered by SUMMARY-PRED.
label: Query Sentence For Term Summary Predicate
querySentenceForTermSummaryPredicate

comment: (getUserToRunProgramOnComputer AGENT TARGET PROGRAM) means that AGENT gets a user who is logged in on TARGET to start a process associated with PROGRAM on TARGET.
label: Get User To Run Program On Computer
getUserToRunProgramOnComputer

comment: (argNotGenl REL N COL) means that nothing given as the Nth argument to the Relation REL may be an spec of the Collection COL.
label: Arg Not Genl
argNotGenl

comment: A MetaPredicate used for stating that a given predicate behaves transitively, in a specified argument-place, with respect to the inverse of a given binary predicate. (transitiveViaArgInverse PRED BINPRED N) means that the Nth argument position of PRED is "transitive" with respect to the inverse of BINPRED. That is, if (PRED ... ARGN ...) and (BINPRED ARGN-PRIME ARGN) hold, then so does (PRED ... ARGN-PRIME ...). For example,(transitiveViaArgInverse relationAllExists genls 2) holds; thus from (relationAllExists anatomicalParts Mammal Head_AnimalBodyPart) and (genls Horse Mammal) it follows that (relationAllExists anatomicalParts Horse Head_AnimalBodyPart). See also transitiveViaArg.
label: Transitive Via Arg Inverse
transitiveViaArgInverse

comment: An instance of TernaryPredicate and SlotCalculationFormulaPredicate, used to state a method of calculating the value of a slot (c.f., ScalarIntervalSlot) for a given argument through division. (slotCalculationFormula_Division SLOT DIVIDEND-SLOT DIVISOR-SLOT) means that for ARG, the value of VALUE in (SLOT ARG VALUE) can be arrived at by dividing DIVIDEND-SLOT-VALUE in (DIVIDEND-SLOT ARG DIVIDEND-SLOT-VALUE) bu DIVISOR-SLOT-VALUE in (DIVISOR-SLOT ARG DIVISOR-SLOT-VALUE). For example, (slotCalculationFormula_Division priceToEarningsRatio basicPrice earningsPerShare_ForStockType) means that one can arrive at the PE ratio of a given stock by dividing its basic price by its 12 months earnings per share.
label: Slot Calculation Formula Division
slotCalculationFormula-Division

comment: ARG1 is a group of things, and ARG2 is an Individual, such that there is a many-to-one relationship between ARG1 and ARG2. The relationship is that the members of the group ARG1 are each the first arg in an assertion using the BinaryPredicate ARG3; in each of these assertions, ARG2 is the second argument. See also oneToManyReln, everyToEveryReln.
label: Many To One Reln
manyToOneReln

comment: collectionOverlapFraction(COLL1 COLL2 N) states that the fraction of instances of COLL1 which are also instances of COLL2 is N. Thus, you can state things like 52% of people are female as (collectionOverlapFraction HomoSapiens FemaleHuman 0.52)
label: Collection Overlap Fraction
collectionOverlapFraction

comment: A SetOrCollectionPredicate that is used to state that a particular argIsa (q.v.) constraint applies to all relations of a given type. (argIsaForType RELNTYPE N COL) means that (argIsa RELN N COL) holds for any instance RELN of RELNTYPE. Note that this does _not_ preclude (argIsa RELN N SUBCOL) holding for some specialization SUBCOL of COL; e.g. there might in some cases be an asserted constraint on that argument-place that is stricter than that given by COL. For example, (argIsaForType ActorSlot 1 Event) holds even though some actor-slots' first argument-places are constrained to PhysicalEvents.
label: Arg Isa For Type
argIsaForType

comment: (tourDayEventType TOUR DAY EVENTTYPE) means that according to the itinerary of TOUR, an event of type EVENTTYPE is supposed to take place on the day DAY.
label: Tour Day Event Type
tourDayEventType

comment: (dataForValveEtiologyInProcedure EVT VALVE-TYPE ETIOLOGY-TYPE) means that the patient's VALVE-TYPE associated with EVT the focal valve has the etiology ETIOLOGY-TYPE.
label: etiology
dataForValveEtiologyInProcedure

comment:
(coGenlInverseWRTTypes PRED-1 PRED-2 TYPE-1 TYPE-2) means that if:

1) (PRED-1 INS-1 INS-2),
2) (isa INS-1 TYPE-1),
3) (isa INS-2 TYPE-2)

then it follows that
4) (PRED-2 INS-2 INS-1).

Moreover, 1) follows from the conjunction of 2), 3), and 4).
label: Co Genl Inverse WRT Types
coGenlInverseWRTTypes

comment: (difference_Propositional THING1 THING2 SENT1 SENT2) means that SENT1 describes some important fact about THING1 and SENT2 describes some fact about THING2 and the fact that these sentences hold underscores a salient difference between THING1 and THING2. See also similarity_Propositional and differWRTSet.
label: Difference-Propositional
difference-Propositional

comment:
A ternary GeneralizedQuantifier. (relativelyFewComparedTo SOC1 SOC2 SOC3) means that the percentage of instances of SOC1 that are instances of SOC2 is less than the percentage of instances of SOC3 that are instances of SOC2. For example,

(relativelyFewComparedTo UnitedStatesPerson BuddhistPerson ChinesePerson)

means that the percentage of Americans who are Buddhists is lower than the percentage of Chinese people who are Buddhists. See also relativelyFew and relativelyFewComparedToType.
label: Relatively Few Compared To
relativelyFewComparedTo

comment: (statusInConflictEvent AGENT EVENT STATUS) means that the Agent_PartiallyTangible AGENT has the given ConflictEventStatus STATUS in the ConflictEvent EVENT. An example of this would be (statusInConflictEvent DenverBroncos SuperBowl33-SecondQuarter Winning), which says that the Denver Broncos were winning Super Bowl XXXIII during the quarter mentioned. Statements ascribing an attribute to an agent will in most cases need to be explicitly temporally qualified. The example given is an exception, because the DenverBroncos held Winning status throughout the entire second quarter. If we wanted to assert that the Broncos were winning at some particular time during Super Bowl XXXIII, we would use holdsIn or holdsSometimeDuring to make explicit when the claim is true.
label: Status In Conflict Event
statusInConflictEvent

comment: A predicate that relates a CycL term and an integer (representing an argument-position) to a CycL formula in which the term appears (in that position). (argN TERM N FORMULA) means that TERM occurs in the Nth argument-position within FORMULA. For example, the sentence `(argN Dog 1 (genls Dog Mammal))' holds. Note that argN's first and third argument-places are both "quoted" (see quotedArgument); thus in the context of the above argN sentence the constituent term `Dog' denotes itself (rather than the collection of dogs), and similarly for the constituent genls sentence.
label: Arg N
argN

comment: (tourTravelSubLegTransport TOUR PATH TRAVELINGTYPE) means that a subleg of the leg of tour represented by PATH will involve a TransportationEventByVehicleType of type TRAVELINGTYPE.
label: Tour Travel Sub Leg Transport
tourTravelSubLegTransport

comment: (durationBetweenSubSituationTypes_Existential SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE1 SUBSITTYPE2 DUR) means that for any instantiation INST of SITTYPE there exists an instance, SIT1, of SUBSITTYPE1 that is a properSubSituations of INST, and an instance, SIT2, of SUBSITTYPE2 that is a properSubSituations of INST and such that (startsAfterEndingOf SIT2 SIT1), and such that there is a time interval INT of duration DUR such that(timeIntervalBetween INT SIT1 SIT2).
label: Duration Between Sub Situation Types Existential
durationBetweenSubSituationTypes-Existential

comment: (preChangeValueOfQuantity TEMPORAL-THING THING SLOT VALUE) means that the instance of TemporalThing TEMPORAL-THING changed the value of SLOT applied to THING from VALUE. To specify what the value of SLOT applied to THING is changed to, use postChangeValueOfQuantity. preChangeValueOfQuantity, postChangeValueOfQuantity, and changesQuantityByAmount can be used together to perform arithmetical calculations about the value of SLOT applied to THING with respect to TEMPORAL-THING.
label: Pre Change Value Of Quantity
preChangeValueOfQuantity

comment: (typicalArgIsa PRED NUM COL) says that typically, the NUMth argument-place of PRED is filled by an instance of COL. Note that COL must be a spec of COLGENL, where (argIsa PRED NUM COLGENL).
label: Typical Arg Isa
typicalArgIsa

comment: (unitAssignedNthSuppEffort MISSION UNIT N) means that           UNIT is the Nth supporting effort during MISSION.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: units assigned to a particular supporting effort
label: unit assigned to a particular supporting effort
unitAssignedNthSuppEffort

comment: An assertion of the form (argGenlsInputModeForDetermination PRED N TYPE DET) means that relative to the InductiveLogicProgrammingDetermination DET, the Nth argument of the Predicate PRED should be a sub-collection of the Collection TYPE and that argument position has a mode of an input variable. The sense of mode here is derived from Prolog_ComputerLanguage.
label: Arg Genls Input Mode For Determination
argGenlsInputModeForDetermination
True Query
trueQuery
comment: (trueQuery QUERY) is true iff the QUERY is true.

This predicate compares two things in terms of some QuantitySlot that relates them to different instances of a given specialization of Quantity. (differentInQuantityRelation T1 T2 SLOT) means that there are different #$Quantities QUANT-1 and QUANT-2, such that (SLOT T1 QUANT-1) and (BINPRED T2 QUANT-2).
label: Different In Quantity Relation
differentInQuantityRelation

comment: (packetsOfTypeFromReachTarget PACKET_TYPE FROM_COMP TO_COMP) means that Packet_Networks of the type PACKET_TYPE, sent from FROM_COMP, will (barring some sort of snafu) reach TO_COMP. More precisely, it means that either (a) there is no Firewall_Network mediating remote connections between FROM_COMP and TO_COMP, or (b) there is a Firewall_Network between the two computers, but it does not filter packets of PACKET_TYPE from FROM_COMP to TO_COMP.
label: Packets Of Type From Reach Target
packetsOfTypeFromReachTarget

comment: (grossDomesticProduct GE THING MONEY) means that the instance of MonetaryValue MONEY is a measure of the value of the GeopoliticalEntity GE's total domestic production of goods and services during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. A country would be a typical instance of GE. THING will often be a time period -- for example, a calendar year such as (YearFn 1997) or a calendar quarter such as (QuarterFn 4 (YearFn 1997)); but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. MONEY will sometimes be specified using the function USDollarFn, which returns a UnitOfMoney denominated in US dollars of a particular year; for example, to express the fact that the gross domestic product of the United Arab Emirates for 1997 was $35,930,000,000 in 1990 U.S. dollars, we can say (grossDomesticProduct UnitedArabEmirates (YearFn 1997) ((USDollarFn 1990) 3.593e+10)). See also grossDomesticProduct_Nominal and grossNationalProduct.
label: GDP
grossDomesticProduct

comment: (termPhrases_Lexical TERM CONSTRAINT STRING) means that STRING is a word or phrase explicitly in Cyc's lexicon (i.e. not requiring parsing or generation) that denotes TERM and that meets CONSTRAINT. Cf. termPhrases.
label: Term Phrases Lexical
termPhrases-Lexical

comment: An assertion of the form (requestReservesQuantityOfIndForInterval REQUEST QUANT INDIVIDUAL INTERVAL) states that the #ResourceRequest represents a request to reserve the Quantity QUANT, that is a 'part' of the Individual INDIVIDUAL, during the TimeInterval INTERVAL. This is a core predicate for describing what an Allotment reserves. The amount that ALLOT reserves of INDIVIDUAL can also be represented using the requestReservesPercentageOfIndForInterval (q.v.).
label: Request Reserves Quantity Of Ind For Interval
requestReservesQuantityOfIndForInterval

comment: The predicate corresponding to DrivingDistanceBetweenFn. (drivingDistanceBetween PLACE1 PLACE2 DISTANCE) means that according to the Google Maps website, the driving distance between PLACE1 and PLACE2 is DISTANCE.
label: Driving Distance Between
drivingDistanceBetween

comment: A specialization of trueSentence and necessary that is used to state that a given CycL sentence is logically true (in the intended semantics of CycL) -- i.e. it is equivalent to True. Note that this is not a KBDependentRelation: we do not assume that all logical truths are provable in Cyc. Also, note that logicallyTrueSentence is notAssertible.
label: Logically True Sentence
logicallyTrueSentence

comment: (structureSubstringForNthStructureOfTypeAtOffsetHasInterpretationAndScore STRUCTURE STRING N TYPE OFFSET INTERPRETATION SCORE) means that the Nth occurrence of the structure-type TYPE in the abstract structure (AbstractStructure, q.v.) STRUCTURE contains (via subInfoStructures) the string STRING at offset OFFSET, such that this occurrence of STRING has been assigned a semantic interpretation INTERPRETATION with score SCORE.
label: Structure Substring For Nth Structure Of Type At Offset Has Interpretation And Score
structureSubstringForNthStructureOfTypeAtOffsetHasInterpretationAndScore

comment: (closestOfTypeToObject OBJ1 OBJ2 COL) means that OBJ2 is the instance of COL such that the distanceBetween it and OBJ1 is smaller than for any other instance of COL.
label: Closest Of Type To Object
closestOfTypeToObject

comment: (levelOfExposureToSubstanceTypeViaRoute OBJECT STUFF-TYPE ROUTE-TYPE LEVEL) says that OBJECT is exposed to instances of STUFF-TYPE via the exposure route ROUTE-TYPE to the degree expressed by LEVEL. For example, (levelOfExposureToSubstanceTypeViaRoute #$BobTheAdult CigaretteSmoke Inhaling veryHighAmountOf) says that Bob is exposed to cigarette smoke via inhalation to a high degree. Despite the occurrence of a spec of Event in the arg3, this predicate is an instance of NonDavidsonianPredicate, intended to be used with temporal qualification, to talk about exposure without explicitly having to reify an exposure event.
label: Level Of Exposure To Substance Type Via Route
levelOfExposureToSubstanceTypeViaRoute

comment:
A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keSuggestionPreds_SpecSpec COL1 BINPRED COL2) means that for every known specialization SPEC1 of COL1, it is suggested that there be some specialization SPEC2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED SPEC2 SPEC1) is known in the knowledge base.

For example,

(keSuggestionPredsInverse_SpecSpec SpaceInAFixedHOC eventTypeOccursAtLocationType HumanActivity)

means that for every known specialization SPACE-TYPE of SpaceInAFixedHOC, it is suggested that there be a specialization ACT-TYPE of HumanActivity such that (eventTypeOccursAtLocationType ACT-TYPE SPACE-TYPE) is known in the knowledge base.

comment: An instance of TemporallyQualifiableRelation. (adjustedEPS ORG MONEY TIME) means MONEY is the amount that would be earned (i.e. profit) by ORG per share of stock during the time interval that is subsumed by TIME, if all amortization and exceptional costs to ORG were added back to ORG's profits. This value is called "adjusted EPS" or "headline EPS" (because it is often the EPS reported by companies). The exact nature of the adjustments made varies from company to company. See also adjustedEarningsPerShare_ForStockType.
label: Adjusted EPS For Period
adjustedEPSForPeriod

comment: A CycInferenceHeuristicRelevancePredicate. (irrelevantMt MT) means that all assertions made in the Microtheory MT should be heuristically considered very unlikely to be relevant to inferences done in the Microtheory MT-1 in which (irrelevantMt MT) is asserted (where MT-1 and MT need not be the same). As a consequence, note that when (irrelevantMt MT) is asserted in a Microtheory MT-1, each of the assertions in MT will be an irrelevantAssertion (q.v.) for inferences done in MT-1.

comment:
(pertinentQuerySentenceWithTerms SOURCE-SENTENCE TERM-SET NEW-SENTENCE SUBSTITUTION-COUNT) means that NEW-SENTENCE is a CycLSentence_Askable constructed by taking the CycLSentence_Askable SOURCE-SENTENCE and replacing terms or free variables in it with SUBSTITUTION-COUNT many terms from TERM-SET.

pertinentQuerySentenceWithTerms is supported by a removal module that can be called by the Cyc inference engine. The removal module requires the first two argument positions to be bound, the third to be unbound, and the fourth can be either bound or unbound.

Here is an example of how the removal module works. Given this query sentence: 

(pertinentQuerySentenceWithTerms 
   (Quote (objectFoundInLocation #$OsamaBinLaden ?X)) 
   (TheSet #$MohamedAtta Iran) 
   ?SENT 
   ?SUBST-COUNT)

The following will be returned as bindings for <?SENT, ?SUBST-COUNT>: 

<(Quote (objectFoundInLocation #$MohamedAtta ?X)), 1>
<(Quote (objectFoundInLocation #$OsamaBinLaden Iran)), 1>
<(Quote (objectFoundInLocation #$MohamedAtta Iran)), 2>
label: Pertinent Query Sentence With Terms
pertinentQuerySentenceWithTerms

comment: (exportQuotaDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the export quota of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE for the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (Of course, the existence of export quotas is the exception rather than the rule.) THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of oil exports, for example, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil REGION is allowed to export. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of export, under the quota, of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION during the temporal extent of THING. Oil exports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day.

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relation with respect to a given thing and a given collection. (relationInstanceExistsMax BINPRED THING COL N) means that there exists at most N instances (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) of COL that THING bears the relation PRED to, such that (PRED INST(i) THING) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(thereExistAtMost N ?INST (and (isa ?INST COL) (BINPRED THING ?INST)))) .

For example, `(relationInstanceExistsMax physicalParts MyLeftHand Thumb 1)' means that my left hand has at most one thumb. Cf. relationExistsMaxInstance, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Instance Exists Max

comment: (jointlyCatastrophicSituations AGENT SIT1 SIT2) means that the outcomes(s) of SIT1 and SIT2 are catastrophically worse to AGENT than the respective outcomes of SIT1 and SIT2 individually. In other words, for AGENT the occurrence of both SIT1 and SIT2 is far worse than the occurrence of either one individually.
label: Jointly Catastrophic Situations
jointlyCatastrophicSituations

comment: A predicate used to map representational systems into CycL. It is used in lieu of synonymousExternalConcept when the system uses strings rather than terms to denote some concept, a common practice in rdf-based representations that treat relations as having 'domains' (whose objects are typically represented using terms of the representation language) and 'ranges' (frequently represented using strings, uninterpreted symbols, numerals, and floats). For example, a system SYS might represent that a particular object OBJ is blue with a triple, 'REF color "blue"' where 'REF' represents OBJ, 'color' represents the color relation, and the string "blue" represents the color blue. In order to map this example into Cyc, we would add a synonymousExternalConcept assertion associating the SYS terms REF, an interpretationForPredWithStringInArg assertion associating color with its CycL correlate, and an assertion of the form (interpretationForSystemString BlueColor SYS "blue"). Note that this presupposes that "blue" is unambiguous in SYS, which need not be the case. If a string is ambiguous, additional context is needed -- see #$interpretationForSystemStringInContext.
label: Interpretation For System String
interpretationForSystemString
subPropertyOf: Concept In System Default Display String

comment: (constraintOnReplacementBasis TEMPLATE LIST1 LIST2 POS SET-OR-COLLECTION) means that, for TEMPLATE, if each nth FormulaArgPosition in LIST1 is a member of the nth SetOrCollection in LIST2, then the term in POS must be a member of SET-OR-COLLECTION. For example, (constraintOnReplacementBasis FormulaTemplate001 (TheList (FormulaArgPositionFn 1 1) (FormulaArgPosition 1 2)) (TheList Person (TheSetOf X (genls X ContainerArtifact)) (FormulaArgPositionFn 1 3) (TheSet Cycorp))) means that, for FormulaTemplate001, if the term in arg position (1 2) of the formula is an instance of Person, and if the term in arg position (1 2) of the formula is a specialization of ContainerArtifact, then the term in arg position (1 3) of the formula must be Cycorp.
label: Constraint On Replacement Basis
constraintOnReplacementBasis

comment:
(nounStringOccursAsSubjectForVerbStringsInCorpus STRING USAGES SOURCE) means that USAGES represents all observed usages of the noun with nonplural string STRING as a subject in the instance of InformationStore SOURCE. USAGES must take the form of an extensional list (see List_Extensional) of infinitive verb-strings. A given verb can appear more than once in a list to reflect multiple occurrences with the noun.

For example, (nounStringOccursAsSubjectForVerbStringsInCorpus "apple" (TheList "fall" "fall" "look" "taste") NewYorkTimes2001TextCorpus) means that in the New York Times 2001 corpus, the noun 'apple' occurred twice as the subject of the verb 'to fall,' once as the subject of the verb 'to look,' and once as the subject of the verb 'to taste.'

See also nounStringOccursAsObjectForVerbStringsInCorpus.
label: Noun String Occurs As Subject For Verb Strings In Corpus
nounStringOccursAsSubjectForVerbStringsInCorpus

comment: ARG1 is a group of things, and ARG2 is a group of things, such that there is a one-to-one relationship between ARG1 and ARG2. The relationship is that each of the things in the group ARG1 is the first arg to the BinaryPredicate ARG3 where exactly one of the members of the group ARG2 is the second argument. The groups ARG1 and ARG2 must have the same number of members. See also oneToManyReln and everyToEveryReln.
label: One To One Reln

More precisely, it means that if ORG is an instance of ORGTYPE, and (susceptibleToDiseaseCausedBy ORGTYPE PATHOTYPE), and ORG is the nonDeliberateActors in an instance of ACTIONTYPE, the likelihood that there will exist an infection caused by this action, in which the infectingOrganismMob is a mob of instances of PATHOTYPE and of which ORG is the infectionHost, is highAmountOf.

comment: A UnaryPredicate used for stating a certain restriction regarding the use of a given Collection in assertions to the Cyc Knowledge Base. (notAssertibleCollection COL) means that no ground atomic formula (or "GAF"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence) whose initial (or "0th" argument-place) term is `isa', and whose 2nd argument-place term denotes COL, can be asserted to the KB. See also notAssertible, which constrains predicates in a similar fashion.

For instance, suppose we wanted to translate the sentence "Joe has 3 friends, at least, who get along with each other." (thereExistAtLeast_RelHolds 3 ?PALS likesAsFriend (likesAsFriend Joe ?PALS))
label: There Exist At Least Rel Holds
thereExistAtLeast-RelHolds

comment: A predicate used for probability statements. (conditionalProbabilitySet PROPOSITION SETOFPROPOSITIONS PROBNO) means that the probability of PROPOSITION being true, given that all the propositions in SETOFPROPOSITIONS are known to be true, in the applicable Microtheory, is PROBNO (a real number between zero and one, where zero means certainly false and one means certainly true). In most microtheories, generally, this conditionalProbabilitySet refers to the conditional probability that PROPOSITION is true given only that the propositions in SETOFPROPOSITIONS, and the domainAssumptions accessible in the applicable Microtheory, are true, without regard to any further evidence or the truth of any other assertions. See also conditionalProbability, priorProbability, derivedProbability, conditionallyIndependent, and the function version of this predicate: ConditionalProbabilitySetFn. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.
label: Conditional Probability Set
conditionalProbabilitySet

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relation with respect to a given collection and a given thing. (relationExistsMinInstance BINPRED COL THING N) means that there exists at least N instances (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) of COL that bear the relation PRED to THING such that (PRED INST(i) THING) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(thereExistAtLeast N ?INST (and (isa ?INST COL) (BINPRED ?INST THING))) .

For example, `(relationExistsMinInstance physicalParts Hand MyLeftThumb 1)' means that my left thumb is part of at least one hand. Cf. relationInstanceExistsMin, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa1_5 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the first argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the fifth argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ARG5 ... ) is semantically well-formed only if ARG5 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.

comment: (vulnerableToType_Truth THREAT-OBJ-TYPE OBJECT HARM-TYPE TRUTH-VALUE) is used to state which of the two vulnerability predicates, vulnerableToType or invulnerableToType holds for (THREAT-OBJ-TYPE OBJECT HARM-TYPE). Specifically, TRUTH-VALUE is True iff (vulnerableToType THREAT-OBJ-TYPE OBJECT HARM-TYPE) and conversely TRUTH-VALUE is False iff (invulnerableToType THREAT-OBJ-TYPE OBJECT HARM-TYPE).

vulnerableToType-Truth

comment:
A ternary MetaLanguagePredicate that is used to state the precise position of a given CycLTerm within a given CycLFormula in which it occurs. The term might be an immediate constituent of the formula, or it might be nested (to any depth) inside some other constituent(s).

(termHasPositionInFormula TERM INTEGER-LIST FORMULA) means that TERM occurs in the location within FORMULA that is described by INTEGER-LIST, according to the following convention. The first integer in INTEGER-LIST is the number of an argument-place in FORMULA that is occupied by either (a) TERM itself or (b) by some sub-formula SUBFORMULA that contains TERM. In case (a), TERM's exact location has been identified, and INTEGER-LIST will contain no further integers. In case (b), the second integer in INTEGER-LIST is the number of the argument-place in SUBFORMULA that is occupied by either (a) TERM itself or (b) by some sub-formula SUBSUBFORMULA that contains TERM. And so on.

For example, the sentence '(termHasPositionInFormula Dog (TheList 1) (genls Dog Mammal))' holds, as does '(termHasPositionInFormula Dog (TheList 2 1) (isa Muffet (AdultFn Dog))'.

Note that termHasPositionInFormula's first and third argument-places are both "quoted" (see quotedArgument). See also argN.
label: Term Has Position In Formula
termHasPositionInFormula

comment: (combatForceRatioInEvent EVENT AGENT1 AGENT2 N) means that force ratio of AGENT1's units to AGENT2's units is N.
