useRFRuleForMovieTopics
comment: (useRFRuleForMovieTopics RULE) tells a reformulation specification that it should use RULE to reformulate formulae during term replacement, so as to produce WFF results without bothering the user.

a predicate which characterize the capacity in which some agent does a kind of action. (actsInCapacity_RequiredFunction AGENT SLOT EVENT-TYPE) indicates that an agent does a certain type of action as a required function (rather than, say, as an optional function).
label: required function
actsInCapacity-RequiredFunction
Term Chosen
termChosen
comment: (termChosen TERM) is true for any closed Cyc TERM, and indicates that TERM has been chosen from the set of terms in the universe of discourse. This predicate is primarily used on a variable so that the moment of choice of a particular term as the binding for that variable can be identified. There should never be methods for generating bindings for non-closed termChosen literals.

(regularFrequencyOfActionType EVENTTYPE ACTORTYPE ROLE FREQ) means that instances ACTOR of ACTORTYPE typically play role ROLE in events of type EVENTTYPE with frequency FREQ. For instance, (regularFrequencyOfActionType ShavingBody #$AdultMalePerson performedBy Daily) means that men who shave regularly, typically shave daily. Thus this predicate is useful for ACTORTYPEs of which it cannot be said that typical instances regularly play role ROLE in events of type EVENTTYPE. For cases where that *can* be said, use the more specific predicate frequencyOfActionType.
label: Regular Frequency Of Action Type
regularFrequencyOfActionType

comment: A predicate used to indirectly map concepts from external data sources into Cyc, even though the target concept has not been reified. (synonymousExternalPredWRTTypes RELN SOURCE STRING TYPE1 TYPE2) means that the string STRING, as it occurs in the data source SOURCE, denotes a binary predicate PRED such that (coGenlInverseWRTTypes RELN PRED TYPE1 TYPE2).
label: Synonymous External Pred WRT Types Inverse
synonymousExternalPredWRTTypes-Inverse

comment: (binRelationExistsAllSpecsType PRED COL1 COL2 COL-TYPE) means that for every subcollection of COL2 that are also instances of COL-TYPE, TYPE2, there exists an instance of COL1, INS1, such that (PRED INS1 TYPE2) holds.
label: Bin Relation Exists All Specs Type
binRelationExistsAllSpecsType

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates a MultiDirectionalCommunication (q.v.) and an agent to information received by the latter in the course of the former. (infoGathered COMM AGENT INFO) means that there is a subevent of COMM that is an InformationTransferEvent in which AGENT is a recipientOfInfo and INFO is an infoTransferred.

When it comes to multi-directional communication, infoGathered is the "flip-side" of infoContributed (q.v.). In successful two-way communication (see BiDirectionalCommunication), any information contributed by one party will in turn be gathered by the other party, and vice versa. In communications among larger groups, however, in which a given party might gather some but not all of the information contributed by the other parties, things can get much more complicated and the foregoing symmetry might not be present.
label: Info Gathered
infoGathered

comment: (credibilityToAgent INFOTR AGT AMOUNT) means that the InformationTransferEvent INFOTR has a credibility, or believability, to the Agent_Generic AGT, of amount AMOUNT. So, for instance, (credibilityToAgent ReadingUSAToday001 Sue (VeryLowToLowAmountFn Credibility)) means that Sue finds what she is reading in USAToday_TheNewspaper in that particular instance fairly unconvincing, and (credibilityToAgent Threatening101 Bill (HighAmountFn Credibility)) means that Bill finds that particular MakingAThreat quite credible. Note: to say that some agent is credible, write rules stating that any Communicating in which that agent is the senderOfInfo has a high credibility for whomever receives it. Similarly, to say that some InformationBearingThing is credible, say that any InformationTransferEvents in which it is the informationOrigin has a high credibility for the recipientOfInfo.
label: credibility
credibilityToAgent

comment:
(hasNumberOfValuesOfTypeViaPred INS BIN-PRED TYPE POS-INTEGER) holds just in case INS is related to POS-INTEGER number of instances of TYPE via performing events that stand in BIN-PRED to those instances of TYPE. For example, If Martha Stewart has baked NUM cakes, then 
(hasNumberOfValuesOfTypeViaPred MarthaStewart outputsCreated Cake NUM)

holds.
label: Has Number Of Values Of Type Via Pred
hasNumberOfValuesOfTypeViaPred

comment: The corresponding predicate for CycInferenceAnswerFn. (inferenceAnswerBindingsAndJustifications ANSWER BINDING-SET JUSTIFICATION-SET) means that the CycInferenceAnswer ANSWER is composed of (i) an encoding of BINDING-SET, and (ii) the set of CycInferenceAnswerJustifications JUSTIFICATION-SET.
label: Inference Answer Bindings And Justifications
inferenceAnswerBindingsAndJustifications

comment: (marketDemandIsPerfectlyPriceInelasticWRTChange MARKET PRODUCT OLD-PRICE NEW-PRICE) means that given a change in MARKET's price of PRODUCT from OLD-PRICE to NEW-PRICE, there will be no change in demand; precisely speaking, theabsolute value of the elasticity of demand in response to this change is 0.
label: Market Demand Is Perfectly Price Inelastic WRT Change
marketDemandIsPerfectlyPriceInelasticWRTChange
subPropertyOf: Market Demand Is Price Inelastic WRT Change

comment: matchBetween is used to identify an AnalogyMatch between two AnalogyCases, one being the base case and one being the target case. Its format is (matchBetween BASE TARGET MATCH).
label: Match Between
matchBetween

comment: If the CycLReformulator is operating in MT in the mode MODE, and it encounters a reformulation rule with no reformulationDirectionInMode meta-assertion for MODE stated in MT or a genlMt thereof, the extent of this predicate will be used to determine the reformulation direction of the rule.
label: Default Reformulation Direction In Mode For Pred
defaultReformulationDirectionInModeForPred

comment: Objects bound to the variable ARG2 which occurs in the CycL expression ARG1 will be instances of the collection ARG3.
label: Query Var Type
queryVarType

comment: This is a specialized representation (semiotic) predicate meaning representation due to some arbitrary symbolic convention, such as when the English word 'Parthenon' represents the actual Parthenon, when a roaring lion represents MGM Studios, or when the abstract tetrahedron represent 'Fire' in alchemy. (signifiesTo_Symbol THING1 THING2 AGENT) means that, to AGENT, THING1 represents THING2 because of some arbitrary convention or association of the two (that is known to AGENT). THING1 need not resemble THING2 in any way, nor need it be causally related to THING2. THING1 acts as an 'arbitrary sign' of THING2. This is called 'symbolic' representation. Compare this with the predicates signifiesTo_Icon and signifiesTo_Index. It's possible for all three to apply to the same representation. The spoken word 'Bow-Wow' is not only a conventional 'symbol' of barking but also an 'icon' because it resembles what it represents. If the basis for the representation is unknown, use the more general predicate signifiesTo.
label: symbol
signifiesTo-Symbol

comment: The functional predicate corresponding to GroupsOfMaxSizeFn. (groupsOfMaxSize relates a NonNegativeInteger N and a collection of TemporalThings TYPE to the collection of all Groups composed of at most N instances of TYPE.
label: Groups Of Max Size
groupsOfMaxSize

comment: A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa based relationship holds between the fifth argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg5ResultIsa FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the fifth argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg5ResultIsa _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultIsa.
label: Inter Arg 5 Result Isa
interArg5ResultIsa

comment: (sensorTypeMaxEffectiveRange_IdealCondition SENSOR-TYPE RANGE OBJECT-TYPE) means that the specialization of Sensor SENSOR-TYPE has an effective range for detecting instances of OBJECT-TYPE of RANGE under ideal conditions.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: maximum sensor ranges under ideal conditions
label: maximum sensor range under ideal conditions
sensorTypeMaxEffectiveRange-IdealCondition

comment: (dateOfTypeInRange DATE DATE-TYPE EARLY LATE) holds just in case DATE is an instance of DATE-TYPE and falls between EARLY and LATE according to the convention established for DATE-TYPE (an instance of NormalTimeParameter.
label: Date Of Type In Range
dateOfTypeInRange
subPropertyOf: Interval Of Type Lies Between Exclusive

comment: (typesCapabilityEnablesCapability SE-TYPE SIT-TYPE1 ROLE1 SIT-TYPE2 ROLE2) means that instances of SE-TYPE have the ability to play the role ROLE1 in situations of type SIT-TYPE1 and that this ability enables SE to play the role ROLE2 in situations of type SIT-TYPE2.
label: Types Capability Enables Capability
typesCapabilityEnablesCapability

comment:
A ternary RotationalOrientationPredicate that relates a HexalateralObject to a CartesianCoordinateSystem to an AngularDistance. (lateralOrientationInCoordinateSystem OBJ SYSTEM DIST) means that DIST is the angular distance that OBJ has "strayed" (so to speak) from its standard or original rotational orientation about its lateral (side-to-side) axis in SYSTEM. (See #$NoteOnStandardRotationalOrientation.

In flight dynamics, the lateral orientation of an aircraft is known as its "pitch".

See also normalOrientationInCoordinateSystem and longitudinalOrientationInCoordinateSystem.
label: Lateral Orientation In Coordinate System
lateralOrientationInCoordinateSystem

comment: (keStrongSuggestion_New TERM CONSTRAINT FORMULA) states a strong suggestion that FORMULA should be known to be true about TERM, where FORMULA is an open formula containing one keyword, constraints on which are given in CONSTRAINT. For example, (implies (isa ?X UnitedStatesPresident) (keStrongSuggestion_New ?X (isa #$TheUnknownTerm Person) (knowsAbout #$TheUnknownTerm ?X))) states a strong suggestion that for US Presidents, Cyc learn which things stand in the knowsAbout relation to them, where those things are constrainted to be instances of Person.
label: Ke Strong Suggestion New
keStrongSuggestion-New

comment: (wantsToRelnInstance AGT THING RELN) means that the Agent_PartiallyTangible ?AGT wants to be in the relation RELN to THING.
label: Wants To Reln Instance
wantsToRelnInstance

comment: (typesHaveRelationInSubSituationType SCRIPT SCENE TYPE1 TYPE2 BINREL) means that in an instantiation of SCRIPT, SCRIPT-INST, it will hold in the sub-event that is the instantiation of SCENE (see holdsIn) that an instance of TYPE1 and an instance of TYPE2 will have the relation BINREL to each other.
label: Types Have Relation In Sub Situation Type
typesHaveRelationInSubSituationType

comment: (num_GenQuantRelnToType RELN SETORCOL1 SETORCOL2 NUM) means that for NUM elements X of SETORCOL1 there is an INST, where (elementOf INST SETORCOL2), such that (RELN X INST) holds.
label: Num Gen Quant Reln To Type
num-GenQuantRelnToType

comment: A predicate used to state the price that shares of a particular company's stock (of a given "class"; e.g. common or preferred) are currently being traded at. Actually, this price is based on the most recent price-quote for that stock, and quotes are delayed by a set time (e.g. 20-minutes on the London Exchange) from the time of the actual trade. More precisely, then, (stockPrice_Last STOCK PRICE DATE EXCHANGE) means that, as of DATE, the most recent price quoted on EXCHANGE for STOCK is PRICE. Also see stockPrice_Ask and stockPrice_Bid.
label: last price
stockPrice-Last

comment: (typicallyRelnTo PRED SET-OR-COL-1 SET-OR-COL-2) means that typically (i.e., most and some) elements EL-1 of SET-OR-COL-1 are such that (PRED EL-1 SET-OR-COL-2).
label: Typically Reln To
typicallyRelnTo

comment: A QueryDedicatedPredicate used for querying for differences between two terms.
label: Query Difference On Terms
queryDifferenceOnTerms

comment:
(multiWordStringSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred_Inverse WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION BINARY-PREDICATE LIST) means that the fact that 
   (multiWordStringSenseExtension WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION LIST)
is explained in part by the fact that 
   (BINARY-PREDICATE ARG1 ARG2)
for some ARG1 and ARG2 such that 
   (multiWordString LIST WORD SPEECH-PART-1 ARG2)
for some N.

The reason why this sense extension is only partly explained by the above considerations reflects the fact that due to Cyc's incomplete knowledge, there will be many cases where BINARY-PREDICATE is not an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and so cannot reliably broker sense extensions from SPEECH-PART-1 to SPEECH-PART-2 for any word denoting one of its arg1s. Rather, there is a possibly unreified specialization SPEC-PRED of BINARY-PRED (see genlPreds) that is an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and the fact that (SPEC-PRED ARG1 ARG2) fully explains the sense extension in question.
label: Multi Word String Sense Extension Brokered By Pred Inverse
multiWordStringSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred-Inverse
Combine Dags
combineDags
comment: (combineDags ?Combined ?Schema ?Dag1 ... ?Dagn) creates a new dag by substituting into ?Schema the parts ?Dag1 .. ?Dagn at positions indicated in ?Schema by the integers 1 .. n. The new Dag is bound to the variable ?Combined.

An assertion of the form (indMightPlayRoleInSitType_Linkage OBJ ROLE SIT-TYPE) is used to assert that there exists evidence that the SomethingExisting OBJ may be filling ROLE, an instance of BinaryRolePredicate, in an instance of SIT-TYPE, some sub-collection of Situation
label: Ind Might Play Role In Sit Type Evidential
indMightPlayRoleInSitType-Evidential

comment: (phraseTypesMeetNCRuleSyntacticConstraints MODIFIER-TYPE HEAD-TYPE RULE) means that MODIFIER-TYPE and HEAD-TYPE are consistent with the syntactic constraints on the modifier and head (respectively) or RULE.
label: Phrase Types Meet NC Rule Syntactic Constraints
phraseTypesMeetNCRuleSyntacticConstraints

comment: (schemaIntegrationObjectTypeFromODS INTEGRATION COLL SOURCE-ODS) means that the instance of IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources, INTEGRATION, must produce a table that defines an object that is an instance of COLL and that the need to do so is motivated by the source knowledge source having an non-ReifiedMapping schema that defines this sort of object.
label: Schema Integration Object Type From ODS
schemaIntegrationObjectTypeFromODS

comment: This predicate relates things to their equivalence class with respect to some collection and some equivalence relation. (equivalenceClassWRT COL REL THING SUBCOL) means that SUBCOL is the collection or set of elements of COL that bear the relation REL to THING. For instance, (equivalenceClassWRT CanadianPerson cotemporal JeanChretien CANADIANSCOTEMPORALWITHJC) means that JeanChretien is cotemporal with all the Canadians that are elements of the set CANADIANSCOTEMPORALCWITHJC.
label: Equivalence Class WRT
equivalenceClassWRT

comment: (interArgGenl1_2 REL INDEPENDENT-COL DEPENDENT-COL) means that, when a spec of INDEPENDENT-COL appears as the first argument to REL, the second argument is constrained to be a spec of DEPENDENT-COL.
label: Inter Arg Genl 1 2
interArgGenl1-2

comment: After an agent performs an event of type arg1, the agent performs an event of type arg3 which is a penalty assessed by the judicial agent in arg1 of type arg2.
label: Judicial Action Type
judicialActionType

comment: (productionAmountDuring PRODUCER PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the NonNegativeScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE produced by the instance of SomethingExisting PRODUCER during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. PRODUCER might, for example, be a Country, a Business, or a GeographicalRegion. THING will often be a calendar time interval; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. If AMOUNT is a Rate, AMOUNT indicates the average rate of production of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by PRODUCER during the temporal extent of THING. See also productionAmount, which can be used when the time period is unknown.
label: Production Amount During
productionAmountDuring

comment: (relativeOrientation_Underspecified OBJ1 OBJ2 ORIENT) states that relative to OBJ2, OBJ1 occupies the OrientedLocation_Underspecified denoted by ORIENT. This predicate allows us to express relativistic notions of orientation, such as 'sick is better than dead', 'ecstatic' is better than 'happy', etc. More usefully, it allows us to define the lexical semantics of actions like 'to raise X' (the subabstraction of X after the raise occupies an upwardly oriented state relative to the subabstraction of X just before the raise). Many verbs, such as 'improve', 'increase' and 'enhance' have this core meaning.
label: Relative Orientation Underspecified
relativeOrientation-Underspecified

comment: This is the corresponding predicate of the function StreetNamedFn. An assertion of the form (streetWithNameInRegion STREET NAME CITY) means that the Street_Generic STREET is the one picked out by the SubLString NAME within the City CITY.
label: Street With Name In Region
streetWithNameInRegion

comment: (decreasesVulnerabilityTo SITUATION OBJECT RESULT-TYPE) means that being in situation SITUATION decreases OBJECT's vulnerability to RESULT-TYPE. This predicate is similar to makesVulnerableToDegree except that, unlike makesVulnerableToDegree, it expresses a relative decrease in OBJECT's vulnerability rather than an absolute degree of vulnerability. It also resembles vulnerableIn, but there is an important difference that must be observed, namely that when using decreasesVulnerabilityTo one assumes that certain conditions coming into effect descrease vulnerability. Therefore, it should not be used to declare vulnerabilities outright; Cyc should have to conlcude that a situation decreases an object's vulnerability to some result.
label: Decreases Vulnerability To
decreasesVulnerabilityTo
Generates As First Order
generatesAsFirstOrder
comment: (generatesAsFirstOrder COLLECTION-TYPE) means that the second-order collection COLLECTION-TYPE should be paraphrased as if it were a first-order collection. That is, it can be assumed that it will be clear that paraphrases of (isa COL COLLECTION-TYPE) are about COL, and not about instances of COL.
(sectionTypeHasTitle WORK-TYPE SECTION-TYPE STRING) means that every instance of WORK-TYPE, a type of ConceptualWork, has exactly one subWorks of type SECTION-TYPE with title STRING.
label: Section Type Has Title
sectionTypeHasTitle

comment: (nearestDifferentGenls COL-1 COL-2 NEAR-DIFF) relates collections COL-1 and COL-2 to the nearest unsubsumed collections NEAR-DIFF of which COL-1 is a subset but COL-2 is not. This predicate is notAssertible, since it must always be recomputed from the current state of the genls heirarchy. For comparison, see nearestDifferentIsa.
label: Nearest Different Genls
nearestDifferentGenls
Omit From Follow Ups
omitFromFollowUps
comment: (omitFromFollowUps CONC) means that CONC is a concept that should not be offered as a follow-up for a query in the context of our query augmentation application. A good example of an ARG1 for such an assertion would be Device_UserPowered. Although this constant is a legitimate node in Cyc's ontology -- it allows for generalizations that are extremely useful from the point of view of Knowledge Representation -- it is at the same time too general a concept to be of much use in a web search. Note that this does not affect the disambiguation phase of query augmentation. Nor does it affect subtopic followups. Rather it only affects presentation of related follow up concepts (see qaConceptPrintString for more details on what related follow up concepts are, and how to generate them.)
(lineHasSlopeAtPoint_Quantitative LINE POINT SLOPE) means that the line LINE has a slope of numeric value SLOPE at the point POINT.
label: Line Has Slope At Point Quantitative
lineHasSlopeAtPoint-Quantitative

comment: An instance of FirstOrderCollectionPredicate. This predicate is used to describe the ways that types of existing things can function and are intended by their designers to function. (typeIntendedBehaviorCapable OBJTYPE SITTYPE ROLE) means that instances of OBJTYPE are intended by OBJTYPE's designer to play role ROLE in situations or events of type SITTYPE, and that instances of OBJTYPE can play role ROLE in situations or events of type SITTYPE. For example, instances of Clothing_Generic are intended to be capable of being removed and being put on. We can represent this by (typeIntendedBehaviorCapable Clothing_Generic Undressing objectRemoved), and (typeIntendedBehaviorCapable Clothing_Generic PuttingOnAClothingItem objectActedOn) See also (TypeCapableFn behaviorCapable) and typePrimaryFunction.
label: Type Intended Behavior Capable
typeIntendedBehaviorCapable

comment:
A ternary TemporalPredicate that is used to state how long one TemporalThing starts after another starts. (startsDurationAfterStartingOf AFTER TIME BEFORE) means that AFTER starts duration TIME after BEFORE starts. That is, the startingPoint (q.v.) of AFTER is after the starting point of BEFORE, by an interval of Time_Quantity TIME.

See also startsAfterStartingOf and startsDurationAfterEndingOf.
label: Starts Duration After Starting Of
startsDurationAfterStartingOf
Collection Differs From Genls WRT Bin Rel
collectionDiffersFromGenlsWRTBinRel

comment: qaIrrelevantTerm is a unary predicate. (qaIrrelevantTerm TERM) means that TERM should be more or less ignored from the Query Augmentation application. More precisely, printed representations of TERM (for example via preferredGenUnit) should not show up in the Query Augmentation (QA) Interface. On the other hand, (qaIrrelevantTerm TERM) should not entail that QA relevant deductions will be ignored. For example, WebSearchRuleMacroPredicate is not something which QA users will want to search on, thus (qaIrrelevantTerm WebSearchRuleMacroPredicate) should be asserted. Such an assertion does not preclude this term from being mentioned in rules which conclude qaFollowupConcepts.
label: Qa Irrelevant Term
qaIrrelevantTerm

comment: (erects AGENT STRUCTURE MATERIAL-TYPE LOCATION) means that  AGENT erects STRUCTURE using material of the type MATERIAL-TYPE in or  at LOCATION.
label: erection
erects
Use Reformulation Rule For Negation Processing
useReformulationRuleForNegationProcessing
comment: (useReformulationRuleForNegationProcessing RULE) indicates that RULE will be used by the NegationProcessingRLModule.

An assertion of the form (sitServesHigherSpecificationForAgents SIT SPEC AGENT) is used to represent the fact that a particular Situation SIT indirectly increases the likelihood that the Agent_Generic AGENT's NormativeSpecification SPEC will be satisfied. A NormativeSpecification describes a type of situation. This predicate is most useful for associating a situation that bears the relation sitServesSpecificationForAgents to another instance of NormativeSpecification for AGENT, SPEC2, such that the assertion (derivativeSpecificationOf SPEC2 SPEC) holds. So, let us say that Billy plans to rob a bank in order to buy a car. The actual event of him robbing a bank would bear the relation sitServesHigherSpecificationForAgents to the NormativeSpecification of buying a car for Billy because the robbery bears the relation sitSatisfiesSpecificationForAgents to the NormativeSpecification of robbing a bank. This predicate implies that AGENT is aware of SIT.
label: Sit Serves Higher Specification For Agents
sitServesHigherSpecificationForAgents

comment: (availableToAgentTypeForEvent AGENT-TYPE OBJECT EVENT) means that OBJECT is typically available for agents of type AGENT-TYPE to use in EVENT. For example, (availableToAgentTypeForEvent HumanCyclist Cyc #$CycProject) means that Cyc is available to human cyclists for use in the Cyc project. If an instance of AGENT-TYPE is capable of using OBJECT in EVENT, nothing prevents that agent from choosing to use OBJECT in EVENT. Compare this predicate to availableForEvent and availableToAgentTypeForEventType.
label: Available To Agent Type For Event
availableToAgentTypeForEvent
Program Algorithm Internals
programAlgorithmInternals
comment: (programAlgorithmInternals ALGORITHM . INTERNALS) relates ALGORITHM to the list INTERNALS of the relevant instances of SoftwareParameter that are internal parameters to the algorithmic process.

An instance of #$CompletenessGroundsPredicate that is used to state, about a collection or predicate whose extent is inferentially complete (see #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate), that the completeness derives mainly from a conventional stipulation, rather than from the nature of the items in the extent themselves, and that the convention is not something stipulated by the designers of the Cyc system, but exists in the world outside of Cyc. For example, (completelyAssertedCollection DayOfWeekType) holds, and so does (completeByExternalConvention DayOfWeekType). Cf. completeByCycConvention.
label: Complete By External Convention
completeByExternalConvention

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates a pair of tangible objects, space regions, or spatially-localized events to their mereological difference. (spatialDifference DIFFERENCE THING1 THING2) means that DIFFERENCE is the unique SpatialThing (of the same basic type as THING1 and THING2) such that a spatial thing intersects (see spatiallyIntersects) DIFFERENCE if and only if it intersects with THING1 and is disjoint with (see spatiallyDisjoint) THING2.

Note that "of the same basic type" in the above means that the three relata are either all PartiallyTangibles, all SpaceRegions, or all Event_Localizeds. This restriction is needed in order to ensure the uniqueness of DIFFERENCE, since a tangible object, a space region, and an event can have the same spatial extent (see cospatial), despite their being distinct things.

See the corresponding function SpatialDifferenceFn. Also see spatialSum and spatialProduct.
label: spatial difference
spatialDifference

comment: A ternary predicate that relates a given event to the number of injuries it caused within a specified population. (injuryCount EVENT ORGTYPE N) means that N instances of ORGTYPE (some specialization of Organism_Whole) were injured as an immediate and direct result of EVENT. See also deathToll, casualtyCount.
label: Injury Count
injuryCount
Source Fixed Semantic Value For Relation Arg
sourceFixedSemanticValueForRelationArg

comment: (genFormat_ArgFixed RELN ARG-NUM ARG-VALUE STRING LIST) means that when generating an English phrase from a formula whose operator is RELN and whose ARG-NUMth argument is ARG-VALUE, use STRING and LIST instead of what would be used based on the regular genFormat assertion.
label: Gen Format Arg Fixed
genFormat-ArgFixed

comment: (openingTagForStructure STRUC SOURCE TAG) means that STRUC, an instance of either GraphicalStructure or TextString generated from SOURCE, an HTMLSource, has, in SOURCE, an opening tag of TAG, a tag that is the result of OpenTagFn.
label: Opening Tag For Structure
openingTagForStructure

comment: (computerProcessID COMP PROC ID) means that ComputerProcessRunning PROC is running on Computer COMP with IDString ID.
label: Computer Process ID
computerProcessID

comment: (rationalIntermediateGoals AGT CYCFORMULA1 CYCFORMULA2) means that, given the agent's overall beliefs and goals, it would be rational for the agent to adopt CYCFORMULA1 as an intermediateGoals in order to achieve CYCFORMULA2. Note that the sense of 'rationality' used here is merely 'economic' rationality; i.e., rationality relative to attaining ones goals, given one's beliefs. No evaluation of the rationality of the ends, or of the beliefs of the agent, is presumed here. Note also that, as a default, Cyc assumes that agents act rationally, i.e., that they adopt as intermediateGoals their rationalIntermediateGoals.
label: Rational Intermediate Goals
rationalIntermediateGoals

comment: (candidateNthSubSituationTypeDuringType SCRIPT SIT SCENE SUBSIT N) means that 1) it is possible in the context of the assertion that (and (isa SUBSIT (NthSubSituationTypeFn SCRIPT SCENE N)) (isa SIT SCRIPT) (subSituations SIT SUBSIT)), 2) some evidence for the conjunction exists, and 3) at least one of the three conjuncts is an unknownSentence in the context of the assertion. It also presupposes that (iteratedProperSubSituationTypes SCRIPT SCENE).
label: Candidate Nth Sub Situation Type During Type
candidateNthSubSituationTypeDuringType

comment:
A quaternary predicate that is used to put a constraint on the size of Quantity that a given QuantitySlot can relate a given thing to. (quantityConstraint SLOT THING COMPARE LIMIT) means that for any quantity QUANT such that (SLOT THING QUANT) is true, the comparison constraint (COMPARE QUANT LIMIT) must hold.

For example,

(quantityConstraint heightOfObject EiffelTower greaterThan (Meter 200))

means that the height of the Eiffel Tower is more than 200 meters.
label: Quantity Constraint
quantityConstraint

comment: (numberOfPrescriptionsDuring DRUGTYPE RXFILLTYPE PERIOD NUM) means that NUM DrugPrescriptions of type RXFILLTYPE have been filled for DRUGTYPE during PERIOD. RXFILLTYPE may be FillingAPrescription_Retail, FillingAPrescription_MailOrder, FillingANewPrescription, FillingARefillPrescription, intersections of these, or merely FillingAPrescription.
label: Number Of Prescriptions During
numberOfPrescriptionsDuring

comment: (hasPurposeInWork WORK DOCSTRUC PURPOSE) means that the GraphicalStructure DOCSTRUC is contained within the StructurallySpecificWork WORK (see containsStructure_CW) and has the #$DocumentStructurePurposeAttribute PURPOSE within WORK.
label: Has Purpose In Work
hasPurposeInWork

comment: (representsAgentInEvent REPRESENTATIVE AGENT EVENT) means that REPRESENTATIVE is an agent who represents AGENT in the temporal situation EVENT. It is not uncommon for the same REPRESENTATIVE to represent multiple agents in the same EVENT, e.g. when someone is appointed to represent the interests of a group.
label: Represents Agent In Event
representsAgentInEvent

comment: (collectionIntersection2 COL GENL1 GENL2) means that COL is the intersection of GENL1 and GENL2. Every instance of COL is an instance of GENL1 and GENL2. Each Collection that is a spec of both GENL1 and GENL2 is also a spec of COL.
label: Collection Intersection 2
collectionIntersection2

comment: (laborForceFractionDuring REGION COL THING NR) means that NR is the quotient of the labor force of the economic sector or occupation COL in the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING (as dividend) and the total labor force of REGION during the temporal extent of THING (as divisor), where the labor force (of an economic sector or occupation) in a region at a point in time is the sum of the number of persons employed and unemployed (in the sector or occupation) in the region. COL can range from a broad economic sector, such as agriculture, manufacturing, or services to a more specific segment of the economy such as the automobile industry; in either of these cases, COL will be a specialization of the collection Industry_Localized. Alternatively, COL can be an instance of the collection PersonTypeByOccupation. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that agriculture accounted for 37 percent of Oman's labor force in 1993, we can say (laborForceFractionDuring Oman AgriculturalEconomicSector (YearFn 1993) (Percent 37)). See also laborForceDuring and laborForceOfIndustryOrOccupationDuring.
label: Labor Force Fraction During
laborForceFractionDuring

comment:
An instance of RuleMacroPredicate. predExpansionListForType relates a predicate PREDICATE to a collection TYPE and a list LIST of binary predicates such that: 1) Each member MEMBER-1 through MEMBER-N of LIST has an arg1Isa that is at least as general as TYPE; 2) The placement of MEMBER-M in list as its Mth member indicates that the arg2Isa of MEMBER is consistent with the argMthIsa of PREDICATE; a conjunction of the form, 
  (and
    (isa ?TYPE-INS TYPE)
    (MEMBER-1 ?TYPE-INS ARG-2-MEMBER-1)
       .
       .
       .
    (MEMBER-N ?TYPE-INS ARG-2-MEMBER-N))
entails a sentence of the form, 
  (PREDICATE ARG-2-MEMBER-1 ... ARG-2-MEMBER-N);
and 3) from 
  (PREDICATE ARG-2-MEMBER-1 ... ARG-2-MEMBER-N)
a sentence of the form, 
  (thereExists ?TYPE-INS
    (and
      (isa ?TYPE-INS TYPE)
      (MEMBER-1 ?TYPE-INS ARG-2-MEMBER-1)
         .
         .
         .
      (MEMBER-N ?TYPE-INS ARG-2-MEMBER-N)))
follows. Thus (predExpansionListForType TYPE LIST PREDICATE) means that PREDICATE is fully axiomatizable -- rules giving necessary and sufficient conditions for its application can be authored -- in the way indicated above. An important specialization of predExpansionListForType is nonDavidsonianPredReln, which allows one to define a non-davidsonian predicate from a series of binary situation predicates and a given situation-type.
label: Pred Expansion List For Type
predExpansionListForType

comment: A predicate to describe how normal a thing is to a 'typical observer'. (normalityOfThing THING COL NORMALITY) means that, for an instance of COL, THING has the normality level NORMALITY for a typical observer. The notion of typical observer will, of course, be dependent on the microtheory in which the assertion is made. Such assertions need to be asserted in sufficiently specific contexts. Note that normality is different from but related to frequency (e.g. frequencyOfActionType, Frequency). For example, a mechanic sees broken cars every day, but those cars are still abnormal cars. To assert the normality of thing for a particular observer, see normalityForAgent.
label: Normality Of Thing
normalityOfThing
Compute Relevant Subcollection
computeRelevantSubcollection
comment: (computeRelevantSubcollection COL) means that it makes sense to compute the relevant subcollection of COL. Making a computeRelevantSubcollection assertion will cause certain forward rules to fire and thereby the KB will might know what SUBCOL is such that (relevantSubcollection COL SUBCOL) and some of the ELEMENT such that (isaRelevantInstance ELEMENT COL).

An assertion of the form (argIsaConstantModeForDetermination PRED N TYPE DET) means that relative to the InductiveLogicProgrammingDetermination DET, the Nth argument of the Predicate PRED should be an instance of the Collection TYPE and that argument position has a constant mode (i.e., for the induction of rules, that argument must have a constant as its value and cannot take a variable). The sense of mode here is derived from Prolog_ComputerLanguage.
label: Arg Isa Constant Mode For Determination
argIsaConstantModeForDetermination

comment: This generalization of skillCapableOf can be used to assert that a given individual agent has the ability to play a certain role in a certain type of #$LearnedActivity (q.v.). (learnedCapableOf AGENT ACTTYPE ROLE) means that AGENT has acquired the necessary abilities to act in ROLE in normal instances of ACTTYPE. For example, that #$Gumby has learned to walk is expressed by (learnedCapableOf #$Gumby WalkingOnTwoLegs performedBy). learnedCapableOf entails that AGENT satisfies any physical or intellectual prerequisites for acquiring, possessing, and exercising the ability; but it is neutral as to whether AGENT has the necessary resources of time, money, opportunity, etc., to exercise the ability in any particular instance of ACTTYPE. Note that ROLE should normally be a fairly "central" one to ACTTYPEs, i.e. a specialization of doneBy or deliberateActors.
label: Learned Capable Of
learnedCapableOf

comment: A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly genls based relationship holds between the second argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg2ResultGenls FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when a subcollection of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the second argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value of that function for those arguments is a subcollection of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is a subcollection of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is a subcollection of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg2ResultGenls _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultGenl.
label: Inter Arg 2 Result Genls
interArg2ResultGenls

comment: (nodeOfTypeInNetwork HARDWARE HARDWARE-TYPE NETWORK) means that HARDWARE is one of the Computers that constitutes the ComputerNetwork NETWORK, and HARDWARE plays the role of HARDWARE-TYPE in NETWORK. This predicate is useful for stating that computers are nodes (with particular roles) in networks larger than a local area network. For instance, (nodeOfTypeInNetwork Router001 Router_Network Internet) means that Router001 is a network router on the Internet. label: Node Of Type In Network

comment: (nthLargestElement X N SET FUNCTION) means that X is an element of SET that has precisely N-1 other elements with a larger value for FUNCTION. For example, (nthLargestElement Alaska_State 1 State_UnitedStates (FunctionToArg 2 areaOfRegion)) means that Alaska is the largest state (no elements have a larger areaOfRegion). Yet there may be more nthLargestElements. For example, (nthLargestElement ?X 1 (TheSet 1 2 3 -3) AbsoluteValueFn) is true for both 3 and -3 ; when the elements in the set are ordered according to their absolute value both 3 and -3 are largest elements. See also nthSmallestElement.
label: Nth Largest Element

comment: (exportAmountDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE exported by the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of automobile exports, for example, AMOUNT might be an Integer indicating the number of cars exported. In the case of oil exports, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil exported, or it might be an instance of MonetaryValue indicating the monetary value of all the oil exported. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of export of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION during the temporal extent of THING. Oil exports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day or in terms of so many dollars per day (again, indicating the monetary value of the oil). The total value of a region's exports of all goods and services (over a given time period) can be expressed with this predicate using the constant Product as the second argument.
label: Export Amount During
exportAmountDuring

Intuitively, (latestDateOfFactOfCalendarCoveringType ASSERT CAL-TYPE DATE) means that DATE is the latest date of type CAL-TYPE at which the content expressed by ASSERT is known to be true in the KB.

latestDateOfFactOfCalendarCoveringType

inconsistentMeanings

(occurrenceNOfStringInStructure CIS INTEGER STRING STRUCTURE) means that the instance CIS of TextStringOccurrence is the INTEGERth occurrence of the instance STRING of CharacterString in (is a subInfoStructures of) the instance of AbstractStructure STRUCTURE.

comment: assertTemplate_Test relates a class of natural language statements (e.g. sentences) to CycL. In addition to the slot for the Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation, assertTemplate-Test also has a test that must succeed for the template to match. For example, (assertTemplate_Test STemplate objectHasColor ((NPTemplate :obj) (#$Be-TheWord Verb) (AdjPTemplate :color)) (objectHasColor :obj :color) (isa :color Color)) would map "Muffet is green" to (objectHasColor Muffet GreenColor), but would not match "Muffet is happy.".

assertTemplate-Test

comment: (decreases_Generic TEMP-THING THING SLOT) means the value of the predicate SLOT applied to THING (in the first argument position) will decrease over some time period after the start of TEMP-THING. Compared with its value immediately before TEMP-THING, the value of SLOT applied to THING will be lower immediately following or some time after the start of TEMP-THING. This is the most generic of the SlotTrendPredicates relating to decreasing of a given QuantitySlot: the decrease may be causal, or may not be, and may occur immediately, or over a period of time following TEMP-THING. For GAFs, or in the consequents of rules dealing with decreased quantities, use the more specific predicates if possible. See #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for a map of related predicates.
label: Decreases-Generic
decreases-Generic
Procedure On Animal Body Part Type Status
procedureOnAnimalBodyPartTypeStatus

comment:
A MetaPredicate that is used to state that a given predicate is 'reflexive' in a certain sense with respect to two of its argument-places. (reflexiveInArgs PRED M N) means that whenever PRED holds with a given thing in its Mth (or Nth) argument-place, then it also holds with that same thing in both its Mth and Nth argument-places (keeping all the other arguments fixed).

More precisely, (reflexiveInArgs PRED M N) means that if PRED holds of a given sequence of arguments ARGS, then it also holds of both (i) the sequence obtained by replacing the Nth item in ARGS with a (repeat occurrence) of the Mth item and (ii) the sequence obtained by replacing the Mth item in ARGS with a (repeat occurrence) of the Nth item. Put schematically (and supposing without loss of generality that M<N), if this holds:

(1) (PRED ... THINGM ... THINGN ...)

then so do both of these:

(2a) (PRED ... THINGM ... THINGM ...)

(2b) (PRED ... THINGN ... THINGN ...)

where the argument-sequence in (2a) is just like that in (1) except for having THINGM as its Mth and Nth items (and analogously for (2b) with respect to THINGN).

For example, a ternary predicate called compatriotsOf that took as its arguments two persons (not constrained to be distinct) and a geopolitical entity would be reflexive in its first and second arguments.

Every ReflexiveBinaryPredicate (q.v.) is of course reflexive in its (only) two argument-places. But note that the converse is not true: a binary predicate BINPRED such that (reflexiveInArgs BINPRED 1 2) holds might not be fully reflexive. For the reflexive-in-args property only entails that if a thing THING stands in the BINPRED relation to something (in either argument-place) then (BINPRED THING THING) holds, while a ReflexiveBinaryPredicate relates everything (that satisfies the predicate's argument-type constraints) to itself. Thus, a binary predicate attendsTheSameChurchAs would be reflexiveInArgs in its two argument-places, but not a ReflexiveBinaryPredicate.
label: Reflexive In Args
reflexiveInArgs

comment: (typeMakesMoreVulnerableThan_Object THREAT-OBJ1 THREAT-OBJ2 OBJECT-TYPE HARM-TYPE) means that otherwise normal interactions of existing things of type THREAT-OBJ1 with existing things of type OBJECT-TYPE generally make the latter more vulnerable to hardships of type HARM-TYPE than do interactions with existing things of type THREAT-OBJ2. This predicate provides a broad method to express that some classes of objects pose greater risks than others and should enable broad, comparative vulnerability knowledge representations. For a similar, instance level predicate see makesMoreVulnerableThan_Object.
label: Type Makes More Vulnerable Than Object
typeMakesMoreVulnerableThan-Object

comment: (typeSoleFunction SE-TYPE SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that if INS is an instance of SE-TYPE then, (soleFunction INS SIT-TYPE ROLE): i.e., all instances of SE-TYPE have as their sole function playing role ROLE in situations of type SIT-TYPE, and this as the result of the design of some intelligent agent or user.
label: Type Sole Function
typeSoleFunction

comment: A predicate used for probability statements. (bayesParentSet BAYESVARIABLE SETOFBAYESVARIABLES BAYESNET) means that the BayesDiscreteOutcome associated with each bayes variable in the set SETOFBAYESVARIABLES influences the BayesDiscreteOutcome associated with BAYESVARIABLE, and that each member of SETOFBAYESVARIABLES is an immediate 'parent node' of the BAYESVARIABLE node in the Bayesian Network BAYESNET representing probabilistic influence in the applicable Microtheory. That is, each BayesVariable in SETOFBAYESVARIABLES is a direct parent of BAYESVARIABLE in the BayesNet. Note that BAYESVARIABLE and any BayesVariable in SETOFBAYESVARIABLES cannot be conditionallyIndependent in the Microtheory since one is a bayesParent of the other. Given the outcome associations of all the members of SETOFBAYESVARIABLES (bayesParent nodes), then all of BAYESVARIABLE's further ancestor nodes and other non-descendant nodes are conditionallyIndependent of it in the applicable Microtheory. To relate a node to a single one of its parent nodes, rather than the whole set, use bayesParent.
label: Bayes Parent Set
bayesParentSet

comment:
A ternary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate and a specialization of completeExtentDecidableForValueInArg (q.v.) that can apply to a predicate and a specified value for a specified argument-place. (completeExtentEnumerableForValueInArg PRED VALUE N) means that the CycInferenceEngine can enumerate every sequence in the extent of PRED whose Nth item is VALUE. In practical terms this means that, if asked a query of the form (PRED ... VALUE ...), where VALUE appears in the Nth argument-position and all of the other positions (>= 1) are filled with variables, the Inference Engine can return an extensionally complete list of binding-sequences for those variables. That is, for every sequence SEQ in PRED's extension whose Nth member is VALUE (and for nothing else), the returned list contains a sequence of bindings (i.e. CycL terms) whose members denote, pointwise, the members of SEQ excepting VALUE.

For example, (completeExtentEnumerableForValueInArg hasMembers InternationalMonetaryFund 1) holds, as Cyc can enumerate all the members of the International Monetary Fund.

If PRED's extent is completely enumerable for VALUE in the Nth argument and a given sequence of bindings <TERM1, ..., TERM(N-1), TERM(N+1), ...> (whose length matches the arity of PRED, if fixed) is not returned for the above query, that fact consitutes a strong argument for the truth of the negation (not (PRED TERM1 ... TERM(N-1) VALUE TERM(N+1) ...)). But note that it is not a conclusive argument: the normally-reliable "unique name assumption" might fail here, and a term TERMi could conceivably denote something that Cyc can prove a member of a sequence in the extent of PRED only under some other CycL name it has. For suppose Pace resides in Texas, but nobody has told that to Cyc. Cyc can return the binding 'Texas_State' for the query '(cityInState CityOfDallasTX ?X)'; but it might nevertheless fail to return the equally correct binding '(StateOfResidenceFn #$Pace)'.

See also the specialization completeExtentAssertedForValueInArg and see completeExtentEnumerableForArg.
label: Complete Extent Enumerable For Value In Arg
completeExtentEnumerableForValueInArg
subPropertyOf: Complete Extent Decidable For Value In Arg
Non Abducible With Value In Arg
Not Abducible WRT Value In Arg

comment: (codeMapping MAP CODE DENOTATION) specifies one mapping for the reified mapping MAP. When a table uses MAP to interpret some field, the value CODE in that field will be interpreted as DENOTATION. DENOTATION will typically be a Cyc constant, but it might be a string or a number.

codeMapping

comment: This SimpleActionPredicate states that some agent (a Cyclist) has updated some BugzillaBugReport, either by changing its status, or by adding a comment, or both.

comment: (relativeImportanceOf IND1 IND2 GENERIC-VALUE) means that the relative importance of IND1 to IND2 is GENERIC-VALUE. In other words, for an agent who owns, controls, or is otherwise responsible for IND2, IND1 is important to degree GENERIC-QUANTITY.

relativeImportanceOf

comment: The predicate legallyCapableOf indicates that an agent is legally able to take a certain role in a certain type of action. (legallyCapableOf AGENT SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that the individual AGENT is legally qualified and/or entitled to act in this ROLE in Situations of the type SIT-TYPE. For example, a person over 35 years of age is legallyCapableOf becoming UnitedStatesPresident. This notion of legal capability should not be confused with the legality or illegality of an action.

legallyCapableOf
