Backchain Forbidden
backchainForbidden
comment: backchainForbidden is a predicate that allows users to cut down on the number of rules used to prove certain literals, and thus to increase the speed of inferences that involve proving those literals. (backchainForbidden PREDICATE) means that no rules containing a positive literal with PREDICATE as the arg0 (in other words, no implies assertions in which a literal with PREDICATE as the arg0 appears in the consequent) will be used when attempting to prove (non-negated) literals with PREDICATE as the arg0. Asserting (backchainForbidden PREDICATE) is useful when all (non-negated) literals with PREDICATE as the arg0 are expected to be solvable by lookup of ground atomic formulas (GAF's) already in the KB, and so rules won't be needed to prove them. However, asserting (backchainForbidden PREDICATE) is usually counter-productive in contexts where some literals with PREDICATE as the arg0 are expected to be proven via backchaining on rules containing a positive literal with PREDICATE as the arg0. See also the related predicates backchainRequired, backchainEncouraged, and backchainDiscouraged.

An instance of SituationProfilingPredicate. (situationMightBeSubSituationType_ViaCoSubSituationType SIT SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE COSUBSIT COSUBSITTYPE) means that there is evidence to the effect that SIT is an instance of SUBSITTYPE, which is a sub-situation type (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes) of SITTYPE. The evidence is based on knowledge that some instance COSUBSIT of COSUBSITTYPE (which is a different sub-situation type of SUBSITTYPE) occurs in appropriate spatiotemporal proximity to SUBSITTYPE.
label: Situation Might Be Sub Situation Type Via Co Sub Situation Type
situationMightBeSubSituationType-ViaCoSubSituationType

comment: A predicate that relates a market to the price elasticity of supply (the responsiveness of supply to changes in price) for a product-type in that market, in terms of a real numeric value. (marketPriceElasticityOfSupply MARKET PRODUCT OLD-PRICE NEW-PRICE ELASTICITY) means that given a change in MARKET's price of PRODUCT from OLD-PRICE to NEW-PRICE, the elasticity of supply in response to that change has a numeric value of ELASTICITY.
label: elasticity of supply
marketPriceElasticityOfSupply

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that is used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relationship with respect to two collections. (relationExistsCountAll BINPRED COL1 COL2 N) means that for every instance INST of COL2 there are exactly N instances of COL1 (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) such that (BINPRED INST(i) INST) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). It is equivalent to (and so can be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 

  (implies
    (isa ?INST COL2)
    (thereExistExactly N ?INST-I
      (and
             (isa ?INST COL1)
             (BINPRED ?INST-I ?INST)))) .

For example, (relationExistsCountAll anatomicalParts Animal Head_AnimalBodyPart 1) means that every animal head is a part of exactly one animal. See also relationAllExistsCount and #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists Count All
relationExistsCountAll

comment: (affixRuleTypeMorphemePosition RULE-TYPE N MORPH) means that instances of RULE-TYPE are applicable when MORPH is in the Nth position of a word. Example: (affixRuleTypeMorphemePosition SuffixRule 2 LexicalSuffix) means that for a suffix rule to be relevant to a word, an instance of LexicalSuffix must be the second element of the word.
label: Affix Rule Type Morpheme Position
affixRuleTypeMorphemePosition

comment: (typeDeterminesValueOfArgInReln TYPE N PRED) identifies TYPE as the process of determining the value of the Nth argument in any formula FORMULA of the form (PRED . ARGS) where all of the argument-places in FORMULA are bound but for the Nth. For example, (typeDeterminesValueOfArgInReln CalculatingTheAPROnALoan 2 annualPercentageRate) identifies CalculatingTheAPROnALoan as the collection of instances of DeterminingTheValueOfASlot in which one determines the value of ?X in (annualPercentageRate LOAN ?X) for some LOAN.
label: Type Determines Value Of Arg In Reln
typeDeterminesValueOfArgInReln

comment: (requiredTypeForSubSituationType TYPE SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE) means that any instance SIT of the specialization of Situation SUBSITTYPE that is subSituations of some instance od SITTYPE requires a SomethingExisting of type TYPE as resource.
label: Required Type For Sub Situation Type
requiredTypeForSubSituationType

comment: This predicate is used to identify collections whose specs are reasonable to treat as "nameable" -- i.e., one might reasonaby use a name when making generic claims about the collection qua class of its instances. For example, one might use the word "cancer" as a name for the class of instances of Cancer conditions, say in "Cancer is a terrible disease."
label: Nameable Collection
nameableCollection

comment: This event-predicate template expresses the relation between the agent (active participant), the object (passive participant), the device and the location of an activity. Example: (doesToWithAtLocation WritingByHand #$Klein DOCUMENT FEATHER #$CycorpHeadquarters) is true iff Charles Klein writes (or: is writing) DOCUMENT with device FEATHER at Cycorp's main offices.
label: Does To With At Location
doesToWithAtLocation

comment: (sitTypeHasSubSitTypeWithRolePlayerOfType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE OBJ-TYPE ROLE) means that there is at least one subsituation of type SUBSIT-TYPE in any instance of SIT-TYPE that has an object of type OBJ-TYPE playing the role ROLE. There may be other subsituations of type SUBSIT-TYPE in the instance of SIT-TYPE which do not have an object of type OBJ-TYPE playing that role. See onlyTypePlaysRoleInSituationType for the meaning that every subsituation of type SUBSIT-TYPE in SIT-TYPE has an instance of OBJ-TYPE playing role ROLE, but not requiring any such subsituation to exist.
label: Sit Type Has Sub Sit Type With Role Player Of Type
sitTypeHasSubSitTypeWithRolePlayerOfType
Isit: Event Type
isit:EventType
comment:
An IKRIS inner theory term. It is defined by the following axiom: 

    (forAll ?X
        (implies 
          (isit:EventType ?X)
          (thereExists ?Y 
            (and 
              (genls ?Y Event)
              (forAll ?E 
                (equiv (isa ?E ?Y) (isit:instanceOf ?E ?X))))))))

Bascially, anything that has the property isit:EventType is such that there is some spec of event that it is coextensional with .

(commonIonTypeInCompoundTypes COMPOUND1 COMPOUND2 ION) holds if ION is the common ion of the decomposable compounds COMPOUND1 and COMPOUND2, in the sense of the `common ion effect.' This means either that both contain ION as part of their ionicDecomposition, or that ION is the common product of their dissociation. For example, AceticAcid and SodiumAcetate have a common ion: (commonIonTypeInCompoundTypes AceticAcid SodiumAcetate AcetateIon), but so do Ammonia and AmmoniumChloride.
label: shared ion type
commonIonTypeInCompoundTypes

comment: This ternary predicate is used to indicate that a creditor is required, by the terms of a type of loan agreement, to play a particular role in a particular kind of situation. (loanAgreementTypeRequiresOfCreditor AGREEMENT-TYPE SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that entering into an instance of AGREEMENT-TYPE (a specialization of LoanAgreement) requires the creditor to play the Role ROLE in some situation that is an instance of the subcollection of Situation SIT-TYPE.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: loan agreement type requirement on the creditors
label: loan agreement type requirement on the creditor
loanAgreementTypeRequiresOfCreditor

comment: An assertion of the form (regionContainsCountWithInfectionDuring PLACE HOST-TYPE COND-TYPE RANGE DATE) states that measurements made of the population of HOST-TYPE, some subcollection of Organism_Whole, in the GeographicalRegion PLACE for the Date DATE indicates that somewhere in the range of RANGE members of that population suffer from the PhysiologicalConditionType COND-TYPE. For example, (regionContainsCountWithInfectionDuring Syria HomoSapiens AIDS (IntervalRangeFn 0 500) (YearFn 2004)) states that measurements indicate that there are at most 500 members of the human population of Syria who were suffering from AIDS during 2004. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Region Contains Count With Infection During
regionContainsCountWithInfectionDuring
Instance In Role Highly Relevant To Role
instanceInRoleHighlyRelevantToRole

comment: '(sociallyCapableOf BEING SIT-TYPE ROLE)' means that BEING is able to play ROLE in social situations of type SIT-TYPE. This notion of social capability is the weak one of conceivability; for instance, no man is socially capable of playing the role of wife in a family, but any woman is. The relevant social group is one to which BEING belongs.
label: Socially Capable Of
sociallyCapableOf

comment: (antonymsForGenericValue SLOT LOW-WU HIGH-WU) means that the regularDegree forms of LOW-WU and HIGH-WU denote values at the low and high ends, respectively, of the scale determined by SLOT.
label: Antonyms For Generic Value
antonymsForGenericValue

comment:
An instance of KEFacilitationPredicate used to constrain the pragmatic relevance of the values of certain properties for things of a given type. Specifically, (keRelevantPrecisionValueForSlotOnType BINPRED TYPE SIZE) indicates that we should regard an instance of TYPE as having a known value for the property expressed by the QuantitySlot BINPRED only when the instance of ScalarInterval that is its value has an intervalSize no greater than SIZE.

For example, we would reasonably claim to know the age of a particular dog Fido if we can prove that (age Fido (YearsDuration 6)), but not if we could prove merely that (age Fido (YearsDuration 1 19)) -- which is most likely true, of course, since it is so of most dogs. But this is fact about (knowledge about) dogs or animals in general. So: (keRelevantPrecisionValueForSlotOnType age Animal (YearsDuration 1)) would express this constraint.
label: Ke Relevant Precision Value For Slot On Type
keRelevantPrecisionValueForSlotOnType

comment: (worldProductionAmountDuring PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) says that the NonNegativeScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the total amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE produced anywhere in the world during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING.
label: World Production Amount During
worldProductionAmountDuring

comment: An instance of TernaryPredicate, used for tersely expressing a certain class of deontic assertions. oughtTo_RoleInType relates an instance of IntelligentAgent, a specialization of Event, and an instance of BinaryRolePredicate, so as to express the deontic requirement that the agent play that role in an event of that type. For example, (oughtTo_RoleInType Person001 CharitableDonation giver) says that Person001 ought to make a donation to some charity. (oughtTo_RoleInType AGENT EVENT-TYPE ROLE) expands into (oughtToDo AGENT (relationExistsInstance ROLE EVENT-TYPE AGENT)).
label: Ought To Role In Type
oughtTo-RoleInType

comment: An instance of SummaryPredicate useful for summarizing knowledge about THING with respect to PredicateTypes. (predicateTypeSummaryForThing PRED-TYPE THING SENTENCE) means that CycLSentence_Assertible SENTENCE has PRED (an instance of PRED-TYPE) in its arg0 slot and it has the term THING in some slot other than arg0. For example, (predicateTypeSummaryForThing LikesPredicate #$JenniferSullivan (likesAsFriend #$JenniferSullivan #$Cynthia)) is true, and means that some instance of LikesPredicate occurs as the arg0 in (likesAsFriend #$JenniferSullivan #$Cynthia), and that #$JenniferSullivan also occurs in (likesAsFriend #$JenniferSullivan #$Cynthia). This predicate is particularly useful for asking queries with the first and second argument slots bound and the third slot open. For example, asking (predicateTypeSummaryForThing OrganismRequirementsPredicate (AdultFn Dachshund) ?SENTENCE) will mean the system will find any assertions whose arg0 is an instance of OrganismRequirementsPredicate that also contain the term (AdultFn Dachshund). Cf. predicateTypeSummaryForThing_Set.
label: Predicate Type Summary For Thing
predicateTypeSummaryForThing
No Possible Antecedent
noPossibleAntecedent
comment: This is a UnaryPredicate used to flag LinguisticExpressionPegs which have no possible antecedents (see contextuallyPossibleAntecedent) in the local disourse context. This can bu used as a rough guide for identifying referents in need of "bridging" assertions.
(skolemizeForward FUNC) tells the inference engine that terms should be generated for fully-bound uses of FUNC during forward inference.
label: Skolemize Forward
skolemizeForward

comment:
(termForTemplatePositions TERM TEMPLATE-TYPE LIST) means that in the context of using TEMPLATE-TYPE, TERM is passed to positions in templates in a manner described by LIST, according to the following convention. LIST is a list of sub-lists, each of which has a template TEMPLATE as a first argument and some non-zero number of FormulaArgPositions as subsequent elements. In each sub-list, the FormulaArgPositions indicate where to pass TERM as a value to arguments to TEMPLATE. For example, the following formula would hold in the context in which one was adding a scene to a BrushingTeeth script with #$SceneInScriptedEventType-TopicType:

(termForTemplatePositions BrushingTeeth #$SceneInScriptedEventType-TopicType (TheList (TheList #$SceneActorTypesTemplate (FormulaArgPositionFn 1)) (TheList #$SceneRelatedToScriptTemplate (FormulaArgPositionFn 1)) (TheList #$ScriptQuasiTemporalOrderingToOtherSceneTemplate (FormulaArgPositionFn 1)) (TheList #$ScriptQuasiTemporalOrderingFromOtherSceneTemplate (FormulaArgPositionFn 1)))).
label: Term For Template Positions
termForTemplatePositions

comment: (relationExistsMember PRED COLL GROUP) means that for every MEMBER such that (groupMembers GROUP MEMBER), there exists an instance INS of collection COLL such that (PRED INS MEMBER) is true. This predicate enables one to make claims about the members of a group without referencing the members.
label: Relation Exists Member
relationExistsMember

comment:
(startsDuringInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 starts during SIT2.

For example, (startsDuringInSituationType UnwindingOfDNAHelix Transcription_DNAToRNA GeneExpression) means that when DNA unwinds, DNA to RNA transcription starts during gene expression.

Note that (startsDuringInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).
label: Starts During In Situation Type
startsDuringInSituationType
subPropertyOf: Starts After Start Of In Situation Type
Temporal Bounds Intersect In Situation Type

comment: (exposureOfObjectToSubstanceType EXPOSURE OBJECT CONTAMINANT-TYPE) means that during EXPOSURE, OBJECT is exposed to substance of the type CONTAMINANT-TYPE.
label: Exposure Of Object To Substance Type
exposureOfObjectToSubstanceType

comment: (httpdRequestQueryTemplateForSKS WEB-PAGE PHYSICAL-SCHEMA EXPRESSION) states that the web service WEB-PAGE uses EXPRESSION as the query template involving the values for physical fields from PHYSICAL-SCHEMA.
label: Httpd Request Query Template For SKS
httpdRequestQueryTemplateForSKS

comment: (hasAssociatedCMLS THING CMLS AIS) means that SKSI translations involving THING utilize the reified mapping CMLS. Typically THING will be a predicate whose values for a certain argument place utilize the mappings in CMLS.
label: Has Associated CMLS
hasAssociatedCMLS

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates an IntelligentAgent to an MonetaryValue to an Individual. (agentOffersRewardForProcurementOfIndividual AGENT REWARD INDIVIDUAL) means that AGENT is currently offering REWARD for the procurement (or information leading to the procurement) of INDIVIDUAL.

For example, (agentOffersRewardForProcurementOfIndividual (GovernmentFn UnitedStatesOfAmerica) (Dollar_UnitedStates 25000000) #$OsamaBinLaden) means that the U.S. Government is offering 25 million dollars for the procurement (i.e. capture), or information leading to the procurement/capture, of Osama bin Laden.

Similarly, (agentOffersRewardForProcurementOfIndividual Mario (Euro 50) MariosWallet) means that Mario is offering a reward of 50 Euro for the return (or information leading to the return) of his wallet.
label: Agent Offers Reward For Procurement Of Individual
agentOffersRewardForProcurementOfIndividual

comment: A predicate for enumerating assertions to be ignored by the reformulator in a particular specification. (skipAssertionInReformulation SPEC RULE INT) means the reformulator should ignore assertion RULE when invoked by SPEC. The value of RULE is passed to the CycLReformulator parameter :skip-assertions as a list. The value of INT is the place where RULE appears in the list.
label: Skip Assertion In Reformulation
skipAssertionInReformulation

comment: (vulnerabilityCascades SOURCE-TYPE OBJ-TYPE RESULT-TYPE) means that in cases where an instance of SOURCE-TYPE makes an instance of OBJ-TYPE vulnerable to results of type RESULT-TYPE, the vulnerability transfers across other instances of SOURCE-TYPE and OBJ-TYPE. In practical terms this means that every instance of OBJ-TYPE will be vulnerable to (or in) every instance of SOURCE-TYPE. It also means that one should take *extreme* care in making assertions with vulnerabilityCascades. Typical examples will be conceptually true.
label: Vulnerability Cascades
vulnerabilityCascades

comment: (posConstraintForNCR RULE INDEXICAL POS) means that RULE requires its NounCompoundRuleIndexicalTerm_Direct term INDEXICAL to satisfy the TermPhrasesConstraint POS. In general, this means that there is a ncRuleConstraint relating rule RULE to the constraint (NCPOSConstraintFn INDEXICAL POS).
label: Pos Constraint For NCR
posConstraintForNCR

comment:
A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keSuggestionPredsInverse_InsIns COL1 BINPRED COL2) means that for every known instance INS1 of COL1, it is suggested that there be some instance INS2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED INS2 INS1) is known in the knowledge base.

For example,

(keSuggestionPredsInverse_InsIns Cuisine commonFoodTypeOfCuisine DefaultDisjointEdibleStuffType)

means that for every known instance CUIS of Cuisine it is suggested that there be an instance ES-TYPE of DefaultDisjointEdibleStuffType) such that (commonFoodTypeOfCuisine ES-TYPE CUIS) is known in the knowledge base.

See also keSuggestionPreds_InsIns.
label: Ke Suggestion Preds Inverse Ins Ins
keSuggestionPredsInverse-InsIns

comment:
This predicate is a directive for the CycSalientDescriptor. (uninterestingQueryForRelnWithTypeInArg RELN TYPE ARG) means that for any query on RELN where INS is an instance of TYPE, and INS stands in argument place ARG of RELN, (RELN INS VARIABLE) is an uninteresting question.

For example, (uninterestingQueryForRelnWithTypeInArg eventOccursAt MoneyTransaction 1) means that if TRANSACTION is an instance of MoneyTransaction, (eventOccursAt TRANSACTION WHERE) is an uninteresting question for the CycSalientDescriptor to ask.
label: Uninteresting Query For Reln With Type In Arg
uninterestingQueryForRelnWithTypeInArg

comment: (bindingSiteBetween CHEMICAL CHEM_TYPE BINDING_SITE) means that chemicals of type CHEM_TYPE will preferentially bond to CHEMICAL at BINDING_SITE, which is a molecularSubComponents of CHEMICAL.
label: Binding Site Between
bindingSiteBetween

comment: (effectiveDoseForOrganismType SUBSTANCE-TYPE ROUTE-TYPE EFFECT-TYPE PERCENTAGE ORGANISM-TYPE DOSE) means that an amount DOSE of SUBSTANCE-TYPE when taken in via ROUTE-TYPE will produce EFFECT-TYPE in PERCENTAGE of ORGANISM-TYPE.
label: effective dose
effectiveDoseForOrganismType

comment: The predicate infoContributed is used to identify which agent said what in a particular complex communication activity. (infoContributed MULTICOM AGENT INFO) means that in the MultiDirectionalCommunication event MULTICOM, AGENT does something that expresses INFO. Note that speaking, writing, or otherwise signalling are all viable methods of `saying'. The (unspecified) thing that AGENT does in MULTICOM generates the message, and INFO is a propositional item expressing the content of AGENT's message. See also PropositionalInformationThing and IBTGeneration.
label: Info Contributed
infoContributed

comment: programRecodesFromTo is a ternary predicate that relates an instance of FileTranslationProgram to two instances of ComputerFileTypeByFormat. (programRecodesFromTo PROG FORMAT-1 FORMAT-2) means that PROG translates file from FORMAT-1 to FORMAT-2.
label: Program Recodes From To
programRecodesFromTo

comment: (choicesForInPredSpecTask X Y LIST) means that the elements of LIST should be offered to the user as possible predicates relating X to Y.
label: Choices For In Pred Spec Task
choicesForInPredSpecTask

comment: The amount of money specified in ARG3 accrues to an account owned/controlled by ARG1 as a result of the action ARG2.
label: Revenue From Event
revenueFromEvent

comment: (subSituationTypeIteratesEventTypeOverSetWRTSlot SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE SUB-EVENT-TYPE SET SLOT) means that in every instance of SITTYPE each instance INST of SUBSITTYPE consists of one instance of SUB-EVENT-TYPE for each thing THING such that (elementOf THING SET). Also, each element of SET is related by SLOT via an assertion of the form (SLOT SUB-EVENT THING) to exactly one instance SUB-EVENT of SUB-EVENT-TYPE that is a sub-event of INST. Cf. situationTypeIsIteratedSubSituationType_OverSet.
label: Sub Situation Type Iterates Event Type Over Set WRT Slot
subSituationTypeIteratesEventTypeOverSetWRTSlot

comment: (rolesMapToProgramFunctionArgs EVENT-TYPE SLOT PROG-FUNCTION NUM) means that in order to bring about an instance of EVENT-TYPE via the ProgramFunction PROG-FUNCTION, the arg2 value of the appropriate assertion using SLOT must occur as the NUM argument to PROG-FUNCTION. For example, (rolesMapToProgramFunctionArgs SingleEMailSending eMailSendingTextSlot (ProgramFunctionFn "mail-message" (#$CycorpSysdclFileFn "mail-utilities.lisp")) 3) means that to bring about an instance INST of SingleEMailSending, if (eMailSendingTextSlot INST TEXT) holds, then TEXT must be passed to argument 3 of the function mail-message defined in the mail-utilities.lisp file of the Cycorp sysdcl.
label: Roles Map To Program Function Args
rolesMapToProgramFunctionArgs

comment: A predicate used to relate a product type in a market at a certain demand quantity to its total utility in terms of some MonetaryValue. (totalUtilityOfProductTypeAtQuantity MARKET PRODUCT UTILITY QUANTITY) means that the sum of the marginal utility values to consumers of QUANTITY instances of PRODUCT in MARKET is UTILITY.
label: Total Utility Of Product Type At Quantity
totalUtilityOfProductTypeAtQuantity

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat1_1 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the first argument-place of PRED when PRED's first argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ... ARGN) in which ARG1 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg1 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG1' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation. Note that interArgFormat1_1 is one of several "degenerate-case" inter-argument format predicates, in which the specified condition and the corresponding format constraint both have to do with the _same_ argument-place of a given predicate.
label: Inter Arg Format 1 1
interArgFormat1-1

comment: (oughtToBe_SitTypeRolePlayerOfType SIT-TYPE ROLE OBLIGATORY-TYPE) means that, given any instance INS of SIT-TYPE, at least one object playing ROLE in INS should be an instance of OBLIGATORY-TYPE. That is, there should be an instance OBLIGATORY-INS of OBLIGATORY-TYPE such that (ROLE INS OBLIGATORY-INS). Assertions involving this predicate -- which specify what should be the case -- should be made in a normative context, e.g., one that reflects the contents of a particular CodeOfConduct.
label: Ought To Be Sit Type Role Player Of Type
oughtToBe-SitTypeRolePlayerOfType

comment: An assertion of the form (percentDeathsDueToDuring PLACE ORG-TYPE SIT-TYPE PERCENT DATE) states that measurements made of the population of GeographicalRegion PLACE for the Date DATE indicate that PERCENT of the population died from playing the role of objectActedOn in some occurrence of TYPE, a sub-collection of Situation. For instance, an assertion of the form (percentDeathsDueToDuring Syria HomoSapiens AIDS (Percent .0001) (YearFn 2005)) would state that records indicate that .0001% of the human population of Syria died from AIDS during 2005. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Percent Deaths Due To During
percentDeathsDueToDuring
Do Open Local Variables Scope
doOpenLocalVariablesScope
comment: A variable arity complex action predicate. (doOpenLocalVariablesScope PROGRAMMER FILE . VARIABLES) means that PROGRAMMER appends code to the end of computer file FILE that creates a scope in which VARIABLES are available.
During the time interval ARG3, the amount of money specified by ARG4 accrues to ARG1 as a result of actions of type ARG2.
label: Revenue From Type
revenueFromType

comment: (speciesAddedToResultsIn CHEM-TYPE SAMPLE1 SAMPLE2) means that adding a certain (unspecified) amount of the ChemicalSubstanceType CHEM-TYPE to the PartiallyTangible SAMPLE1 results in PartiallyTangible SAMPLE2. Note that speciesAddedToResultsIn is an instance of FunctionalPredicate -- there is a unique SAMPLE2 that results from adding the relevant amount of CHEM-TYPE to SAMPLE1.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: results of adding a chemical species
label: result of adding a chemical species
speciesAddedToResultsIn

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat4_1 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the first argument-place of PRED when PRED's fourth argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ... ARGN) in which ARG4 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg1 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG1' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 4 1
interArgFormat4-1

comment: Where LIST is a list such that each element is a list consisting of a situation type and a BinaryRolePredicate, (situationTypeStages_ForRole SIT-TYPE ROLE LIST) means that in normal circumstances, any agent that plays the role ROLE in an instance of SIT-TYPE will play each of the roles appearing the elements of list, in situations of the types that appear with them, and in the temporal order given by LIST. Thus, for example, (situationTypeStages_ForRole #$ContractKill-Simple directingAgent (TheList (TheList EmployeeHiring hiringAgent) (TheList Murder beneficiary) (TheList PayingForServices fromPossessor)))) means that in a #$ContractKill-Simple, the directingAgent hires somebody (is the hiringAgent in an EmployeeHiring), benefits from the Murder (is the beneficiary in a Murder), and makes a payment (is the fromPossessor in a PayingForServices).
label: Situation Type Stages For Role
situationTypeStages-ForRole

comment:
A TaxonomicPredicateForPredicates used to state that, with respect to arguments of a specified type, one unary predicate generalizes to another. (genlPredsWRTType_Unary PRED1 PRED2 COL) means that, for any THING, if both of these hold: 
  (PRED1 THING)

  (isa THING COL)

then so does 

  (PRED2 THING).
For example, (genlPredsWRTType_Unary trueSentence trueSentence_CaseInsensitive CycLAtomicSentence) holds.

genlPredsWRTType_Unary allows us to specify a genlPreds -like relationship between two UnaryPredicates not related by genlPreds itself (and thus whose respective arg1Isa constraints might not be related by genls).

See also genlPredsWRTTypes (which applies to BinaryPredicates) and genlPredsWRTTypes_Ternary.
label: Genl Preds WRT Type Unary
genlPredsWRTType-Unary

comment: (vesselStenosisDegree EVENT CAS CORONARY-ARTERY-TYPE DEGREE) means that according to the information on CAS, that is associated with EVENT the stenosis degree on CORONARY-ARTERY-TYPE is DEGREE.
label: coronary artery stenosis degree
vesselStenosisDegree

comment: (promotesRisk EVENT AGENT RESULT-SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that if (doneBy EVENT AGENT), then EVENT contributes to AGENT being at risk for playing the role ROLE in a situation of type RESULT-SIT-TYPE as a result. This predicate is intended to be used to express long-term risks, like getting cancer from smoking. See also immediateRisk for risks that would occur during the event rather than at some later time.
label: promoting risk
promotesRisk
Type Subunit Type Linked By Type
typeSubunitTypeLinkedByType

comment: (num_GenQuant COL1 COL2 N) means that there are exactly N elements of COL1 which are also elements of COL2. This predicate is a sort of macro-predicate which can be used to represent the meaning of arbitrarily many English numeric determiners like "two", "three", etc. More specialiuzed predicates for specific numbers can be defined in terms of num_GenQuant. Thus, for instance, #$two-GenQuant can be defined as (num_GenQuant COL1 COL2 2).
label: At Least N Gen Quant
atLeastN-GenQuant
Scheduled Query Folder Of User For Task
scheduledQueryFolderOfUserForTask

comment: A TernaryPredicate. (editionOfPeriodicalByIssueNumber SERIES VOLUME ISSUE) means that ISSUE is the EditionOfCWSeries_Periodic of the PeriodicalSeries SERIES denoted by volume number ISSUE. See also EditionByIssueNumberFn.
label: Edition Of Periodical By Issue Number
editionOfPeriodicalByIssueNumber

comment: borderBetweenPolities BORDER GEO-1 GEO-2) holds just in case BORDER is the border between GEO-1 and GEO-2. This is the corresponding predicate to BorderBetweenPolitiesFn.
label: Border Between Polities
borderBetweenPolities

comment: (keSalientSpecPredicate PRED) means that PRED stands in the genlPreds relation to another predicate GEN-PRED that has already been designated as a keSalientPredicate, but PRED is a potentially valuable predicate, example uses for which might prove useful to a SME. The more general keSalientPredicates will appear in an example sentence for cloning in the Examples page of the UIA, and a link there will allow a SME to access the example sentences for spec preds marked as keSalientSpecPredicates.
label: Ke Salient Spec Predicate
keSalientSpecPredicate

comment: This event-predicate template expresses the relation between the agent (active participant) and the object (passive participant) of an activity. Example: (doesTo Cleaning #$PeterSuen PetersDesk) is true iff Peter cleans Peter's desk (or: is cleaning, depending on the way the assertion is temporally qualified).
label: Does To
doesTo

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat2_1 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the first argument-place of PRED when PRED's second argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ... ARGN) in which ARG2 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg1 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG1' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 2 1
interArgFormat2-1

comment: This is a specialized representation (semiotic) predicate meaning representation due to resemblance, such as when a portrait represents the person depicted. (signifiesTo_Icon THING1 THING2 AGENT) means that, to AGENT, THING1 represents THING2 because THING1 resembles THING2. This is called 'iconic' representation. Compare this with the predicates signifiesTo_Index and signifiesTo_Symbol. It's possible for all three to apply to the same representation. If the basis for the representation is unknown, use the more general predicate signifiesTo.
label: icon
signifiesTo-Icon

comment: (hasReasonForRoleInSitTypeWithRelationTo AGENT ROLE SIT-TYPE REL THING) means that AGENT has a reason or motive to play ROLE in an instance of SIT-TYPE which also stands in relation REL to THING. For example, if AGENT has a reason to travel to New York City, then we can say (hasReasonForRoleInSitTypeWithRelationTo AGENT primaryObjectMoving Travel_TripEvent toLocation CityOfNewYorkNY).
label: has reason to play role in situation of type that bears relation to thing
hasReasonForRoleInSitTypeWithRelationTo

comment: The corresponding predicate of the function RootAllotmentOfCollectionByAgentDuringFn.
label: Root Allotment Of Collection By Agent During
rootAllotmentOfCollectionByAgentDuring

comment: A sentence of the form (functionDescribesThingDuring FUNCTION OBJECT EVENT) means that the PhysicalQuantityOrVectorFunction FUNCTION describes some property (e.g., velocity, position along the x axis, etc.) of the PartiallyTangible OBJECT during the Event EVENT.
label: Function Describes Thing During
functionDescribesThingDuring

comment: (tourTransitsFrom TOUR MOVETYPE FROM) means that, according to its itinerary, TOUR is supposed to include a movement of type MOVETYPE from the PartiallyTangible FROM, considered as a fromLocation.
label: Tour Transits From
tourTransitsFrom

comment: (hardshipPropagatesViaRelation OBJ-TYPE1 OBJ-TYPE2 PRED SIT-TYPE) means that when an INST1 of OBJ-TYPE1 is related via the binary predicate PRED to some second instance INST2 of OBJ-TYPE2, hardships of type SIT-TYPE propagate from INST1 to INST2. Note that INST1 and INST2 do not have to be the same kind of thing, although in many cases they are. For instance, security weaknesses generally propagate through connected computer systems linked in certain ways, that is, if one computer is vulnerable to being attacked in a certain way so are others connected to it. We would represent one version of this as (hardshipPropagatesViaRelation ComputationalSystem ComputationalSystem equivalentHosts Cracking_CompromisingSecurity). A variant in which INST1 and INST2 would be different is (hardshipPropagatesViaRelation Computer ComputerNetwork parts Cracking_CompromisingSecurity).
label: Hardship Propagates Via Relation
hardshipPropagatesViaRelation

comment:
(nextSubSituationTypeToStart SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 is the next situation to start after SIT2.

Note that (nextSubSituationTypeToStart SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).

nextSubSituationTypeToStart

comment: (purchaseFromFractionDuring PT1 PRODUCT-TYPE PT2 THING NR) means that NR is the quotient of the monetary value of purchases of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE by the instance of PartiallyTangible PT1 from the instance of PartiallyTangible PT2 during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING (as dividend) and the monetary value of all purchases of PRODUCT-TYPE by PT1 during the temporal extent of THING (as divisor). PT1 might, for example, be a Country or a Business; and likewise for PT2. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that Norway has a 25 percent share of the European natural gas market in 1998, we can say (purchaseFromFractionDuring ContinentOfEurope NaturalGas Norway (YearFn 1998) (Percent 25)).
label: Purchase From Fraction During
purchaseFromFractionDuring

Note: the first argument can be a non-human intelligent agent, such as a dog or a company, because we often ascribe feelings and emotions to them, and they often behave consistently with having such feelings and emotions. See also feelsTowardsEvent.

comment: (regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfAdjacentDirections REGION-TYPE LEVEL NUM-SIDES) means that NUM-SIDES of REGION-TYPE that have a LEVEL kind of slope are adjacent to one another. For example, (regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfAdjacentDirections Saddle TerrainLowGround 0) means that, of the total number of low ground sides of a saddle, none of them are adjacent. Similarly, (regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfAdjacentDirections Saddle TerrainHighGround 0) means that, of the total number of high ground sides of a saddle, none of them are adjacent. Thus, if there are a total of two high ground and two low ground sides of a saddle, then the two similarly sloping sides are across from one another. To specify the total number of sides that are LEVEL, see regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfDirections. To specify slopes at an instance level, see #$regionSlopeOfSidesFromPoint and #$regionSlopeOfAdjacentSidesFromPoint.

regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfAdjacentDirections

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relationship with respect to two collections. (relationAllExistsMin BINPRED COL1 COL2 N) means that for any instance INST of COL1 there are at least N instances (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST INST(i)) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(implies (isa ?INST COL1) (thereExistAtLeast N ?INST-I (and (isa ?INST-I COL2) (BINPRED ?INST ?INST-I)))) .

For example, `(relationAllExistsMin subEvents EatingEvent Swallowing 1)' means that every act of eating includes at least one swallowing. Cf. relationExistsMinAll, and see #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation All Exists Min
relationAllExistsMin

comment: (linkCutSetBetweenInSystem SET X Y SYS) means that SET is a link-cut-set in the ConnectedPathSystem SYS, and that the points X and Y in SYS are disconnected in the subsystem of SYS obtained by cutting all links in SET from SYS. More strictly, (linkCutSetBetweenInSystem SET X Y SYS) is true if and only if (linkCutSetInSystem SET SYS) is true and (connectedInSystem X Y (LinksCut_SubSystemFn SYS SET)) is false.

That is, (RELN ... ARGN ...) is semantically well-formed only if (quotedIsa ARGN COL) holds. For example, (argQuotedIsa examplePredSentences 1 CycLSentence) holds.

comment: The predicate harmfulProposition is used to state a condition that, if true, would (normally) diminish an agent's chances of success in a particular effort. (harmfulProposition ENDEAVOR PROP GVP) means that if the #$ELSentence-Assertible PROP is true, then AGENT (who is referred to in PROP) will (normally) be hindered in achieving the PurposefulAction ENDEAVOR. GVP is a GenericValuePredicate whose role is to suggest how damaging such an occurrence would be to the success of ENDEAVOR. For example, in a basketball game, it's normally very detrimental if one or more of the team's players is shorter than the average adult. Thus, for any particular game, a highToVeryHighAmountOf disadvantage is indicated if the following harmfulProposition (expressed in CycL) is true: (heightOfObject PLAYER-X (RelativeGenericValueFn heightOfObject HumanAdult veryLowAmountOf)). (Rohrbaugh, 2/1998)
label: Harmful Proposition
harmfulProposition

comment: (limitsObservationOfFrom STHG REG1 REG2) means that STHG conceals or in some manner limits the observation powers possible from REG2 when trying to observe REG1. This predicate embodies two aspects of the OCOKA principles, namely those of Concealment and of Observation. (limitsObservationOfFrom SmokeScreen001 GarnerValley GumbyHill) says that any object in GarnerValley has good concealment from observation from GumbyHill, since SmokeScreen001 prevents observation of those objects from GumbyHill. So this predicate can be used to describe both Concealment (in this case, from the perspective of objects in GarnerValley -- cf. also #$providesConcealmentInCOA) and Observation (here, from the perspective of prospective observers on GumbyHill). Whether a unit seeks to maximize concealment or observation is based on an interaction between the METT-TC principles. Note that if RedUnit001 occupied a position in GarnerValley and BlueUnit001 occupies GumbyHill, it is possible to use this predicate for something like 'SmokeScreen001 currently limits the observation of RedUnit001 by BlueUnit001.'
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: limitations on observation from a particular place
label: limitation on observation from a particular place
limitsObservationOfFrom

Note that each link in a semi-directed path system (see Semi_DirectedPathSystem) must be directed one way or the other or both, and each link in a directed path system (see DirectedPathSystem) must be directed one way or the other but not both, and each link in a bidirected path system (see BidirectedPathSystem) must be directed in both ways.

comment:
A MetaRelation predicate used for stating that one of the arguments to a given function always stands in a specified Relation to the corresponding result returned by the function. (interArgResultReln FUNC N RELN) means that, for any admitted sequence of arguments ARGS to FUNC, the Nth item ARGN of ARGS stands in RELN to the result of applying FUNC to ARGS. Stated schematically: if (FUNC . ARGS) = RESULT, then (RELN ARGN RESULT) holds. For example, 
  (interArgResultReln #$SubPathInsideRegionFn 1 subPaths)
means that the result of applying #$SubPathInsideRegionFn to a given PATH and REGION is itself a sub-path of PATH.

See also interResultArgReln.
label: Inter Arg Result Reln
interArgResultReln

comment: (nearestDifferentGenlMt MT-1 MT-2 NEAR-DIFF) means that NEAR-DIFF is a "nearest" microtheory of which MT-1 is a specialization, but MT-2 is not. That is, (genlMt MT-1 NEAR-DIFF) holds, (genlMt MT-2 NEAR-DIFF) does not hold, MT-1 and NEAR-DIFF are not identical, and there is no reified Microtheory NEARER-DIFF distinct from NEAR-DIFF and MT-1 such that (genlMt MT-1 NEARER-DIFF) holds, (genlMt MT-2 NEARER-DIFF) does not hold, and (genlMt NEARER-DIFF NEAR-DIFF) holds. Note that this predicate is notAssertible, since it must always be recomputed from the current state of the genlMt hierarchy.
label: Nearest Different Genl Mt
nearestDifferentGenlMt

comment: (relevantToVerbMapping REIFIABLETERM LEXICALWORD WORDSENSENUMBER). This predicate is used in work flow to alert someone doing OE or NL work on a particular verb sense to the fact that a fort (or many forts if there are many such assertions) are relevant or could be seen as relevant to representing the verb sense in question. For example, if I thought that the collection GivingSomething would most likely be involved in the semantic representation of the word #$Give-TheWord (with sense number 0 -- check the various denotations and semTrans assertions that a word is involved in to see what sense number corresponds to the sense to be represented), I would make this assertion (relevantToVerbMapping GivingSomething #$Give-TheWord 0).

Organizations can have different amounts of military power in different regions, e.g., (powerInRegion_Military RepublicOfSouthAfrica SubSaharanAfrica mediumAmountOf) but (powerInRegion_Military RepublicOfSouthAfrica ContinentOfEurope #$lowToVeryLowAmountOf).

powerInRegion-Military

comment:
A quaternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa -based relationship holds between a given argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned.

(interArgResultIsa FUNC N INDEP-ARG-COL DEP-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEP-ARG-COL appears as the Nth argument to FUNC, then (regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be) the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of DEP-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is an instance of INDEP-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 ... ARGN-1 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of DEP-ARG-COL.

For example, (interArgResultIsa RoundUpFn 1 RealNumber Integer) means that the rounding-up function RoundUpFn returns an integer whenever it is given a real number as its first (and only) argument.

Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArgResultIsa cannot be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but less flexible ternary interArg1ResultIsa et al.
label: Inter Arg Result Isa
interArgResultIsa

comment:
A RuleMacroPredicate. (relationExistsMost BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that most instances INST2 of COL2 are such that for some instance INST1 of COL1, (BINPRED INST1 INST2) holds. It is equivalent to the more complex form 
(most COL2 (SubcollectionOfWithRelationFromTypeFn COL2 BINPRED COL1)).
For example, (relationExistsMost owns Millionaire Mansion) means that most mansions are owned by millionaires. See also relationInstanceMost.
label: Relation Exists Most
relationExistsMost
